<FIRST>u w AM-MedicareSurtax     07-17 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare Surtax,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Would Accept Higher Payroll Levy WIth Same Tax
Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is willing to accept an
increase in the wage ceiling on which the hospitalization part of
Social Security taxes is levied _ a way to raise taxes with raising
tax rates, a congressional source said Monday night.
   The extra revenue would be aimed at easing, but not completely
eliminating, the income surtax on elderly Americans with high
incomes that finances catastrophic health insurance coverage for
Medicare recipients.
   In a closed session with the House Ways and Means Committee,
administration tax experts said one option in a package of changes
proposed by Rep. Fortney H. Pete Stark, D-Calif., chairman of the
committe's health subcommittee, would be ``generally acceptable,''
according to this source, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified.
   That option would increase the wage base on which the 2.9 percent
payroll tax for Medicare coverage is levied from $50,700 to $60,000
in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, and make state and local
government employees subject to the tax for the first time. No
Medicare tax is paid on income earned over the ceiling.
   The tax is split by employer and employee, each paying half or
1.45 percent.
   Someone making less than $50,700 would see no increase in the
Medicare portion of the Social Security tax paid. Someone making
$60,000 or more would pay $269.70 a year more.
   Stark's package included an alternative: leave state and local
government employees out and raise the ceiling to $90,000. The
administration does not favor this, the source said.
   The surtax _ 15 percent of the underlying tax liability _ has
prompted many protests to Congress, especially from people who have
arranged duplicating private insurance coverage. It can range up to
$800 for about 5 percent of the 33 million people eligible for
Medicare.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee and a major architect of the catastrophic health insurance
program that took effect in January 1988, had been backing a
reduction in the surtax, with no reduction in benefits, on the
grounds that it was too heavy and would build unneeded surpluses of
$2 billion to $4 billion in a few years in the trust fund for
catastrophic coverage.
   But on July 12, Bentsen said new figures from the Congressional
Budget Office showed there would be no surpluses after all. That set
off informal discussions on Capitol Hill and with the administration
on some other way to ease the surtax burden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
