<FIRST>u i AM-Gander-Crash     07-17 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gander-Crash,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review Says Gander Crash Probe Was Sufficient</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judicial review of the Canadian Aviation Safety
Board investigation into the 1985 crash that killed 256 Americans at
Gander, Newfoundland, has found no need for more public inquiry, a
newspaper said Tuesday.
   Sources at the safety board and Department of Transport said the
review, ordered in March by Transport Minister Benoit Bouchard,
generally exonerates the board's professional staff investigators,
the Toronto Globe and Mail reported.
   The investigators found that a thin layer of ice reduced the
lifting capacity of the wings of the Arrow Air jet, causing it to
crash on takeoff on Dec. 12, 1985.
   The newspaper said the review was written by Justice Willard
Estey, a former Supreme Court of Canada judge, and is due to be
released Friday.
   It quoted sources as saying the report gives no credence to the
bomb theory that has been widely promoted by four dissenting members
of the nine-member board, the newspaper says.
   The dissenters had accused the board's investigators of
withholding evidence. They suggested a coverup by Canadian and U.S.
agencies had sought to hide what they argued was a terrorist attack
on the aging DC-8, which was ferrying U.S. troops home for Christmas
after a peacekeeping tour in the Middle East.
   The Globe and Mail quoted sources as saying Estey rejected the
dissenters' allegations as being gossip and innuendo, and that he
concluded no useful purpose would be served by a public inquiry.
   No evidence of a bomb has ever been presented, although the
dissenters say its absence demonstrates the wide-ranging nature of
the coverup.
   Safety board chairman Ken Thorneycraft refused Monday to discuss
Estey's review. He said he was unaware of its findings, but he added
he had always been confident that any independent assessment of the
agency's investigation would conclude it had been conducted
thoroughly and had reached reasonable conclusions.
   ``There are always some things that could have been done
better,'' Thorneycraft said. ``But it will be nice when it (Estey's
report) does come out.''
   Critics of the icing finding, most recently the U.S. Airline
Pilots Association, have accused the board of fabricating evidence
in an effort to blame the pilots of the plane. Both pilots, six
other crew members and all 248 U.S. servicemen on board the jet died
in the Dec. 12, 1985, crash _ the worst ever in Canada.
   The Globe and Mail also reported that Les Filotas, one of the
dissenters who wrote a minority report rejecting the icing finding,
tried to get in touch with Estey during his review.
   It said Filotas sent a five-page letter to Estey in which he
postulated that Arrow Air may have been involved in
``arms-for-hostages exchanges conducted secretly on behalf of highly
placed individuals in the American administration (and that) if so,
there would have been strong motivation for attempts to confound
aspects of the investigation.''
   The letter, obtained through the Access to Information Act,
suggests the unsubstantiated link could also have been a motive for
targeting Air Arrow for a terrorist attack, the paper said.
   It said Estey returned the letter, dated April 2, unread to
Filotas.
   Estey, due to return from vacation Thursday, is expected to be
present at the news conference at which his report will be formally
released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
