<FIRST>r p PM-Pepper'sSeat     07-17 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepper's Seat,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0444 to fix cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Republicans Expected to Win Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Cuban-born women lead the crowded field of
candidates to succeed the late U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper, in an
election that is revealing how the district has changed since Pepper
began representing it in 1962.
   The Republican Party, enjoying an unprecedented 10-8 majority in
Florida's congressional delegation, wants to make it 11-8 by winning
the Aug. 29 special election. Democrats believe a victory could
start a comeback and boost their chances of unseating Republican
Gov. Bob Martinez in 1990.
   Pepper was an old-style liberal who won 14 terms in the House
district by emphasizing social programs benefitting the elderly, for
many years the dominant group in his electorate.
   While the district still includes many older people, half the
residents now are Hispanics, mostly refugees from Castro's Cuba and
their offspring. Pepper catered to their strong anti-communist
feelings while maintaining his liberal social program.
   Pepper died May 30 at age 88, and no single Democrat has emerged
from the balkanized local party to replace him. Two of the early
Democratic front-runners have dropped from the race.
   If current polls hold true, state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a
conservative Republican, would win the seat that includes most of
Miami and surrounding communities to become the first Cuban-American
in Congress.
   Both parties are holding primaries Aug. 1, with runoffs, if
necessary, on Aug. 15.
   ``We're very confident about the campaign,'' Ros-Lehtinen last
week. ``We're going to have a good solid victory in the primary and
we think the primary's going to be a very bitter one for the
Democrats.''
   Businessman Carlos Perez, a millionaire businessman and
fund-raiser for former National Security Council adviser Oliver
North, is her strongest rival. The field also includes insurance
broker David Fleischer and former North Miami Mayor John Stembridge.
   Ros-Lehtinen is starting the campaign with a $200,000 war chest
that she expects to grow to at least $650,000. Her television
commercials, the campaign's first, will begin airing this week.
   Miami City Commissioner Rosario Kennedy, also Cuban-born, is the
early favorite for the Democratic nomination, with strong labor
backing.
   Jo Ann Pepper, the late congressman's niece and a 17-year federal
probation officer, is running against Kennedy with a strong
law-and-order campaign that promises SWAT teams patrolling the
streets.
   Other Democratic candidates include former Florida Bar
Association president Gerald Richman, businessman Bernard Anscher,
black intellectual Marvin Dunn, realtor Sonny Wright, and Eastern
Airlines pilot John Paul Rosser.
   Nearly as notable as the Democrats who are running are those who
aren't.
   State Sen. Jack Gordon, a liberal from Miami Beach who was the
early leader when he announced his candidacy June 13, dropped out
the same week after claiming that comments by Republican National
Committee Chairman Lee Atwater were fueling ethnic tensions. Atwater
had said it was time to elect a Cuban-American to Congress.
   Hialeah Mayor Raul Martinez, another strong runner in the early
going, became angered by the party's inability to reduce the field.
He left, saying he would bypass the ``big mess.''
   Other dropouts include State Sen. Carrie Meek, Cuban-born banker
Raul Masvidal, and sports attorney Jeffrey Allen, who was forced to
leave the race when it was disclosed he is a registered Republican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
