<FIRST>r w PM-BlackCatholics     07-17 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended Priest Plans Second Church, School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest suspended for forming
the unauthorized African-American Catholic Congregation is
considering starting a second church as well as a school, day care
center and housing for the homeless.
   The Rev. George A. Stallings Jr. was quoted in The Washington
Post today as saying the new church would be called the Umoja Temple.
   He said he is looking for a 25-acre site where he can build a
permanent facility for his new African-American church, known as the
Imani Temple.
   Stallings told the Post he plans to build a school, day care
center, administrative offices, temporary housing for the homeless
and permanent housing for senior citizens on the site.
   On Sunday, about 2,500 people attended services at the Imani
Temple, which Stallings contends is a brand of Catholicism that
better serves blacks.
   After the first services on July 2, Stallings was suspended by
the Roman Catholic archdiocese of Washington from leading mass or
performing Catholic sacraments.
   Stallings accuses the church of failing to address the needs of
its black parishioners. He wants to form an African-American
Catholic rite, which he says would still be part of the Catholic
church.
   Last week, 13 black Catholic bishops asked Stallings to abandon
his movement, saying they deplored his separation ``from the unity
of the church.''
   But Stallings told his congregation Sunday that he is following
God's direction, ``and God didn't tell me what bishop I should be
listening to.''
</TEXT>
