<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-17 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASSVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mirror, mirror on the wall, who's the most
same of them all?
   At the 25th Twin-O-Rama on Sunday in the southwestern Wisconsin
community, judges declared Darrell and Dennis Carlson as the most
identical of dozens of adult identical twins.
   ``We're both professional clowns. We both retired from the
telephone company after 31 years of service. We both had 23-year-old
sons. We both drive Ford Econoline vans,'' said Darrell Carlson, 51.
``Our interests are so much alike it's almost scary.''
   They beat out Lori and Lisa Erschenbarr, who used an elaborate
ruse. One sister injured an ankle, so her twin put on an identical
bandage and walked with an identical pair of crutches.
   The 24-year-old sisters, who have won the most-identical twins
prize five times, wore matching lavender blouses and skirts, the
same flowers in their hair and matching bandages on their left
ankles. Both carried a pair of aluminum crutches.
   About 250 pairs of identical twins competed in 14 different
categories, including babies, adults and twins who look the least
alike.
   In some cases, judges counted freckles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GERING, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jim Exon calls himself a ``soup nut,''
but a chili cook-off was a little out of his league.
   Exon said he makes a mean vegetable beef soup, but his debut as
chief judge at Saturday's Oregon Trail Days' chili cook-off had his
head spinning because of complex judging instructions and strict
guidelines.
   ``I'm not used to things this complicated. This is much more
complicated than the Strategic Defense Initiative or the B-2
Bomber,'' said Exon, a Democratic member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee.
   ``Our national defense is simple compared to this,'' he said.
   The cook-off attracted cooks from as far away as Missouri and
Texas.
</TEXT>
