<HEAD>Innocent Woman Killed in Gunfight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pregnant Washington woman sitting on her
front porch is dead after being struck by a stray bullet from what
police believe was a drug-related gunfight.
   Rhonda Anthony, 34, was killed about 2:30 a.m. Sunday as she sat
with her husband, Willy, in front of their house in the southeast
section of the city, police said.
   Charles Alton, 24, was charged with second-degree murder in
Anthony's death, according to authorities.
   Anthony was shot during a shootout between Alton and another man
at a nearby corner that has been the scene of drug-related violence
in recent weeks, police said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Turner's SuperStation to Broadcast Pro-Choice Video</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion rights advocates gain a platform on
national television this week when supporter Ted Turner broadcasts
their pro-choice video on his SuperStation TBS.
   Turner last week called abortion foes ``idiots'' and ``Bozos,''
raising the ire of pro-lifers and drawing attention to the coming
broadcast.
   ``Abortion: For Survival,'' produced for the Fund for the
Feminist Majority, is a half-hour program that depicts abortion as
an issue of public health, family planning, population control and
women's rights. It focuses on the effect of U.S. abortion policies
on American women and women in other countries.
   The program will be aired on Turner's TBS channel Thursday night,
and repeated Saturday afternoon and Sunday morning. It will be
followed by a one-hour studio debate between two pro-choice
activists and two abortion foes moderated by journalist Martin
Agronsky.
   Jennifer Cole, a spokeswoman for the National Right to Life
Committee, called Turner's decision to air the pro-choice program
but not a pro-life film ``very irresponsible journalism.''
   Right-to-life groups want Turner to balance his broadcast by
showing ``Eclipse of Reason,'' a film showing the results of a
24-week abortion.
   That film and its precursor, the better known ``Silent Scream,''
which uses a sonogram to show a fetus being aborted, have been aired
by local and regional cable TV systems in various parts of the
country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Import Quotas Now Have Little Impact, GAO Says</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional research agency says the U.S.
steel industry has returned to ``normal levels of profitability''
and ending import quotas in place the past five years would have
little overall impact.
   ``The effect of the quotas has declined substantially and the
vast majority of them are now going unfilled,'' the General
Accounting Office said in a report released Sunday. ``While
expiration of the quotas might effect the market for a few
individual steel products ... it would likely have little impact on
the market as a whole.''
   Twenty separate quota agreements covering steel imports from 29
countries are due to expire Sept. 30. President Bush is expected to
announce a new steel policy soon after he returns from the Paris
economic summit.
   Senators from states with agricultural and other major exports
have been campaigning against the quotas. Those from steel-producing
states have been urging a five-year extension. The White House is
reportedly weighing proposed two- and four-year extensions.
   The GAO report said the major cause of the industry's plight when
the quotas were adopted in 1985 was the recession earlier in the
decade, a situation made worse by a surge in imports and the soaring
value of the dollar.
</TEXT>
