<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     07-17 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Shoots Higher; Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Currency traders, relieved from the anxiety of
possible interest rate hikes in the United States, actively bought
dollars today, sending the currency sharply higher against the
Japanese yen.
   Stock prices declined on the Tokyo Stock Exchange as volatile
interest rates and uncertainties in Japanese politics before this
weekend's parliamentary election sidelined many investors, dealers
said.
   The dollar closed at 141.53 yen, up 2.03 yen from last Friday's
close of 139.50 yen. It opened at 140.85 yen and moved in a range of
140.85-141.55 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which fell 56.39 points on Friday, shed another 118.55
points, or 0.35 percent, to close at 33,456.22.
   Traders said the dollar's strength followed its upward trend in
New York on Friday, but the renewed strength of the U.S. currency
was largely because of economic indicators released in Washington on
Friday.
   ``Players are buying back the dollar because last weekend's
economic indicators somewhat relieved the market from worrying that
U.S. interest rates would go down,'' said a dealer at a major
commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Friday the nation's retail
sales fell 0.4 percent in June, while the Labor Department said its
producer price index of finished goods dropped 0.1 percent last
month.
   Another dealer said the fact that the leaders of seven major
democracies at the economic summit in Paris did not discuss currency
issues also motivated dollar-buying.
   ``It was as if saying they approved the current level of exchange
rates,'' said the dealer, also speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Securities dealers said uncertainties over the political
situation in Japan sidelined many investors.
   ``With this little trading, there is not much we can do about it
except wait for investors to come back,'' said Ichitaro Watanabe, a
dealer at Nikko Securities Co.
   Volume traded on the first section of the Tokyo exchange was
estimated at 260 million shares.
   Recent media polls show public support for Japan's governing
Liberal Democratic Party has fallen behind the Japan Socialist
Party, the second largest party. An election for half of the 252
seats in the Japanese parliament's upper house is scheduled Sunday.
   ``When an election, in which the ruling party is expected to lose
badly, is less than a week away, it's hard to buy stocks,'' said
another dealer at Nikko, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
