<HEAD>Bomb Explodes in Mecca</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with sources saying blast caused
by bomb; Picks up 4th, `Two bomb ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in the holy Moslem
city of Mecca early today, but authorities reported no casualties or
damage.
   An unnamed official, in a statement carried by the official
Riyadh Radio, said the blast occurred after 1 a.m. in an uninhabited
area on Mount Qubais, near the Grand Mosque.
   The official described the explosion as ``small' and said
security authorities were investigating the incident.
   He did not give other details, but other sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the blast was caused by a bomb.
   Two bomb blasts a week ago killed a Pakistani pilgrim and wounded
16 other worshippers at the height of the pilgrimage season. One
bombs went off on a road leading to the Grand Mosque, the other near
an overpass.
   Both explosions last week occurred during the night, while
pilgrims still were awake, offering prayers or visiting the Kaaba,
the holy shrine within the Grand Mosque in Mecca, birthplace of the
Prophet Mohammed, founder of Islam.
   Some 2 million Moslems were gathered in Mecca for this year's
pilgrimage, which culminated Thursday with Eid al-Adha, or the Feast
of Sacrifice.
   Hundreds of thousands of pilgrims were still in the holy city
today, when the latest explosion occurred, awaiting return flights
home.
</TEXT>
