<FIRST>r p PM-WrightSeat     07-17 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Seat,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Candidates Vying For Wright's House Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARNIE STAPLETON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats who have only recently gotten
over the shock of the resignation of House Speaker Jim Wright are
fighting to keep the congressional seat he held for more than 34
years.
   Three Republicans and one Libertarian are among the eight
candidates on the ballot for the Aug. 12 special election to fill
the House seat Wright first was elected to in 1955. No primaries
will be held.
   ``We're taking the attitude this is a new campaign,'' said David
Rucker, a spokesman for Republican candidate Laraine Bethke. ``As
Republicans, we think the playing field is very level.''
   The district that includes most of Fort Worth long has been a
Democratic stronghold, but Republicans have fared well in recent
elections. Last week, eight Democratic judges, citing a changing
political climate, defected to the Republican Party.
   Wright stepped down as speaker and resigned his House seat last
month amid an ethics investigation that turned up 69 instances of
alleged rules violations.
   The longtime congressman's popularity remained high in his
district even after he announced his resignation May 31, and all of
the candidates have been careful not to criticize Wright.
   Dennis Sheehan, the Tarrant County Democratic Party chairman,
says the Democrats are the only contenders because ``the voters of
District 12 don't like the way the Republican Party railroaded Jim
Wright out of office.''
   Republican leaders disagree.
   ``It was the Democrats who threw Jim Wright out of Congress,''
said Steve Hollern, the GOP county chief. ``If they had been willing
to put their neck on the line to save him, they could have kept him,
but the Democratic Congress was not willing to do that.''
   The special election is to fill the rest of Wright's term, ending
in January 1991. A runoff is expected in late August or September
because no candidate should win 50 percent of the vote.
   Wright and both party chairmen have declined to endorse a
candidate.
   Among the Democrats are three Fort Worth attorneys, George
Petrovich, Jim Lane and Pete Geren.
   Lane was endorsed by the Tarrant County Central Labor Council
AFL-CIO, which represents about 28,000 workers.
   Geren, a former aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, has been endorsed by
the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee and enjoys the
backing of Martin Frost, the senior U.S. congressman from North
Texas.
   The other Democrat is Bill Turner, who owns a fence store.
   Sheehan said none of the Democrats are carbon copies of Wright.
   ``It's impossible for anyone to step into his shoes. They'll have
to establish their own credentials,'' Sheehan said.
   Republican candidate Dr. Bob Lanier, a physician whose syndicated
television show on health matters is broadcast in 40 markets, has
been endorsed by U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm and Texas Gov. Bill Clements.
   In addition to Lanier and Ms. Bethke, a former aide to U.S. Rep.
Dick Armey, private investigator Jim Hunter is running as a
Republican.
   Robert Buckingham Jr., manager of an oil-change garage, has filed
as a Libertarian candidate.
   ``The shock of the events involving Wright has worn off,'' said
Sheehan. ``Voters are now focusing on the reality that somebody must
go to Congress to represent this district, and they want somebody
who will work as hard for the district as Wright did for 34 years.''
</TEXT>
