<HEAD>Black Doctors Called On To Fight Diseases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan, whose nomination as
Health and Human Services secretary was opposed by anti-abortion
activists, has said he supports the recent Supreme Court ruling that
limits the operation.
   Sullivan spoke Saturday to the annual conference of the
predominantly black National Medical Association, of which he is a
member.
   He did not mention the Supreme Court decision allowing states to
restrict abortion in his speech, which focused on the growing costs
of Medicare, but told reporters afterwards that he ``feels very
good'' about the ruling.
   Sullivan said of the ruling, ``by returning this question to the
states for their action, that is the position we wanted.''
   The National Medical Association previously has endorsed Roe vs.
Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion. The group
is expected to reaffirm its support of Roe vs. Wade later this week.
   Sullivan, the only black Cabinet member, stirred concern among
anti-abortionists in then-President-elect Bush's camp last December
for appearing to support women's right to choose abortion.
   The leader of the physicians' group, Dr. Frank Staggers, called
for increased attention to poverty health care, to control ailments
like AIDS and drug addiction that he said threatened to overpower
black communities.
   ``Why should we look at problems which are esoteric when we have
things that are disproportionately affecting blacks?'' he said.
   At least 5,000 physicians were attending the six-day conference
that began Friday.
