<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 0711EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Solzhenitsyn     07-17 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Solzhenitsyn,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solzhenitsyn Says Critics Lie About Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Alexander Solzhenitsyn, in his
first major American interview in 10 years, says he won't return to
his homeland until his new epic is available in every bookstore in
the Soviet Union.
   Since leaving the Soviet Union and arriving in Cavendish, Vt.,
with his family in 1976, Solzhenitsyn has written more than 5,000
printed pages in Russian of an epic, called ``The Red Wheel,''
covering the period surrounding the Russian Revolution of 1917.
   One of the novels of the series, ``August 1914,'' is being
published in English this week by Farrar, Straus &amp; Giroux.
   He said in the July 24 edition of Time magazine that to return
home before ``The Red Wheel'' is available to Soviet citizens would
make him ``sort of mute.'' Time said he is now preparing the final
pages of the work.
   ``No one would know where I stood. I would have expressed
nothing. Once people read it, then we can talk,'' he said.
   But he noted that the major stumbling block to going home is the
pending charge of treason against him for his writings.
   On another topic, Solzhenitsyn said he was amazed when people
give him and his books labels such as anti-Semitic, chauvinistic,
xenophobic and nationalistic.
   ``It is quite extraordinary the extent to which I have been lied
about,'' he said. ``Some people distort things consciously, others
just don't take the trouble to check their sources,'' he said. ``It
is remarkable, and it makes me ashamed of journalists. No one ever
gives any quotes.''
   The 70-year-old Solzhenitsyn, who won the Nobel Prize for
literature in 1970, said public opinion about him is varied in
Europe, but monolithic in the Soviet Union and United States.
   ``In the Soviet Union I can understand it. It is due to the
Politburo,'' he said. ``But in the U.S. fashion is very important.
If the winds of fashion are blowing in one direction, everybody
writes one way and with perfect unanimity. It is perfectly
extraordinary.''
   He said he has chosen to remain silent about the major changes in
the Soviet Union and the Communist world because his focus has been
on his work.
   ``Was I going to interrupt my work and start acting as a
political commentator? I didn't want to do that. I had to finish my
work. I am over 70 years old, and age is pressing on me.''
</TEXT>
