<FIRST>r a PM-StegerExpedition     07-17 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steger Expedition,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trans-Antarctica Team Begins Journey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sled dogs and a Soviet transport plane
seemed reluctant to take off, but Minnesota adventurer Will Steger
and a team of international explorers left for the first
trans-Antarctica dogsled trek.
   Steger and his five teammates from five countries, who hope to
begin the seven-month, 4,000-mile trek by Aug. 1, gave a last round
of hugs to well-wishers before departing Minneapolis-St. Paul
International Airport at 9:30 p.m. Sunday with 13,000 pounds of gear.
   Earlier Sunday, Soviet technicians repaired a faulty engine on
the four-engine cargo plane, a problem with a fuel flow device that
on Saturday threatened to ground the expedition for two days.
   The team's 42 sled dogs were the last cargo to be loaded,
sometimes with a struggle.
   The group plans several stops in Latin America before beginning
their trip across the bottom of the world. The team hopes the
grueling journey will rivet attention on international cooperation,
as well as the continent's stark fragility.
   ``Our mission is hope, hope in the strength and power of
international cooperation,'' Steger said at a news conference at the
College of St. Catherine.
   At the afternoon ceremony, Girl Scouts used scissors to slice
apart a painted tarp depicting the crew members' home countries _
Britain, Japan, China, France, the Soviet Union and the United
States _ and asked them to reassemble the mural at the end of their
expedition.
   At the same time, Steger, 44, wants to pursue a dream he says has
lurked inside him for years: to conquer the world's last untamed
frontier. He calls the Antarctica traverse ``the last of the big
firsts.''
   Others have crossed Antarctica on snowmobiles and giant snow
tractors, but this will be the first unmechanized attempt.
   The venture has also drawn lots of publicity and money, with
corporations in the United States and France contributing nearly $10
million. A $3.5 million aluminum boat will serve as a floating
embassy and communications base.
   The team members are Steger, co-leader Jean-Louis Etienne of
France, Soviet scientist Victor Boyarsky, Englishman Geoff Somers,
Keizo Funatsu of Japan, and Qin Dahe of China.
   Oceanographers Mustafa Omar Moammar and Ibrahim Abdulhamid Alam
of Saudi Arabia will travel with the team for a week on the
continent's interior, then will spend the second half of the
seven-month journey conducting experiments form the expedition's
ship.
   The trip south is to include stops in Havana; Lima, Peru; and
Buenos Aires, Argentina.
   Finally, from the tiny Argentine city of Rio Grande, the crew
will wait for the proper weather to fly to King George Island near
the tip of the Antarctic peninsula, where the Chinese will be
hosting the trek's launch at the Great Wall research base. The
arbitrary point of Seal Nunataks was chosen as the trek's launching
pad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
