<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 0804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DolphinProject     07-17 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dolphin Project,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Volunteers Spot 1,100 Dolphins off Georgia Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 200 volunteers were out to count
dolphins, but the big marine mammals seemed to be as interested in
the people as the humans were in them.
   ``We had one come up so close to the boat I couldn't photograph
him with the telephoto,'' said Lisa E. Bowen of Tallahassee, Fla.
``He came right up, and looked at me, but I couldn't get him on
film.''
   She was among volunteers in 30 boats who spent the weekend
searching for Atlantic bottlenose dolphins along a 25-mile stretch
of Georgia coast, from the South Carolina line to St. Catherines
Island.
   They're trying to help scientists see if the population recovers
from an outbreak of a still-unidentified disease that killed about
half the dolphin population off the eastern United States in 1987
and 1988.
   The volunteers reported 1,100 sightings, but many animals may
have been counted more than once. The weekend effort was the first
of 40 such surveys planned over 10 years by a conservation group,
The Dolphin Project.
   Volunteers try to photograph each animal they see and hope to
build a catalogue to identify individuals by coloring and markings
on their dorsal fins.
   ``I know of no effort of this magnitude that has ever been done
anywhere,'' said Charles Potter, collections manager for the
Smithsonian Institution, a dolphin expert who has worked with the
project.
   ``It's outstanding,'' he said. ``The federal government could
never get this many people out there observing. It just doesn't have
the resources.''
   The project will help monitor part of the population's recovery.
   ``Today, we had reports of dolphins coming up to boats, so close
people could touch them,'' said Beau Cutts, president of the
conservation group, which has headquarters in Marietta.
   ``These are wild dolphins. They seem to exhibit as much interest
in men as we do in the Atlantic bottlenose dolphin.''
   The first survey was from 5 miles offshore to 8 miles inland up
creeks and in marshes.
   Some boats found themselves amid dolphins than they could record
on the written reports.
</TEXT>
