<FIRST>r a PM-BlackRhinos 1stLd-Writethru a0500 07-17 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Rhinos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rancher and Zookeepers Welcome Rhino Shipment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS first 2 grafs to recast.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shipment of 10 endangered black rhinos
arrived special delivery from Africa aboard a jumbo jet, doubling
the population of rhinoceroses in the United States.
   The one-ton beasts landed Sunday at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport in the rear of a Boeing 747. The animals are
destined for zoos and ranches, where they will be bred as part of an
international conservation program.
   One of the females is being taken to La Coma Ranch near McAllen,
owned by Calvin Bentsen, where it will join 400 other exotic
animals, including a male black rhino named Macho.
   ``I told him about it yesterday, and he got all excited,'' joked
Bentsen, 63, a cousin of U.S. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   One of the rhinos broke a horn during the trip from Harare by way
of Frankfurt, West Germany. Several became dehydrated and were
doused with water inside a cargo terminal before being examined and
sprayed with an insecticide to kill any disease-carrying ticks.
   ``They're a little tired,'' said veterinarian Sherri Huntress of
the Dallas Zoo, which is receiving a pair of the animals.
   Veterinarians were most concerned about the condition of a
pregnant rhino, which apparently experienced only normal stress, zoo
officials said.
   In addition to Bentsen and the Dallas Zoo, the Fort Worth and
Milwaukee zoos and the Lee Bass ranch in southern Texas are each
getting a pair of rhinos, and San Diego's zoo is getting one.
   Habitat destruction and poaching have put the animal on the verge
of extinction. Their horns sometimes sell for as much as $4,500
apiece, desired as dagger handles and in medicinal potions.
   Before the shipment, only eight black rhinos were in the United
States.
   There are believed to be fewer than 3,000 southern black rhinos
in the wild. In 1970, there were more than 60,000 inhabiting the
grasslands, marshes and forests of Africa.
   Bentsen said while in 1960 he shot a black rhino in Kenya, he
wouldn't do it now.
   ``A true hunter would never shoot an endangered animal,'' Bentsen
said.
</TEXT>
