<FIRST>r a PM-Summit-Texas 1stLd-Writethru a0452 07-17 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Texas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Officials Hope Bush Will Bring Summit Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs. Inserts 1 new graf after graf 5, bgng ``Bush, born, to add LBJ
background; picks up 6th pvs, bgng ``Back in</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas officials, responding to President
Bush's hint the next economic summit could be held in his adopted
state, describe the prospect in glowing terms.
   ``Texas is a state of international importance and for the
president to bring the leaders of the free world to his home state
is a brilliant idea,'' Gov. Bill Clements' spokesman, Reggie Bashur,
said Sunday.
   Bush, asked Sunday in Paris if he might bring the leaders of the
seven richest democracies to Texas, said: ``That's a distinct
possibility.'' He quickly added, ``However, it's too early. No
decision has been made.''
   The president, speaking to reporters at the end of the 15th
economic summit, said: ``The fact that (Secretary of State) Jim
Baker is from Houston, and I'm from Houston, and (Commerce
Secretary) Bob Mosbacher is from Texas should have nothing to do
with where the next summit's going to be, and there has been no
decision.''
   Bush, born and raised in New England, moved to Texas after World
War II and entered the oil business. He owns a house in
Kennebunkport, Maine, and stays in a hotel when in Houston. But he
maintains Houston as his voting residence.
   Another president from Texas, Lyndon B. Johnson, used to delight
in showing off his LBJ Ranch to foreign visitors in the 1960s, but
never held any formal summits in the state.
   Back in the Lone Star state, officials already are jostling for
the site.
   ``I think that's a great idea,'' said Texas House Speaker Gib
Lewis, noting his hometown of Fort Worth ``would be a super city''
for the summit.
   The hints Bush dropped about the roots he shares with Baker and
Mosbacher were not lost on Houston officials.
   Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby put a plug in for his hometown. ``There's no
better place than Houston to discuss economic initiatives. It's a
great city and President Bush's hometown.''
   Mayor Kathy Whitmire said she had already been thinking about the
summit.
   ``We had considered that he (Bush) will be hosting the economic
summit and we were hoping that he would consider bringing the summit
to his hometown ... since Houston is such a major international city
and since we are involved in a strong economic recovery now,'' Mrs.
Whitmire said.
   She said the main benefit to the city would be the international
exposure.
   ``I am going to be pursuing this issue with Secretary Mosbacher
and Secretary Baker because I think they share my view that Houston
would be a natural.''
   Houston Chamber of Commerce President Eileen Crowley said she
knew of no organized effort to attract the international economic
summit to Houston, but added that Bush may have provided all the
incentive the city needed Sunday.
   ``Given an opening like that, let's not let the opportunity go
by,'' she said. ``I'm sure we'll be talking about it.''
</TEXT>
