<FIRST>r i PM-Burma     07-17 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0521 to fix cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Members Arrested For Rangoon Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces have arrested three members
of the main opposition party for a recent bombing at a government
oil refinery that killed three people, the chief of military
intelligence said today.
   Authorities said three people were killed and two others wounded
when a box in a package exploded at the Syriam refinery on the
northern bank of the Rangoon River on July 7.
   ``Three National League for Democracy youths have admitted their
responsibility for the blast at Syriam,'' intelligence chief Brig.
Gen. Khin Nyunt told a news conference.
   Khin Nyunt said he was convinced the Syriam bombing was connected
to a bomb explosion at Rangoon's City Hall on July 10. The
government-run Radio Rangoon said three people were killed in that
attack.
   Khin Nyunt said no arrests have been made for that bombing.
   The National League for Democracy is the largest and most popular
opposition group to emerge from a national uprising for democracy
which the army brutally crushed last year.
   The general said the youths _ identified as Than Zaw, Moe Kyaw
Thiu and Nyi Nyi U _ confessed to the refinery bombing. At the news
conference, he showed what he said were their photographs and party
identity cards.
   The bomb caused no damage to the refinery, one of only two in the
country.
   He identified the ``mastermind'' of the bombing as Moe Thiha, an
organizer for the National League for Democracy, and said he
remained at large.
   He charged that Moe Thiha received explosives training from the
rebel Karen National Union, an ethnic minority group battling for
greater autonomy from the government.
   Apparently referring to Aung San Suu Kyi, the general secretary
of the opposition party, Khin Nyunt said a party leader had made
``indirect suggestions that the military is responsible for the
recent bombings (and) insinuations that the military was after her
life.
   ``In fact we are worried that she might fall and hurt her toe
even, because we will be blamed for any harm to her,'' he said.
   ``Now it is obvious who is behind the recent bombing and plans to
disrupt law and order in the country,'' he added.
   Authorities have banned public demonstrations under martial law
declared since the army cracked down on a huge nationwide movement
for democracy in September.
   Khin Nyunt said restrictions on expression and movement of the
political parties would be lifted ``step by step depending on
security conditions.''
   An election would definitely be held in May and ``full freedom
will be given for the final party campaigns,'' he said.
   The National League has criticized the government's refusal to
talk with opposition groups and expressed doubts that the military
would hand over power.

</TEXT>
