<FIRST>u a PM-Apollo-20YearsAgo     07-17 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apollo-20 Years Ago,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Happened 20 Years Ago On Historic Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Apollo Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of what occurred
exactly 20 years ago today during the Apollo 11 moon flight:
   One day after launch, Apollo 11 is streaking outward from Earth
toward the moon, which is still more than 100,000 miles ahead.
   At 12:17 p.m. EDT, the astronauts fire the rocket engine on
Columbia, their command and service module, for three seconds, just
long enough to put the craft precisely on target for the moon.
   Later, astronauts Neil Armstrong, Edwin E. ``Buzz'' Aldrin Jr.
and Michael Collins beam a 36-minute television show to Mission
Control in Houston. They show a view of the Earth, now 128,000 miles
behind them, and then give a tour of their small space cabin.
   At 9:42 p.m. EDT, Mission Control bids the crew goodnight.
</TEXT>
