<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HolocaustMemorial     07-17 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holocaust Memorial,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contract Awarded for Construction of Holocaust Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council announced
today it has awarded a $53.3 million contract for construction of a
museum on the National Mall.
   Construction of the Holocaust Memorial Museum 400 yards from the
Washington Monument will begin next week, with completion expected
in three years. The contract was awarded to Blake Construction Co.
Inc. of Washington.
   The five-story, 250,000-square-foot limestone and brick building
will be constructed with private funds. Organizers say they hope to
raise $147 million to build and equip the museum, prepare permanent
exhibits and establish an endowment. To date, about $70 million has
been raised, officials said.
   ``With this action, the council is taking a significant and
irreversible step toward a noble and vital goal _ the establishment
of a national museum in the nation's capital to tell the story of
the six million Jews killed in the Holocaust and the millions of
other victims of Nazism,'' said Harvey M. Myerhoff, the council
chairman.
   The council was established in 1980 by Congress.
</TEXT>
