<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NBC-Controversy     07-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NBC-Controversy,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Executives Urge Strong Stand Against `New McCarthyism'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top NBC executives promised to withstand
pressure from self-appointed TV censors who oppose controversial
programs and mount campaigns aimed at advertisers with tactics one
called ``new McCarthyism.''
   Special-interest groups, many led by fundamentalist Christian
ministers, that urge sponsors to avoid programs considered
objectionable, present a significant worry to the network, NBC
Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff told television reporters
this weekend.
   ``What you become concerned about is a sort of new McCarthyism
where certain parties are out there speaking for what I think is a
minority viewpoint in terms of what is acceptable network fare,''
Tartikoff said.
   Robert Wright, NBC president and chief executive officer, said
the network would be sensitive in its programming decisions during
the coming season, but would not shy away from hot topics.
   ``Our position is we will continue to look for and develop
controversial issues,'' Wright said.
   Special-interest groups campaigned, with some success, against
NBC's ``Nightingales,'' ``Saturday Night Live'' and ``Roe vs.
Wade,'' among other shows.
   NBC was unable to sell all available advertising spots for the
critically acclaimed, but highly controversial, movie-of-the-week
``Roe vs. Wade'' because of its focus on abortion rights.
   ``The nervousness is not on our part,'' Tartikoff said. ``It's on
the part of the advertisers. They're caving incredibly quickly.''
   In response to advertiser defections, NBC added 10 staff members
to its standards department. Tartikoff said the network also was
conducting a study to examine whether critical special-interest
groups truly represent a change in the majority of viewers' values.
   Tartikoff did not admit that the series ``Nightingales'' was
canceled because of interest-group pressure. The series, about a
group of student nurses who spend a lot of time in sexy lingerie or
chasing doctors, was criticized by real nurses. Their write-in
campaign caused some sponsors to withdraw their commercials.
   ``I don't think there was anything up for contention on our fall
schedule that got eliminated because of these groups,'' he said,
while admitting that he was concerned about getting the new fall
schedule started without any problems.
   Wright said the network would pay special attention to
programming for the coming season, and that ``we will be a little
more reserved than we have been.''
   But Tartikoff seemed less willing to accommodate amateur critics.
   ``What I'm telling you is that there's a brush fire burning out
there, and I'm trying to put it out,'' he said. ``And I think if we
put it out, then we can go about our business.''
   Tartikoff's reference to McCarthyism linked critics' efforts to
the 1950s communist witch hunts staged by then-Sen. Joe McCarthy.
</TEXT>
