<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-17 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0524,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharon Calls For Arafat's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 10th graf pvs, `A 58-year-old ...' to CORRECT age to 61;
picks up 11th pvs, `He was...'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   KATZRIN, Israeli-Annexed Golan Heights (AP) _ Industry Minister
Ariel Sharon called on the government today to ``eliminate'' PLO
chief Yasser Arafat to end the Palestinian uprising and revive the
Middle East peace process.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, soldiers today blew up the homes of
two Palestinians suspected of fatally stabbing an Israeli building
contractor on Friday, the army said.
   Speaking to reporters in this small Israeli town on a strategic
plateau captured from Syria, Sharon renewed his demands for strong
steps to end the 19-month Palestinian uprising, which has claimed
the lives of 565 Palestinians and 36 Israelis.
   ``We have to stop using slogans, dishing out promises and handing
out tranquilizers. The time has come to deal with terror and
violence,'' Sharon said.
   ``I think we are in a war, it's a different kind of war but a
war,'' he said. ``The most important thing is to restore law and
order, to bring an end to terror and violence called the intefadeh
(Arabic for uprising).''
   Sharon, a member of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing
Likud bloc, said the government also must ``eliminate the heads of
the terrorist organizations, first of all, Arafat.''
   Unless this is done, he said, ``I do not see any real possibility
of arriving at peace or starting a peace process.''
   It was not Sharon's first threat against the chief of the
Palestine Liberation Organization. On Jan. 28, he said on Israel
radio ``there will be no peace as long as Arafat lives.''
   Sharon's tour of the Golan, annexed after its capture from Syria
in 1967, came as the Cabinet faced its toughest political crisis,
which Sharon prompted by proposing a list of hard-line amendments to
the government's peace initiative.
   A 61-year-old retired general, Sharon is also a former defense
minister who spearheaded Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon to rout
PLO guerrilla strongholds from that country.
   He was forced out of the post in 1983 when an Israeli inquiry
commission found him indirectly responsible for the slayings of
hundreds of Palestinians by Israeli-backed forces in the Sabra and
Chattilla refugee camps in Beirut.
   But recently Sharon has made a comeback. His most notable gain
came July 5 when he forced Shamir to accept as Likud policy a list
of preconditions to the prime minister's peace initiative.
   Shamir's plan calls for holding elections in the occupied
territories to elect Palestinians to negotiate limited self-rule
with Israel, and Sharon's chief condition was that any vote be
delayed until the end of the uprising.
   The conditions triggered a Cabinet crisis when the center-left
Labor Party responded last week by threatening to leave the
government unless it was made clear that Likud's hard-line stance
was not government policy.
   The homes of the two 16-year-old Palestinians were destroyed in
Gaza City's Shajaiya quarter after the two were arrested for
allegedly killing 64-year-old Zalman Yosef Schlein in the southern
Israel town of Gan Yavne.
   ``The two confessed to planning and carrying out the murder with
a nationalist motive,'' the army said in a statement.
   The two, Nahed Yusef Radwan Gundiah and Mohammed Mahmud Ayed
Hamdiya, also allegedly confessed to belonging to groups associated
with Fatah, Arafat's mainstream faction of the PLO, the army said.
   At least 20 people were said to have lived in each house, and the
noise of the explosions could be heard across Gaza City, Arab
reporters said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
