<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchClosings     07-17 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Closings,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>5 More Detroit-Area Catholic Churches Close Under Archdiocese Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five more Roman Catholic Churches have closed as
part of Cardinal Edmund Szoka's program to eliminate 30 inner-city
parishes that have been losing members.
   Sunday's closings brings to 26 the number of churches that have
shut their doors. Four others are to close later this year.
   ``We're all very unhappy but reconciled, I guess,'' said George
Blanchard, a member of St. Monica parish for 65 years. ``What else
can you do?''
   Also holding final Masses on Sunday were Antioch, Patronage of
St. Joseph, St. Stanislaus and Resurrection churches.
   Parishioners and officials of 18 parishes were turned down Friday
by the Michigan Court of Appeals in their effort to block the
closings.
   ``My father died a year and a half ago at 96, and I'm just glad
he didn't have to see this,'' said Mary Wojcik, a member of
Resurrection parish. ``It would have broken his heart.''
   The archdiocese cites declining membership, a shortage of priests
and the costs of maintaining the large churches as reasons for
ordering the closings.
</TEXT>
