<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineDrop     07-17 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Drop,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Washing Up on South Carolina Beaches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 pounds of cocaine with an
estimated street value of $7.5 million have been plucked from South
Carolina beaches and waters in the past two weeks, an official said
today.
   The contraband, wrapped in Styrofoam and baled in burlap bags,
may have been from an unsuccessful air drop by smugglers, said James
McGivney, agent in charge of the Drug Enforcement Administration in
Columbia.
   ``Right now we're in the position of trying to determine whether
it was a vessel that kicked them (the bales) off or an air drop that
went bad. We don't have any indication that either a vessel or an
aircraft sank,'' he said.
   Smugglers sometimes bring drugs north on small planes and then
drop them to be picked up by others.
   Some of the bales were found on beaches while others were picked
up offshore by charter fishermen, McGivney said. He didn't know how
many bales were found in all.
   ``Several bales were picked up from as far south as Edisto Beach
and from as far north as the Little River area,'' a distance of
about 120 miles, McGivney said.
   The wholesale value of the cocaine was at least $1.5 million. At
$100 a gram, the drugs have a street value of $7.5 million, McGivney
said. The Coast Guard, Customs, the FBI and the DEA took custody of
the cocaine, McGivney said. No arrests have been made.
   Packages of cocaine also washed ashore on Texas beaches earlier
this month. Officials there speculated that the tightly wrapped
packages came from a drug smuggler's ship that went down in Tropical
Storm Allison in June.
   Officials didn't know how many packages in all were found, but
the largest was 55 pounds, said Cliff Wolfe, a Customs agent in
Houston.
</TEXT>
