<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-US     07-17 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-US,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kabul Seeks Formal U.S. Request for Journalist's Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it must have
a formal letter from the United States requesting the release of an
American photographer who was captured after entering the country
with guerrillas.
   Tony O'Brien, who was on assignent for Time-Life Inc., was
arrested June 8 in Kabul at a hideout used by the Moslem guerrillas
who are trying to overthrow the Soviet-supported government.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said the Afghan
government has decided in principle to release the 43-year-old
photographer.
   ``But we will need a letter from the American government
requesting us to release Mr. O'Brien,'' Amani said. ``We hope the
American consular officer who is in town is carrying such a letter,
which should also authorize her as the representative of the
American government.''
   Renny Smith from the U.S. Embassy in New Delhi arrived in Kabul
on Sunday to oversee O'Brien's release.
   Mrs. Smith said she would not comment on the Afghan demand.
   ``I was told everything was OK. In fact, I have booked myself to
return on Tuesday,'' she said.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Afghan government appeared to be using O'Brien in an effort to force
the United States into issuing a statement that could be construed
as recognizing President Najib's government as legitimate. The
United States supports the rebels.
   A French photographer and an Italian photojournalist captured by
government forces were freed last year, but only after their
governments formally requested their release and dispatched senior
officials to Kabul.
   The clemency pleas by the French and Italian governments were
widely publicized by Kabul as a show of official international
recognition.
   The United States withdrew its ambassador from Kabul in protest
after Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up a
faltering Marxist government. The U.S. Embassy closed in January in
the final days of the Soviet withdrawal.
   Other major Western nations also closed their embassies, citing
fears of rapidly deteriorating security after the Soviets left.
   The Afghan government said last month it had decided to release
O'Brien, who is from Santa Fe, N.M., in response to a personal
request to Najib from Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser
Arafat.
</TEXT>
