<FIRST>u w PM-KALFlight 1stLd-Writethru a0456 07-17 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-KAL Flight, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Under Way in 1983 Korean Air Lines Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 12 grafs new with jury selection process under way; pick
up 11th graf pvs, KAL says.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today in a civil trial
arising from the 1983 Korean Air Lines disaster in which a jumbo jet
strayed into Soviet air space and was shot down by a Soviet fighter
plane, killing all 269 people aboard.
   Families of passengers killed in the shootdown of Flight 007 are
seeking to prove in court that the airliner's crew engaged in
willful misconduct.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization concluded Flight
007 had been off course for nearly 5{ hours before it was destroyed.
   U.S. District Court Judge Aubrey Robinson is presiding at the
civil trial, which he told a pool of 36 prospective jurors will last
three to four weeks. A six-member jury and three alternates are to
be chosen from the pool of District of Columbia residents.
   Lawyers for the families said they expect to present about 10
witnesses, several of them Korean Air Lines crew members who flew
the northern Pacific route of the ill-fated Flight 007. Lawyers for
the airline said they may present nearly two dozen witnesses,
including as many as 11 employees of the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   Lawyers for the families suggest in court papers that crew
members aboard the Boeing 747 knew shortly after leaving Anchorage,
Alaska, on the last leg of their journey, that because of an error
they made before takeoff they were operating without a reliable
Inertia Navigation System. The three computerized devices aboard the
aircraft were the primary means of navigating the flight.
   Instead of temporarily aborting the flight to reprogram the
system, the crew may have decided to navigate the flight without it,
in clear violation of proper piloting procedure, say the families'
lawyers.
   Crewmen aboard some previous flights that had been aborted had
been disciplined.
   The plaintiffs contend that willful misconduct by the jet's crew
makes the airline liable for damages in excess of the
$75,000-per-passenger limit normally permitted under international
agreement.
   The U.S. government said the plane was lost due to a navigational
mistake and that its pilot did not know he was over Soviet
territory. The Soviet Union contends the plane intentionally flew
its course to photograph sensitive military installations.
   The jumbo jet was flying from New York to Seoul, South Korea,
when a Soviet military jet attacked it over Sakhalin Island, a site
of Soviet military installations.
   Rep. Larry McDonald, D-Ga., who was the chairman of the John
Birch Society, and 60 other U.S. citizens were among the victims.
   KAL says the only inference that can be drawn from the ``assumed
deviation'' from a normal flight path is that the crew was negligent
in failing to notice it had gone off course. The judge said in a
ruling last November that negligence may not be the only explanation.
   ``A failure to notice that the flight was off-course at Point A,
or point B, or Point C ... might be evidence only of negligence,''
said Robinson. ``But a failure to notice that the flight was
off-course at Point A and point B and Point C ... is susceptible to
a different interpretation.''
   That ``different interpretation'' is that ``the crew was aware of
its deviation but elected not to report it and take corrective
action,'' suggested the judge.
   Robinson found sufficient evidence for a conclusion that the crew
of Flight 007 knew the navigation system aboard the plane was
unreliable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NotesSeized     07-17 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Notes Seized,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reporter Covering Union Meeting Detained, Notes Taken</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reporter covering a meeting of
striking carpenters was detained briefly and had his notes and a
tape recording of the proceedings confiscated.
   Johnny Gunter, a business writer for The Clarion-Ledger, was
covering a vote Sunday by carpenter union members on a proposed
contract with Georgia-Pacific's plywood and particleboard mills at
Taylorsville.
   Gunter filed a robbery complaint against Jones Fitzhugh, an
official with the Southern Council of Industrial Workers, and Loyd
McGee, a carpenters union member.
   Fitzhugh and McGee turned themselves in and each posted $200
bond. Justice Court Judge Dale Ford said Gunter would have to file a
civil lawsuit to recover his materials.
   The notes and cassette tape were confiscated near the end of a
meeting at Taylorsville High School that was attended by about 400
striking Georgia-Pacific workers.
   Gunter said he was admitted to the meeting by a union official,
and that he took notes and recorded the discussion. He said he made
no attempt to disguise his presence.
   Toward the end of the meeting, Gunter said, someone pointed him
out to Fitzhugh, who was presiding. Gunter said McGee then
approached him and asked for a camera, which he didn't have, and
then demanded his tape recorder. Gunter refused to surrender it and
was told to leave the meeting _ but that first he would have to give
up his cassette and notebook.
   Gunter said he refused to give up his notes and that he and his
wife, who was with him, got up to leave.
   ``We'd only taken a couple of steps when 20 to 25 men crowded
around us. I tried to shove my way past them and couldn't get
through,'' Gunter said. ``Several of the men were grabbing for my
recorder and notebook. Others locked the auditorium door so we
couldn't leave.''
   Gunter said he finally surrendered his tape and notes and was
allowed to leave. He then filed the robbery complaint.
   Fitzhugh declined to comment after posting bond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
