<FIRST>u a PM-PTLTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0480 07-17 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PTL Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense To Open Case Today in Trial of Former PTL Aides</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with today's testimony; Picks up
6th graf, `Bakker and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former PTL aides charged with evading
$487,000 in federal income taxes had several hundred thousand
dollars more in questionable income the government did not
challenge, an Internal Revenue Service agent testified today.
   IRS Agent Charles F. Mauney, an expert in tax-evasion cases,
testified that David and James Taggart did not report more than
$400,000 in taxable income for the years 1984 and 1985.
   Mauney, who was questioned by government prosecutor David Brown,
testified that the IRS did not challenge more than $320,000 in PTL
payments to the defendants for those years. The defendants are also
charged with similar violations for the years 1986 and 1987 _ a
topic expected to be taken up as Mauney's testimony continues.
   ``There has been some testimony or documents in this trial which
purport to account for some of these (payments),'' Mauney said.
``The government decided not to challenge these items.
   ``A lot of these items are questionable,'' he said. ``If I was
doing a civil examination I would not allow them.''
   The Taggarts, accused of taking more than $1 million in PTL money
to bankroll their extravagant lifestyle, were fired by the TV
ministry following the resignation of PTL founder Jim Bakker.
   Defense attorney Ben Cotten has not ruled out an appearance by
Bakker, who was the defendants' boss and close friend during the
years the Taggarts' were charged with evading $487,000 in income
taxes.
   Bakker and Richard Dortch _ his former top deputy at the
now-bankrupt television ministry _ are scheduled to go on trial in
Charlotte Aug. 28 on 24 counts of wire and mail fraud and conspiracy.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Potter gave the jury the day off
Friday. The prosecution is expected to rest its case today after
about two hours of additional testimony.
   The Taggart brothers joined PTL in the late 1970s as piano
players. Within a few years, David, 32, was promoted to Bakker's top
personal aide and James, 35, became PTL's interior decorator.
   Both were fired when Jerry Falwell took over at the television
ministry when Bakker's resigned in March 1987 following revelations
of the Jessica Hahn sex-and-money scandal.
   Following a 16-month grand jury investigation into PTL's
operation under Bakker's leadership, the Taggarts were charged with
tax evasion and conspiracy last December.
   Prosecutors accuse them of diverting more than $1.1 million in
PTL money to their own use by taking large cash advances and by
using blank ministry checks to pay off their personal credit card
bills.
   Beginning July 5, testimony from dozens of New York shopkeepers
and friends of the Taggarts showed the defendants went on spending
sprees in the most exclusive stores in Manhattan, Florida,
California and Europe. The purchases included a $96,000 ring and an
$85,000 diamond and sapphire pin.
   Prosecutors charge the Taggarts used money donated to the
tax-exempt religious organization to buy a $640,000 condominium in
the exclusive Trump Tower New York skyscraper on Fifth Avenue.
   On Thursday, the assistant manager of a Charlotte bank testified
the Taggarts' combined net worth grew from $171,000 to nearly $1.7
million from 1984 through 1987.
   If convicted, the Taggarts each face a maximum sentence of 25
years in prison and fines of up to more than $1 million.
   For about seven years, David Taggart served as Bakker's personal
aide for all but a short time in 1983, when he left PTL for several
months. Older brother James was an interior decorator whose firm was
paid more than $1.2 million over three years by PTL.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
