<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Ferry     07-17 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Ferry,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferry Capsizes Near Capital, 60 Feared Drowned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger ferry capsized in the Jamuna
River near Dhaka and at least 60 people were feared drowned, police
said Monday.
   The ferry was carrying at least 70 passengers when it capsized
during a sudden rainstorm Sunday near Manikganj, about 35 miles
northwest of Dhaka, police said.
   ``We have reports that 10 people swam ashore and the rest are
missing,'' said a police official at Manikganj, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Abdul Kader, an official who helped in the rescue, said it was
unlikely any more survivors would be found.
   ``The river was very fast at the point the boat sank so it was
difficult for anyone to survive even if the person knew how to
swim,'' he said. ``The rainstorm, which lasted 30 minutes, whipped
up high waves as the boat went down.''
   Bangladesh is criss-crossed by hundreds of rivers, and ferries
are a popular means of transport. Ferry accidents are common during
the summer monsoon, which lasts from July through September.
</TEXT>
