<DOCNO> AP890717-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Jesuits     07-17 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Jesuits,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jesuit Sinologist Pessimistic About China's Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jesuit priest who publishes a newsletter on
China said Monday he holds little hope for the country's future
until the demise of aging conservative leaders who are behind the
crackdown on dissent.
   ``I'm not very optimistic,'' said Rev. Yves Nalet, who puts out
the Jesuit-funded China News Analysis. ``It's very rare to have an
elderly leadership with a good vision of the future. They are afraid
of death.''
   Nalet, a 42-year-old Frenchman, and two other priests are
continuing a rich history of Jesuit scholarship on China with their
newsletter published twice a month in this British colony.
   ``One of the traditional works of the Jesuits is to try to
understand what is happening in the society where you live,'' Nalet
said.
   He noted that the Jesuits, a Roman Catholic order founded in 1534
by Ignatius Loyola, has been interested in Chinese culture since the
time of Matteo Ricci (1552-1610), the brilliant Jesuit scholar who
became a court official during the Ming dynasty. Some members of the
order learned classical Chinese and became mathematicians and
astronomers to the country's emperors.
   The Jesuits who write China News Analysis each have a doctorate
in Chinese studies. They subscribe to scores of newspapers and
periodicals from China that form the core of their research.
   Nalet said their publication, which first appeared in 1953, has
about 800 subscribers, including embassies, schools and government
agencies.
   The demand for news and views about China has shot up since the
events of the spring, when a student-led movement for democratic
change in Beijing captured the imagination of the world.
   The government, led by a group of aging revolutionaries, called
in the military to crush the movement and ordered a crackdown on all
dissent. Moderate party chief Zhao Ziyang was sacked and replaced by
Jiang Zemin, the little-known party head of Shanghai.
   ``My impression is that Jiang Zemin doesn't have much power,''
Naley said in an interview in his office. ``The only base he has is
that he's backed by Deng Xiaoping,'' the 84-year-old senior leader
of China.
   The political situation is in ``a period of transition until the
elder leaders die,'' said Nalet, who believes that no real change in
the country can occur until a new generation takes control. No
obvious successor to the aging revolutionaries has emerged, however,
meaning the likelihood of a continuing power struggle.
   Nalet also is pessimistic about China's economy, which has
quickly grown in the past decade under Deng's policy of
modernization and opening to the outside world.
   ``Behind the facade of party unity raw power struggles have
always existed; the latest episode has shattered forever the myth of
a party united in the pursuit of modernization,'' the July 15
edition of the newsletter said.
   The private sector that mushroomed under Deng's policies may be
hit hard by the latest political campaigns that have attacked
Western ideals. ``I don't think many people will want to start a
business of their own, it's too dangerous,'' he said.
   Nalet said that many of Zhao's economic advisers who favored
reforms have lost their jobs in the crackdown, ``so we are going to
go back to a centralized, planned economy.''
   Rural enterprises that also grew rapidly recently may find it
difficult to get raw materials if the government decides to take
strong measures to ensure critical resources go to state-run
factories, he said. That would exacerbate an already serious
unemployment problem in the countryside.
   The Jesuit scholar, in reviewing the events in Beijing, said the
democracy movement ``was too early and went too far.''
   Communist China is only 40 years old and the aging
revolutionaries who still wield power responded to the movement by
saying, ``We have built a country, we have built a party and we
don't want to see this disappear.''
   He expressed hope that the democracy movement ``may have started
a new vision'' among the Chinese. ``How long it will take to come
back is another question.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0084 </DOCNO>
