<DOCNO> AP890717-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Charges Opposition Lawmaker's Campaign Funded By North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition lawmaker was charged with
espionage Monday for allegedly receiving $120,000 from North Korea
and running for public office on the order of communist agents.
   In the most serious such case in South Korean history, the Agency
for National Security Planning said Suh Kyung-won was turned over to
prosecutors, who have 30 days to produce the indictment needed for
trial.
   If convicted, Suh, 52, could face the death penalty.
   Suh aide Pang Yang-hyun, who also was charged with espionage, is
accused of being the middleman in Suh's alleged transactions with
the Pyongyang government.
   The intelligence agency said Suh received a total of $120,000 on
14 occasions between April 1985, when he was allegedly recruited by
North Korean agents, and December 1988.
   The intelligence agency's evidence included photographs, bank
records, a North Korean passport it said Suh used, a memorandum he
allegedly wrote for communist agents, straw slippers from a hotel in
Pyongyang and paper on which he allegedly wrote code words for North
Korean agents.
   The evidence also included notes intelligence agents said Suh
made during a meeting with North Korean leader Kim Il Sung,
outlining Kim's ideas for unification.
   Ahn Ung-mo, deputy director of the security agency, said Suh ran
for the National Assembly as a member of the leading opposition
Party for Peace and Democracy. Suh did so on secret orders from
North Korea, which had given him campaign funds, Ahn said.
   ``Suh won a seat in the National Assembly under direction from
North Korea, passed secrets to Pyongyang and staged various
anti-government activities,'' Ahn said.
   The leading opposition Party for Peace and Democracy expelled Suh
as a member after he was arrested June 28 and it has accused the
government of harassment and political sabotage for the questioning
of party members.
   The leader of the party, Kim Dae-jung, turned down two requests
to be interviewed by intelligence agents, saying he had nothing to
add to the investigation that authorities cannot learn elsewhere.
   Suh, a farmer and dissident-turned-lawmaker, surrendered June 25
after first telling party leaders he had illegally visited North
Korea in August. He was arrested June 28 on charges of violating
national security.
   South Korea forbids unauthorized trips to North Korea,
maintaining that dialogue on unification must be conducted through
official channels.
   The case is the most serious of its kind since the peninsula was
divided at the end of World War II because of the alleged frequency
of Suh's contact with North Korea and the political overtones.
   In 1949, shortly after the new government took office, some South
Korean legislators were accused of pro-North Korea activities. In
the early 1970s, a lawmaker was investigated for communist activity.
   Also Monday, news reports said immigration controls have been
tightened to block foreigners from entering South Korea to
participate in a peace march aimed at unification.
   About 100 foreigners, including about 30 Americans, were expected
to enter the country for a July 20-27 ``International Grand Peace
March for the Reunification of the Korean Peninsula.'' Authorities
said the march would be stopped.
   Immigration procedures were tightened at all ports of entry and
police were checking hotels for marchers already suspected to be in
South Korea, according to Seoul newspapers.
   South Korean law prohibits foreigners from engaging in political
activity, and in the past those breaking the law have been detained
and deported.
</TEXT>
