<DOCNO> AP890717-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     07-17 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Business Inventories Suggest More Production Cutbacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business sales were virtually flat in May while
inventories rose 0.7 percent, the government said Monday, leading
some analysts to predict further production cutbacks during the rest
of the year.
   ``The implication is that production is going to slow some more
in the second half of year,'' said economist Bruce Steinberg of
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York.
   ``It could imply a small inventory correction in the second
half,'' said James Annable, an economist at the First National Bank
of Chicago.
   When not accompanied by increases in sales, rising inventories
often prompt manufacturers to cut back production until stockpiled
goods are sold, resulting in a loss of jobs.
   The Commerce Department said inventories held on shelves and
backlots climbed to a seasonally adjusted $776.9 billion in May
after a 0.8 percent rise in April.
   The pace of business sales, on the other hand, hardly moved,
rising a minuscule 0.02 percent to a seasonally adjusted $517.9
billion. Sales had risen 2.0 percent in April after holding steady
in March.
   The May business activity produced a slight increase in the ratio
of inventories to sales. It was 1.5, meaning it would take 1{ months
to exhaust inventories at the May sales pace. The ratio was 1.49 in
April and 1.51 in March.
   Analysts noted the buildup was most felt in the retail area,
where the economy has slowed the most as the Federal Reserve
tightened credit to contain inflation. Inventories were up 0.9
percent compared with a sales decrease of 0.1 percent.
   ``I'm starting to wonder whether retailer inventories are getting
out of hand,'' said Michael Niemira, an economist at Mitsubishi Bank
in New York. ``The numbers suggest they're growing a little too
fast.''
   The automobile industry, which has seen swollen new car
inventories, already has reduced production at some factories.
Commerce said auto inventories rose 0.9 percent in May while sales
dropped 1.8 percent from April.
   But even without the automobile category, inventories rose 0.9
percent in May.
   Other major inventory increases were noted at department and
clothing stores, Steinberg said. Overall, general merchandise
inventories rose 2.2 percent.
   All categories showed increased inventories in May, however.
   In addition to the 0.9 percent increase in the retail area,
manufacturers' backlogs were up 0.6 percent while wholesalers'
buildup was 0.8 percent. Inventories were 8.1 percent above May 1988.
   Wholesalers registered the only sales increase in May, up 0.5
percent. Manufactuers' sales fell 0.2 percent and retailers' were
down 0.1 percent. Sales rose 8.2 percent over May of last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-Cardinal Bjt   07-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Cardinal, Bjt,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Reviews Conviction of Cardinal Mindszenty</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A review of Cardinal Jozsef Mindszenty's
case by the communist authorities is raising hopes he will be
declared innocent of treason and other trumped-up charges on which
he was convicted 40 years ago.
   The world watched in disbelief in 1949 when Hungary subjected him
to the kind of show trial Josef Stalin used so often in the Soviet
Union. There were allegations the Roman Catholic prelate was drugged
into submission.
   Mindszenty was released during the uprising of 1956 and fled to
the American legation in Budapest, which later became the U.S.
Embassy. He remained there for 15 years before being granted safe
passage to Rome.
   The reform movement sweeping Hungary already has resulted in the
rehabilitation of Imre Nagy, the premier executed for leading the
uprising aginst Stalinism.
   Church officials hope the same will be done for Mindszenty, who
died in Vienna in 1975 at age 83. His rehabilitation would vastly
improve the climate for a visit to Hungary by Pope John Paul II
scheduled for September 1991.
   ``The rehabilitations have started,'' said the Rev. Ervin
Szepesdi, chief aide to Cardinal Laszlo Paskai, current leader of
the Hungarian church.
   He would not give further details, a possible reflection of the
matter's sensitivity, referring instead to reports in official media
last week that the review was under way.
   Mindszenty's case became a symbol of the Cold War and religious
persecution in the Soviet bloc. Its resolution presents several
difficulties, including the allegations of drugging and reports that
important documents have disappeared.
   L'Avvenire, the newspaper published by the Italian Bishops
Conference, said Thursday: ``The long suffering of the primate of
the Hungarian church remains in the history of the country as one of
the most grevious wounds inflicted on the nation's Christian
tradition.''
   The cardinal was appointed to the primacy with the communist
government's asseent, but tension between church and state grew and
he was arrested at the end of 1948.
   In February 1949, Mindszenty was sentenced to life in prison for
high treason after confessing, almost certainly under the effect of
duress or drugs, to most of the charges against him. Protests came
from around the world.
   At the U.S. mission, he lived in a third-floor apartment until
the Vatican worked out the departure arrangement in 1971. Its
efforts to gain his freedom were complicated by Mindszenty's desire
to be cleared before leaving.
   The decision of Pope Paul VI to remove Mindszenty from the
primacy of the Hungarian church in 1974 was followed by improved
relations between Hungary and the Vatican.
   Mindszenty regarded himself as a sacrifice to a thaw in the Cold
War, writing in his memoirs he became an unwelcome guest of the
Americans ``because I stood in the way of the policy of detente.''
   Last week, the official news agency MTI quoted Paskai as saying
in a letter to the government he believed the review of Mindszenty's
``unlawful conviction'' would increase the government's credibility
and promote ``national reconciliation.''
   Premier Miklos Nemeth responded by confirming ``that the
Hungarian government had requested the prosecutor general to review
the penal procedure'' against Mindszenty, the agency said.
   There has been no indication of how long the review would take.
   About half the 10.6 million people in Hungary are Catholics, but
many no longer practice the faith.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CultConnection 1stLd-Writethru a0493 07-17 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cult Connection, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Investigate Possible Drug Cult Link to Chicago Mob</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf with comment from Chicago officials;
INSERTS 4 grafs after 7th graf, `Among Jaramillo's ...' with officials'
comment; Picks up last graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Narcotics and money-laundering schemes
may link Chicago mob bosses to a cult-influenced drug ring blamed
for 15 slayings near Matamoros, Mexico, a newspaper reported.
   ``We can acknowledge we are looking into a relationship, but I
really can't go into any details,'' said Charles Harrison, assistant
special agent in charge of the U.S. Customs regional office in
Houston.
   But officials in Chicago said today they knew of no such
connection.
   The Brownsville Herald reported Sunday in a copyright story that
Harrison's agency is investigating a possible relationship between
Chicago organized crime leaders and the cult ring.
   It identified Manuel ``Poncho'' Jaramillo, who lives in Mission,
Texas, as an alleged connection between the two groups. The
newspaper cited court transcripts, indictments, affidavits and
police records filed in drug and racketeering cases in south Texas
and Illinois.
   Jaramillo's Houston attorney, Dennis Yates, called drug and
racketeering allegations against his client ``harassment.''
   ``Those accusations, as far as we're concerned, are absolutely
untrue,'' Yates said. ``They aren't substantiated, they have not
been substantiated and they never will be substantiated.''
   Among Jaramillo's associates are Albert Caesar Tocco, a reputed
Chicago mob boss arrested in January by FBI agents and charged in a
48-count federal racketeering indictment, according to the Herald.
   Bob Long, an FBI spokesman in Chicago, said he knew nothing about
it.
   ``Apparently they're saying Tocco may have some involvement''
with the Matamoros drug ring, Long said by telephone today. ``They
may or may not be correct,'' he said.
   Tocco, 59, is jailed at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in
downtown Chicago awaiting a Nov. 6 trial on the racketeering charges.
   Jerry Gladden, chief investigator for the Chicago Crime
Commission, also said he's unaware of any connection between the
Chicago mob and the cult ring.
   Jaramillo also is allegedly connected with members of the
Matamoros-based Hernandez family, which Mexican and American agents
believe was central to a gruesome cult accused of killing 15 people,
federal investigators said. Police have said some of the cult's
victims were sacrificed in rituals aimed at protecting a narcotics
ring.
</TEXT>
