<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka-Militias     07-17 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka-Militias,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Militia Forcing Young Men to Join The Fight, Refugees Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Muthiah left his home in
northern Sri Lanka and bicycled 170 miles to Colombo to escape
recruitment into a Tamil militia that is supported by Indian
peacekeeping troops.
   Residents say the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front,
which controls the government of the Northeastern Province, is
preparing for another round of fighting with rival militias by
forcing Tamils to join its ranks.
   Hundreds of Tamil youths have fled the region, claiming the group
was picking up men from their homes, shaving off their hair and
eyebrows and forcing them to undergo training at military camps.
   ``It is not safe for me at home any more,'' said Muthiah, 25, who
registered at a relief center set up for the Tamils near Colombo.
``Tamil groups assisted by Indian peacekeeping troops have been
cordoning off villages and searching every home for young men.''
   ``I do not want to join any movement,'' he said. ``I just want to
live in peace with my family.''
   Another Tamil youth, Mylvaganan Mathyvathanan, 17, said he jumped
off a jeep taking him to an army camp and made his way to Colombo
from his village in the northern district of Jaffna. He said he
complained to Indian soldiers about the forced conscription, ``but
they just turned away and were not interested.''
   At least 386 men registered last week at the center, which
provides them with food and a place to sleep. Hundreds of others
have visited but have not registered because they do not want to
reveal their identities.
   The Liberation Front admits it is recruiting youths for a civil
volunteer group but denies using force.
   But the recruitments have been stepped up since May, when a rival
militia, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, opened talks with the
government.
   The two groups have been bitter rivals since the Liberation Front
accepted a 1987 peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil secessionist
war. The Tigers rejected the accord's offer of limited autonomy and
continued fighting for an independent Tamil nation.
   The accord was sponsored by neighboring India, which sent in
troops to enforce a surrender by the Tamil groups. The Indian
soldiers have aligned with the Liberation Front and hold joint
patrols with its members to ferret out the Tigers.
   ``We have reports that the abductions are done with the
connivance of the Indian peacekeeping forces,'' says Foreign
Minister Ranjan Wijeratne. ``I have taken up this matter with the
Indian High Commission (embassy) who have said they will look into
the charge.''
   Indian officials in Colombo deny the charge. But the New Delhi
government has said it supports the Liberation Front government and
views the Tigers' talks with Colombo with suspicion.
   Wijeratne says also that the provincial government was not
authorized to raise a volunteer force.
   ``The civil volunteer force should come under the direct
authority of the inspector-general of police and recruitment,
training and issuing of arms should be done by the deputy
inspector-general of police in charge of the northern region,'' he
said.
   Both posts named by Wijeratne are controlled by the federal
government in Colombo.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
live mostly on the north and east. Tamil militants, including the
Liberation Front and the Tigers, started fighting for an independent
nation in 1983, claiming they were discriminated against by the
Sinhalese, who form 75 percent of the population and control the
government and the military.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed in the separatist war. The
victims include at least 800 Indian soldiers and many Tamils who
were caught up in the fighting between the two groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WasteDump     07-17 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waste Dump,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Worn Down by Radioactive Dump Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven years after a 400-acre landfill
loaded with radioactive and chemical wastes was closed by its
operator, dust is flying as the company tries to stop more waste
from seeping into groundwater and a lake.
   Bulldozers are piling tons of dirt and clay atop the 22 burial
trenches, which residents call poison pits, at US Ecology's landfill
in an effort to put a tight lid on the facility just west of town.
Eventually, there will be a 4-foot-thick layer of dense clay over 65
acres.
   ``We're trying to stop rain water from going down and carrying
(waste) away from the site,'' said Mark Bowen, site manager. ``We're
installing clay caps on the trenches that will cut the water seepage
by more than half.''
   ``By eliminating water from entering the trenches, we hope to
stop the escape of waste buried in them,'' he said.
   After two decades battling the company, residents of Sheffield, a
town of 1,000 people 60 miles north of Peoria, are cynical about
claims the landfill will be stabilized, unconvinced of their safety
and weary of the fight.
   They say that tritium, a radioactive form of hydrogen, and
solvents, pesticides and poisons escaping into underground water and
seeping into Trout Lake can't be stopped by simply piling new clay
atop the trenches. The buried wastes include highly radioactive
plutonium and uranium, about 100 pounds in all.
   Trout Lake is off limits to fishing, swimming or any recreation
because of the dump.
   The dump was closed in 1978 when the state refused to allow the
operator, then called Nuclear Engineering Co., to bury waste in a
new trench. The state said tritium gas was leaking and the ground
was too sandy to prevent wastes from migrating away from the site,
leased from the state.
   The company ``put the keys to the gate on the table in one of the
sheds and sent us a telegram saying `We have finished our work at
the site. Since you own it, it's yours again,''' said Clifford
Weaver, a lawyer who represented the state.
   The state filed a $97 million lawsuit, charging the company had
broken its 99-year lease and demanding that it remove the
radioactive wastes.
   Ten years of litigation produced an agreement from the company,
which became US Ecology Inc. in 1981, to spend $8 million for
immediate maintenance and long-term care of the facility.
   A second state lawsuit demanding exhumation of chemical wastes
remains active.
   ``We've fought the dump for 100 years, it seems,'' said Jay
Langford, a pharmacy owner and member of a citizens group opposed to
the dump. ``They won't stop the leaking. It will leak some more and
they will buy another farm to keep it on their property.''
   As part of its agreement, US Ecology purchased a 170-acre buffer
zone around the dump.
   Langford said the clay cap is only a smoke screen.
   ``They are just so deceiving. They are willing to let it ruin all
our lakes, streams and water supplies. Who cares if they put a
beautiful cap on it? It's what's underneath that's the problem,''
Langford said.
   Beautician Robin Hewitt said she uses bottled water because water
from the town's well ``smells like rotten eggs and chlorine and is
pure rust coming out of the faucets.''
   The landfill trenches hold 7.6 million cubic feet of buried
wastes.
   US Ecology says exhumation of the waste is unnecessary, would
take 15 years and cost $500 million, which would bankrupt the
company.
   ``The caps should be finished by the end of August, and then
we'll start preparing the soil, seeding it and building fence,''
said Mark Cade, company spokesman.
   Cade said no danger is associated with the dump.
   ``The fact is, this site has never been unsafe,'' Cade said.
``This is not a serious problem. It's a perception problem. They say
this is a horrible place but I can't find the horrible place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
