<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he will
nominate Glen A. Holden, a Los Angeles insurance executive, to be
ambassador to Jamaica.
   Bush also said he has chosen Lannon Walker, a career Foreign
Service office and onetime ambassador to Senegal, to be ambassador
to Nigeria. He would succeed Princeton Nathan Lyman.
   Holden, who has a long background in the insurance business, has
been the head of the Holden Group in Los Angeles since 1973. He
would succeed Michael Sotirhos.
   The White House also said Bush is nominating Howard K. Walker, a
career foreign service officer, as ambassador to Madagascar and the
Republic of the Comoros. Walker, who would succeed Patricia Gates
Lynch, is a senior inspector general at the State Department and
former director of its Office of West African affairs.
   The nominations, which require Senate confirmation, were
announced here at the end of Bush's four-nation, 10-day journey
through Europe.
