<FIRST>r i AM-BarbaraBush 1stLd-Writethru a0598 07-17 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0598,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Unveils Cornerstone of New American School</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds. adds overline and subs graf 4, bgng ``She added, to CORRECT
spelling of scraping; picks up 5th pvs, ``Mrs. Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush unveiled the
cornerstone of a new American school in the Hague on Monday and
confessed that no one can find a similar marker back at the White
House.
   ``One of the great mysteries of the White House is where they put
the cornerstone,'' she said.
   The first lady said historians know when the cornerstone was laid
and who did it, but ``absolutely no one knows where.''
   She added, ``We decided that was one uncertainty we could live
with.'' The White House is currently getting a facelift that
involves scraping off its many layers of paint and restoring the
original stonework.
   Mrs. Bush spoke at the future site of the American School of The
Hague. At this point, the school is still a dusty construction site
with concrete forms.
   The inscription on the stone reads: ``The American School of the
Hague. This cornerstone unveiled by Mrs. Barbara Bush, first lady,
July 17, 1989, on the occasion of the first visit by a president of
the United States of America to the Netherlands.''
   Mrs. Bush was accompanied by Ria Lubbers, wife of Dutch Prime
Minister Ruud Lubbers, Susan Baker, wife of Secretary of State James
A. Baker III, and the wives of several other Dutch officials.
   Mrs. Bush and her entourage also stopped in Amsterdam to visit
the Van Gogh Museum. About a dozen demonstrators awaited her,
chanting ``Bush go home.''
   If she saw them, it was only in passing.
   Dirk van der Oord, the museum's public affairs director,
dismissed the protest as ``very old stuff, 20 years ago. For
Amsterdam, it's very small.''
   Touring the museum, Mrs. Bush stopped to scrutinize the Van Gogh
painting, ``Field with Iris,'' and said aloud four times, ``I love
this one.''
</TEXT>
