<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First item for release 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Kadeem Hardison says he took the part of
Dwayne on NBC's ``A Different World'' because he figured there was
no way the show would last and possibly trap him in television.
   ``It was awful,'' Hardison said in an interview for the July 22
issue of TV Guide, recalling the day he saw an episode of the
``Cosby Show'' spinoff being taped. ``I didn't think the show was
going to last more than five episodes.''
   The 23-year-old actor, who was a bicycle messenger at the time,
says he needed the work but didn't want to get stuck on TV.
   ``I thought I'd make good money in a short period of time and
they were going to let me play a home boy on TV,'' he recalls,
adding his opinion of the show has changed.
   ``I love it. It's great work,'' Hardison said. ``But I
desparately want to get into something else.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mouth that roars will soon be
singing.
   Morton Downey Jr., the confrontational television talk-show host,
is scheduled to perform Aug. 4 to 6 at Trump Castle Hotel and Casino.
   Downey has occasionally sung on his syndicated program. He has
released an album of songs, but the casino gig will mark his first
concert appearance, said Thomas Cantone, the casino's entertainment
vice president.
   Downey's father was the Irish tenor Morton Downey. The younger
Downey used to sing on the motel cocktail lounge circuit, but his
musical career never advanced further.
   ``His audience is our audience, and the demographics are right up
the casino's alley,'' Cantone said. ``Sometimes, you have to do
something different ... in order to attract the attention of
(gamblers).''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Paar, who is recovering from a heart attack
he suffered July 4, says he owes his life to a book on how to
recognize the symptoms of heart disease.
   Paar, whose condition was revealed Monday, was recovering in New
York Hospital, where he was transferred July 7 after initial
treatment near his home in Greenwich, Conn., said hospital
spokeswoman Myrna Manners.
   A day or two before he was stricken, the 71-year-old former talk
show host read a book that describes the symptoms of various
ailments, including heart attacks.
   ``A book saved my life,'' the hospital quoted Paar as saying. ``I
awoke at about 3:30 a.m. with a pain in my chest and I tried to fool
myself into thinking it was just indigestion.''
   But he recalled what he'd read in ``Symptoms,'' by Isadore
Rosenfeld, and got help.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Norm Bangerter underwent two hours'
surgery Monday to repair a shattered elbow he suffered when he fell
during a London visit.
   Doctors at the University of Utah's Sorenson Medical Center
pronounced the operation a success and said the 56-year-old
Republican will have to wear a cast for some time while the injury
heals, said hospital spokesman John Dwan.
   Bangerter, one of eight governors on a European trip organized by
the National Governors Association, was hurt July 4 when he fell at
Westminster Abbey.
