<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1454EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FugitivesArrested     07-17 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fugitives Arrested,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Task Force Arrests 456</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a task force designed to get
``career drug criminals'' off the streets have arrested 456 people,
including 25 charged with murder, officials said Monday.
   The U.S. Marshals Service led the Street Terror Offender Program,
or STOP, aimed at fugitives in the Washington-Baltimore area sought
in drug-related homicides or on other drug charges.
   Some fugitives were arrested as far away as California and
Florida, officials said.
   ``The eight-week program was designed to remove from the streets
career drug criminals,'' Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said at a
news conference announcing the arrests.
   William J. Bennett, director of the Office of National Drug
Control Policy, said those arrested ``have found that the criminal
justice system in this area works.''
   The program, Bennett said, proves ``the bad guys can be
apprehended and brought to justice.''
   The $1.3 million federal program, which began May 22, targeted
those with an active drug felony warrant and at least three felony
drug arrests or convictions. Also targeted were suspects with an
active warrant for a drug-related homicide.
   Among those arrested was Herbert Douglas Jr., a suspect in three
Washington homicides.
   Douglas had been sentenced to 146 years in prison after being
convicted in a 1981 shootout with police during an armed robbery,
but he was paroled after serving less than six years. He is charged
with murder in a 1987 killing and a 1989 double homicide.
   Authorities also said they arrested Tony Miller, an alias for
Sean Henry.
   On the day Henry's trial was to begin on charges of distribution
of cocaine, the court received a death certificate for him. He was
subsequently arrested under another name and released, but a
fingerprint check revealed his identity. He was arrested at Parris
Island, S.C., while attending Marine Corps boot camp.
   U.S. Marshals Service Director Stanley Morris said about 62
percent of those sought were considered armed and dangerous, but
that all the arrests were made without a shot being fired.
   STOP targeted 840 fugitives, arrested 456 and filed detainers on
155 already jailed on other charges. A total of 229 remain at-large.
   ``People get tired,'' Morris said in an interview when asked why
the program ended before all the suspects were arrested.
   ``Eight weeks is a long time. Our experience is that's about ...
the length of time you can run an operation like this without people
starting to get homesick, a little careless and start to lose their
edge.''
   The program involved 56 federal marshals and 34 local officers.
Officials lauded the cooperation between federal and local agencies.
   Of those arrested, 172 were wanted for crimes in the District of
Columbia, 154 in Baltimore and 130 in suburban Maryland and Virginia.
   Bennett said a similar program could be carried out elsewhere,
but he would not say where.
   ``It's not the sort of thing you want to let out ahead of time,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
