<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Karajan     07-17 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Karajan,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tributes Abound to Herbert von Karajan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Berlin Philharmonic on Monday
mourned the death of Herbert von Karajan, its former ``conductor for
life,'' and the Salzburg Festival, where he was to perform this
month, held a minute of silence.
   Tributes abounded for the Austrian-born maestro who died Sunday
of heart failure at age 81.
   The Berlin Philharmonic, which he quit in April after a stormy
relationship for three decades, said Karajan had ``stamped his
orchestra with his own inimitable style.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl sent a telegram to Karajan's
widow, praising the maestro for his more than 30 years with the
Berlin Philharmonic.
   Kohl said Karajan helped continue Berlin's reputation as ``one of
the (world's) leading cultural metropolises. We thank him for that.''
   In Austria, Salzburg Festival president Albert Moser called for a
minute of silence for Karajan during rehearsals and gave a brief
speech, a spokeswoman said.
   Karajan was to have opened this year's festival July 27 with
Giuseppe Verdi's Opera ``A Masked Ball,'' with Placido Domingo.
   In a statement, the festival directorate said it mourned Karajan,
who made ``a substantial mark'' on the festival, and it had not yet
determined who will replace him.
   Festival organizers confirmed reports that Karajan died of heart
failure at his home in Anif, outside Salzburg, said the spokeswoman
who commented on condition of anonymity.
   No funeral plans were announced. The Austria Press Agency
reported it would take place in Anif exclusively for family members
but no date was given. Salzburg Festival organizers said they could
not yet confirm the report.
   British opera director John Schlesinger, who had been preparing
the Verdi performance with Karajan, said the show will go on but
Karajan will be sorely missed.
   ``The death of maestro von Karajan is a terrible blow for all of
us. We had been working together on `Un Ballo in Maschera' for more
than a year with great enthusiasm and close collaboration,''
Schlesinger said from Salzburg.
   Karajan, who conducted at the Salzburg Festival since 1948, was
its sole artistic director in 1956-60 and had been on the
directorate since 1964. Last year he resigned from the body but
continued to conduct during this year's festival.
   Riccardo Muti, musical director of La Scala in Milan, told Rome's
Il Messaggero newspaper in Ravenna:
   ``We have lost the most important conductor of our time, the last
great maestro of the Romantic era. Karajan did not leave heirs, but
in reality we are all his heirs, some more, some less,'' Muti said.
   The West German newspaper Die Welt said Karajan was ``perhaps one
of the last great aesthetes of the music scene _ a man with
heightened sensitivity for a tone with color, for a seamless
transition, for music that seems as if it comes from the heavens.''
   The widow of Wilhelm Furtwaengler, who Karajan succeeded as head
of the Berlin Philharmonic, said Karajan's death marks ``the end of
an epoch'' in concert halls.
   ``He was especially brilliant in conducting Anton Bruckner and
Richard Strauss I have never heard such a brilliant ``Don Quijote''
than when he conducted it two years ago in Berlin,'' said Elisabeth
Furtwaengler.
   But Karajan's wealth, love for publicity and what some viewed as
vanity have also irritated many critics.
   The London Times said of Karajan on Monday: ``He was the greatest
orchestral trainer of our century, and maybe of all time. He was an
egomaniac, a bully and a ruthless opportunist. ... He received far
more adulation, sold far more records, made far more money than any
other classical musician.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
