<FIRST>r w AM-CelebratingApollo11     07-17 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Celebrating Apollo 11,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moon Landing Coverage Replayed at Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space buff who wants to relive the night
Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin first walked on the moon can do so
Thursday at the National Air and Space Museum.
   In the same building where the Apollo 11 command module is
displayed, the original television coverage of the moon landing will
be replayed Thursday, the 20th anniversary of the event.
   It will be timed to the actual event, including Armstrong's ``one
small step for a man, one giant leap for mankind'' statement at
10:56 p.m. The show runs from 7:30 p.m. to 1:30 a.m.
   Earlier Thursday, Armstrong, Aldrin and Michael Collins, who
orbited in the command module, will join President Bush for a
ceremony on the steps of the museum.
   The 3,700 journalists who covered the historic flight have been
invited, along with 46 astronauts, to attend a Thursday night party
at the National Press Club.
</TEXT>
