<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ConventionYearLater     07-17 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Convention Year Later,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>People Remember Different Things About 1988 Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Different people remember different things about
the Democratic National Convention that opened a year ago Tuesday,
but everyone at least seems to remember that it happened in Atlanta.
   That makes officials of the Georgia capital happy as they try to
sell their city as the site for the 1994 Super Bowl and the 1996
Summer Olympics.
   There aren't many physical reminders left of the four-day
convention that nominated Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis as the
party's presidential standard-bearer: Colorful banners on light
poles and some nicely paved sidewalks in the convention district.
   But some remember the convention and Dukakis' speech as the high
point of the Democratic campaign.
   ``There are very few things I have been involved in that have run
so smoothly or so triumphantly,'' said Mayor Andrew Young, who
chaired Atlanta '88, the non-profit group that organized the
convention. ``If we could have kept running the campaign, we might
be running the White House.''
   Atlanta '88 President Bobby Kahn remembers Dukakis' triumphant
entry into The Omni arena on the final night to the tune of Neil
Diamond's ``Coming To America.'' But even better, he recalls: ``We
got out of the Omni on time.''
   That saved labor and insurance costs and helped bring the event
in $500,000 under budget. Atlanta '88 spent $14.5 million, most of
it from a special hotel-motel tax.
   Other memories are less pleasant and more immediate.
   The the court system is still dealing with some of the 1,200
misdemeanor cases filed against anti-abortion protesters who came to
capture a share of the convention's limelight.
   Last week, Randall Terry, head of the anti-abortion group
Operation Rescue, returned to Atlanta on a book promotion tour and
was arrested on warrants stemming from the protests. Terry's
attorney said he thought the warrants had been vacated. The activist
was freed on bail.
   Also before the courts is a lawsuit against actor Rob Lowe
stemming from an incident turing the round-the-clock partying that
occupied some of the 4,210 delegates, 13,500-odd journalists and
thousands of other hangers-on convention week.
   Lowe is accused of seducing a teen-age Atlanta girl and then
persuading her to have sex with another woman while he taped it with
his home video camera. Fulton County prosecutors are considering
criminal charges against Lowe, who denies wrongdoing.
   Bad publicity has been turned to good advantage in one case.
   The uproar over the small size of the Omni _ hundreds of
delegates and reporters were locked out one night when fire marshals
declared the place overcrowded _ added impetus to efforts to build
the Georgia Dome.
   The dome, an enclosed stadium designed to hold 72,000 people, is
to be located next door to The Omni and the World Congress Center.
An Atlanta architect was chosen last week to build it.
   Construction of the dome is considered essential to the city's
bids for the 1994 Super Bowl and the 1996 Summer Olympics.
   The convention put Atlanta on the map again for many people, said
Chamber of Commerce official Barry King, who's been lobbying the
International Olympic Committee for the games.
   ``It proved to the world we could do it, that Atlanta was a
capable city, a modern town and not a burned-out cinder from 125
years ago,'' King said, referring to Civil War images.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-TeacherStandards Bjt   07-17 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Standards, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Teaching Certificate to be Offered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers will be rigorously tested on their
specialty, teaching techniques and knowledge of child development
under a voluntary national certification system outlined Monday by
an independent panel.
   With its new national credential, to be offered in 29 fields
starting in 1993, the National Board for Professional Teaching
Standards says it hopes to dispel the myth that ``any modestly
educated person with some instinct for nurturing has the requisite
qualifications to teach.''
   The private group said it hopes that the system will also lead to
improved teacher training and, ultimately, to better-educated
children.
   ``This process will push the renewal of American education a big
step closer to reality,'' former North Carolina Gov. James Hunt,
chairman of the 63-member board, said Monday in releasing the
guidelines.
   The nation's 2.5 million teachers will need a bachelor of arts
degree and at least three years of experience to apply for
certification, according to the new blueprint.
   Board president James A. Kelly said professions such as medicine
and law took decades to set standards for practitioners. He said the
teacher standards board, formed in 1987, will compress the process
into five years ``because we want to influence the quality of the
enormous influx of new teachers needed during the 1990s.''
   The new credential is expected to help draw more and better
people into teaching and help teachers move into new roles as
mentors, curriculum specialists and other positions requiring
expertise or extra responsibility.
   Certified teachers may also command better salaries, but Kelly
said local authorities will have to determine that. ``The board has
always said we want our certificates to be recognized,'' he said in
an interview. ``But it's not the board's business to say how each
school district and private school should recognize certified
teachers.''
   The national board was proposed three years ago by the Carnegie
Forum on Education and the Economy in a report called ``A Nation
Prepared: Teachers for the 21st Century.'' Many were skeptical that
its mix of teachers, government officials, business leaders and
higher education representatives could succeed at what they said was
a highly controversial task with uncertain potential to improve
education.
   Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers
and a longtime backer of national teacher certification, said the
criteria laid out Monday prove the skeptics wrong.
   ``They said it couldn't be done but we did it,'' Shanker said.
``We can be proud that we have come so far.''
   Mary Futrell, president of the National Education Association,
called the guidelines ``an important step down the long road toward
developing a national teaching certificate that can be supported and
embraced by all teachers.''
   The two teacher unions each have seven seats on the board and
have been active in developing the certification process.
   The board said the 29 fields for which it plans to issue
certificates include music, art, foreign languages, physical
education, special education, vocational fields, and subject areas
such as math, science, social studies and English for different age
groups.
   Still to be completed is an evaluation system that is
``professionally credible, publicly acceptable, legally defensible,
administratively feasible and economically affordable for the
teacher candidates,'' Hunt said. ``These assessments will be
state-of-the-art and go far beyond the pencil and paper assessments
used for state licensing today.''
   Among the potential assessment methods described Monday were
multiple choice tests, essays, interviews, simulated lesson plans,
simulated parent conferences, documentation of performance and
observation by trained examiners in the workplace. There will be no
limit on the number or percentage of teachers certified.
   A typical evaluation could involve asking a music teacher to
bring a videotape of an orchestra rehearsal or asking a teacher to
come to an assessment center to discuss and defend alternative
instructional methods, Kelly said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
