<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--GoneWithTheWind     07-17 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gone With The Wind,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film History Buffs Honor Living Heroes of `GWTW' After 50 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank ``Junior'' Coughlan gave a damn
a little too early in ``Gone With The Wind,'' and so he landed on
the cutting room floor.
   Coughlan, now 73, played a soldier who had one line in the 1939
classic: ``Put me down. Put me down. Damn you, I can walk.''
   ``They cut me out because I said `damn' an hour and a half before
Clark Gable did,'' said Coughlan, of Los Alamitos. ``Back then, that
was a big deal.''
   Coughlan was among 600 people who spent Sunday afternoon at
Culver City Studios to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the film
adaptation of Margaret Mitchell's ``Story of the Old South.''
   The Culver City Historical Society used the motion picture's
golden anniversary as an opportunity to raise funds for a museum of
movie memorabilia and to help put Culver City on the movie-making
map.
   Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer said all of its productions came out of
``Hollywood'' until the 1970s when it confessed to residing in
Culver City.
</TEXT>
