<FIRST>r i AM-France-Summit     07-17 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Summit,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Announces Arrest of Suspected Terrorists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French authorities arrested an unspecified number of
suspected terrorists in connection with the just-completed economic
summit and bicentennial celebrations, the interior minister said
Monday.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse and state-owned
television reported that three of those arrested belonged to the
Irish Republican Army.
   Interior Minister Pierre Joxe, however, gave no information about
how many people were involved or where and when they were picked up.
   Joxe said the suspected terrorists were arrested during the
intense pre-summit security sweep carried out throughout France.
   More than 30,000 additional police and troops were brought into
Paris to ensure security and control crowds for last weekend's
events.
   Prime Minister Michel Rocard congratulated Joxe for what he
called the ``perfect success'' of the work of police and security
forces during the weekend.
   State-owned television Antenne 2 said the three IRA members were
arrested in Ste. Menehould in eastern France on the basis of
information provided by the British authorities.
   It said they came to the attention of the French security
services during preparations for the summit of the seven richest
democracies and for celebrations of the 200th anniversary of the
French Revolution.
   Under French law, the police and the interior minister, who has
responsibility for police affairs, are not required to give names or
other details of arrested persons.
   ``France has made progress in the field of terrorism,'' Joxe
declared. ``Thanks to the reinforced surveillance, which worked
well, the national police was able to make certain arrests.''
   He refused to give any further information. According to the
television report, the IRA members were in possession of false
identity papers and detonators when they were picked up on July 14.
   They were assembled in what was described as ``a rear base'' for
strikes against British army installations in West Germany, and were
not explicitly planning any action to disrupt the summit or the
anniversary celebration, the television said.
   Joxe said his services had received no indication of an
``individual threat'' concerning any of the 34 chiefs of state or
government who were in Paris over the weekend.
   Most of the visiting leaders had left Paris by midday Monday.
</TEXT>
