<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Leasing     07-17 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Leasing,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Firm Signs Deal to Lease Land in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese firm Monday granted an American camera
company the right to lease 60 million square feet to third parties
for 25 years.
   The Concord Camera Corp. signed the agreement in Hong Kong with
the Wan Kong Economic Development Corp. of Baoan County.
   Under the unusual agreement, Concord, based in Rahway, N.J., will
sub-lease manufacturing space and supply labor to corporations which
want to set up operations in China.
   Jack Benun, chairman of Concord, declined to say how much the
deal was worth. He also said his company had yet to determine how
much it would charge for space in the planned industrial park, to be
used mostly for light industry.
   The deal appears to be an attempt on China's part to regain the
confidence of Western investors following the bloody June 3-4
crackdown on a movement for freedom.
   Over the weekend, the official China News Service quoted a
Chinese official from Hainan province as saying China wanted to go
ahead with another project that also allows a foreign firm to lease
space to foreign investors. An official at the Hong Kong office of
that firm, Kumagai Gumi, the Japanese construction giant, said
Monday the firm had no comment on the Chinese report about the
Yongpu Port.
   In recent weeks, Hong Kong newspapers have said conservative
Chinese officials, whose have gained power as a result of the
crackdown, had criticized projects such as these. The officials were
quoted as saying the projects were tantamount to selling China's
sovereignty to foreigners.
   To increase confidence of potential investors, Benun said,
Concord was planning on incorporating an insurance company to
guarantee all assets in the area. He said his firm had yet to work
out the details.
   Benun said his Chinese partner would approve any investor as long
as they met the environmental guidelines of Baoan County.
   He said he secured the deal during a visit of top officials from
Baoan County to New Jersey several weeks ago. The basis of the deal,
he said, was Concord's six-year relationship with the county.
   Concord began producing cameras in Baoan in 1983 and has gone
from occupying 10,000 square feet of space to its current production
facilities of 240,000 square feet. It employs 2,000 Chinese.
   Benun said Concord makes about 4 million cameras a year, 55
percent of which are sold in the United States and 45 percent of
which are sold in Europe and Asia.
   Benun said he did not believe the recent turmoil in China would
affect his investment.
   ``It's our belief that with six years under our belt and with the
local authorities having always delivered what they promised there
should be no reason why anything should change,'' Benun said.
   He said the area _ fields and mountains located about 15{ miles
from Hong Kong _ would be ideal for Hong Kong investors.
   ``I've seen it and it's as far as the eye can see,'' he said.
``It's equal to 1,333 football fields.''
   He estimated an initial investment at about $600 million, but he
said his company was not obligated to put up the full amount.
   Concord had $18 million in sales in 1988 and cleared a profit of
2.3 million, Benun said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
