<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     07-17 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Soleil Back On Air With Regular Broadcasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haiti's most popular radio station
went back on the air Monday, resuming regular broadcasts that were
interrupted for three weeks by strikers who alleged a shift in the
station's political orientation.
   The director of the Roman Catholic station Radio Soleil, the Rev.
Arnaux Chery, hired a new staff to replace employees who were fired
or went on strike June 26.
   ``It makes me laugh when people say Radio Soleil is all
through,'' Chery told listeners Monday morning.
   Regular live broadcasts of religious and news programs had been
replaced by music and pre-recorded programs since the strike began.
Strikers had protested the firing of the program director and an
alleged conservative shift in orientation.
   The station has encouraged the poor to fight social injustice,
and it played a crucial role in the downfall of the Duvalier
dictatorship in 1986.
   But since April, Haiti's conservative Conference of Catholic
Bishops began firing station employees, including some of the most
popular reporters. It appointed Chery as station director in an
apparent move to check the influence of radical priests and
employees.
   In several declarations, the bishops accused the fired staffers
of insubordination and reaffirmed the goal of Radio Soleil to
evangelize through ``education, information, and entertainment.''
   The Haitian Press Club on July 5 protested the firing of news
editor Venel Ramarais and said the moves were ``part of a general
plan to destabilize the Haitian press.''
   During the last months of dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier's rule,
Radio Soleil was the only station broadcasting news. Duvalier fled
to exile in France in February 1986.
</TEXT>
