<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-17 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Blames Sri Lanka President For Lack of Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi blamed Sri
Lanka's president Monday for the stalemate on the withdrawal of
Indian troops from the island nation.
   Gandhi said President Ranasinghe Premadasa has not responded to
an Indian proposal for discussions on drawing up a timetable for the
departure of an estimated 40,000 troops.
   The troops were sent sent to disarm Tamil guerrillas under a 1987
peace plan designed to give the minority group limited autonomy.
   ``He has refused to talk,'' Gandhi said upon his return from a
six-day visit to Pakistan, the Soviet Union and France.
   An Indian government spokesman said that in Sri Lanka over the
weekend, Tamil guerrillas killed seven Indian soldiers and two other
clashes left three guerrillas and 10 civilians dead.
   Such clashes previously were routinely reported in Sri Lanka, but
Premadasa's government imposed censorship July 6, citing security
concerns that coincided with a growing estrangement with India.
   Premadasa has demanded that the Indian soldiers in his country
withdraw by July 29, the second anniversary of a peace pact that
dispatched the force.
   Gandhi has said such a quick withdrawal could spawn even more
violence in Sri Lanka. At least 9,000 people, including nearly 1,000
Indian soldiers, have been killed in the Tamil separatist war that
started in 1983 with attacks on the Sinhalese-dominated government
and Sinhalese civilians.
   The Indian troops were invited to Sri Lanka by Premadasa's
predecessor, President Junius R. Jayewardene, who signed the 1987
peace accord.
   Premadasa, who took office in January, opened talks this summer
with the most powerful Tamil guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eeelam. He subsequently called for a speedy Indian
withdrawal.
   Premadasa is Sinhalese, like 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people. Tamils, who comprise 18 percent, say they face Sinhalese
discrimination in jobs, education and use of the Sinhala language.
</TEXT>
