<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Guillen     07-17 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Guillen,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba's `National Poet' Dead At Age 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cubans on Monday filed past the body of
Nicolas Guillen, the country's national poet, as a two-day mourning
period began, according to Cuba's official news agency.
   Guillen, one of Latin America's best-known writers and the man
who introduced African and Latin musical rhythms into verse, died
Sunday after a long illness that resulted in the amputation last
month of his left leg, according to Prensa Latina. He was 87.
   The agency said he had also suffered from advanced
arteriosclerosis and Parkinson's disease.
   Guillen's body lay in state in Havana's Plaza of the Revolution
at the foot of a monument honoring Jose Marti, a famous Cuban poet
of the 19th century. A public funeral was scheduled for Tuesday.
   Guillen's work celebrated Cuba's multiracial and ethnic mix as
well as the 1959 communist revolution that brought Fidel Castro to
power. For more than 25 years he was director of Cuba's Union of
Writers and Artists and, at the time of his death, honorary
president.
   Prensa Latina said word of his death sent a ``shock wave''
through Cuba's people, many of whom know his verses by heart.
   In the prologue to a book of what he called ``mulatto'' poetry,
Guillen said: ``In these verses perhaps enter the same elements that
enter into the ethnic composition of Cuba, where we all are
mestizos. ... One day they will say: Cuban color. These poems
anticipate this day.''
   The passage was quoted by Prensa Latina in a dispatch monitored
in Mexico.
   Born in the city of Camaguey on July 10, 1902, Guillen studied
law in the eastern city and covered the Spanish civil war as a
magazine reporter. Later, he ran unsuccessfully for mayoral and
senate offices, first as a Popular Socialist.
   His first trip abroad, in 1937, was to Mexico, where he
participated in a conference sponsored by the Mexican Revolutionary
Writers and Artists League.
   From 1945 to 1948 he traveled in South America. Recollections of
the trip were included in works published in Buenos Aires and later.
   When Guillen tried to return from a trip to Chile in 1953,
dictator Fulgencio Batista refused to let him into the country and
he began a five-year exile.
   Among his best-known works are ``Themes of the Son,'' a reference
to the Cuban dance, the son, published in 1930, and ``The Dove of
the Popular Flight'' in 1958, which includes his elegies and is
considered a high point in Spanish poetry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
