<FIRST>r a AM-WarMuseum     07-17 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Museum,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red River Ranch Chosen as Site of War Museum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7,500-acre cotton farm once owned by movie star
John Wayne has been selected as the site for a $160 million military
museum and research complex, officials announced Monday.
   The complex will be on John Wayne's Red River Ranch, one of six
sites in Arizona that had competed for the project, said John R.
Radell, chairman of the Institute for the Study of American Wars.
   ``We chose the Casa Grande site because its central location
makes it easily accessible to residents and tourists from metro
Phoenix, Tucson, San Diego and Los Angeles,'' Radell said. ``In
addition, the direct transfer of 300 acres of land provides an
immediate financial beneift.''
   The land, worth $1 million to $2 million, is being donated by the
owners of the ranch, a partnership of Circle K chairman and chief
executive Karl Eller and developers William S. Lund and Timothy R.
Olson.
   Wayne, who died in 1979, had a ``direct, personal involvement''
in the operation of the ranch for about 20 years, Olson said. ``I'm
sure he would be very pleased about the plans to construct this
facility on the property.''
   No member of Wayne's family is involved in the ownership of the
land or the meseum project, he said.
   The first phase of the project, which will concentrate on the
Vietnam and Korean wars, will be completed in five years and is
expected to cost $70 million, Radell said.
   The overall project, which is to cover all American wars, will be
finished in about 20 years and will cost at least $160 million, he
said. So far, the group has raised only $60,000.
</TEXT>
