<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cellar Collapse,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Dead, Six Injured in Potato Cellar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLIANCE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The roof of a potato storage cellar
collapsed Monday, killing one man and injuring six others, police
said.
   A crew had been working to put in footing for supports for the
roof, composed of wooden beams covered with wire, plastic and bales
of straw, Police Chief Bob Jatczak said.
   Three workers, including the one who died, were trapped, he said.
   A group of workers used their hands to dig through the debris,
said Chris Toedtle, a mechanic at the Western Potato Storage Plant
who went to the scene.
   Toedtle estimated it took 10 minutes to find one trapped man and
perhaps 15 minutes longer to dig to where he was.
   Jatczak identified the dead man as William Burgess, 42, of
Alliance. He said Burgess was asyphixiated.
   The cellar was 300 feet long and nine feet from floor to the
ceiling, Jatczak said. Authorities do not know whether there was a
problem with the roof before the collapse, he said.
