<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NewHand     07-17 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Hand,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl Who Lost Hand to Bomb Gets Artificial One in Time for Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 5-year-old girl who lost her left hand
when a bomb exploded at a K mart store is learning to make necklaces
and hair bows with an artificial hand, her mother says.
   The high-tech prosthetic hand came as an early birthday present
for Erin Bower, who turns 6 on Tuesday.
   Erin received the electrically powered hand at Medical Center
Prosthetics in Houston last week and is participating in a
three-week training program to help her use it.
   ``I don't think she'll ever forget this birthday. It's because of
her hand. She loves her hand,'' Erin's mother, Maureen, said in a
telephone interview with The Indianapolis Star.
   Mrs. Bower planned a birthday celebration for Erin, who was
injured April 17 when a bomb went off as she picked up a package of
toothpaste at the K mart store in Castleton. The case remains under
investigation.
   Mrs. Bower said that when Erin put on her electrically powered
hand for the first time, she said, ``Mommy, I wish I could have my
other hand back.''
   ``I said, `Erin, I do, too,''' Mrs. Bower recalled. ``She said,
`It's too bad we just can't grow one.' I told her, `I wish we could,
but we can't.' Then Erin said, `Well, this arm isn't bad, I like
this arm, too.'
   Erin undergoes two hours of therapy a day to learn how to use the
hand, which is activated by nerve impulses in Erin's left arm. The
electrical current released by those muscles is picked up by
electrodes in the artificial hand, causing it to move as Erin
desires.
   Mrs. Bower said the therapy has been fun for her daughter. ``They
know she loves arts-and-crafty kind of things. She's made bead
necklaces. She's made hair bows, so she'll learn to tie. She's
played cards. They have a bow and arrow with a plunger at the end,
and she's learned to do that.''
   Mrs. Bower has been told it will be at least six months before
Erin starts using her artificial hand with the same confidence and
reflexes as the old one.
   She said the training program has also helped her daughter
mentally because she sees other children who have lost limbs.
   ``It helps Erin to put her own problems in perspective. And me,
too,'' said Mrs. Bower. ``What happened to Erin, we're kind of lucky
she's even here with us.''
</TEXT>
