<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Soviet     07-17 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Soviet,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway Says Soviets Failed to Report Mishap on Nuclear-powered Sub</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway said Monday the Soviet Union failed to
report a mishap on a nuclear-powered submarine and that its late
account did not respond to Norway's concern about radiation.
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov said Norwegian observers
were mistaken in reporting a fire aboard the submarine Sunday in the
Barents Sea east of Norway, according to the Soviet news agency Tass.
   It quoted Yazov as saying there was a short circuit in a battery
cell in the vessel's nuclear power system that forced the sub to
surface and switch to auxiliary power.
   ``Its diesel engines were fired and produced the exhaust,'' Yazov
said. ``There were no accidents or other emergencies.''
   There have been two accidents involving Soviet nuclear-powered
submarines near Norway's coast since April, with one claiming 42
lives, and the Norwegians were angry about the Soviet response in
the third incident.
   ``Whether there was smoke from a fire or from a diesel engine is
really beside the point,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman J. Bjoern
Kanavin. ``Our main concern was ... danger of radiation.
   ``The Soviets have indirectly confirmed that there was a problem
with the reactor, and in that kind of situation we want to be
informed.''
   Norway's NTB news agency said that after the Norwegian observers
reported trouble aboard the Alpha-class submarine Soviet suthorities
told the Foreign Ministry there was no threat of radiation.
Preliminary Norwegian tests showed no signs of contamination.
   Norwegian officials said the submarine on Monday reached a base
of the Soviets' Northern Fleet base on the Kola Pennisula under its
own power.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Arild Isegg said Norway accepted
Yazov's explanation on the origin of the smoke.
   ``It may sound plausible that the smoke came from a diesel motor
starting up. But we wonder why they didn't just tell us that from
the beginning,'' Isegg said.
   The Soviets initially denied there was anything wrong with any of
its submarines.
   Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg told reporters Sunday the
Soviet delay in advising Norway of the mishap ``is unacceptable.''
He also used that phrase when the the Soviets did not report a a
fire aboard an Echo II-class sub that was 70 miles off Norway's
coast in the Norwegian Sea. No casualties were reported in that
accident.
   A Soviet MIKE-class submarine caught fire and sank April 7 in the
Norwegian Sea and 42 crewmen perished.
   On Sunday a Norwegian vessel spotted smoke from a Soviet sub and
reported the vessel was 75 miles east of the Norwegian coast in the
Barents Sea and 30 miles north of Soviet territorial waters.
   Defense Ministry officials in Oslo said the smoke could indicate
a fire. Stoltenberg summoned the Soviet ambassador immediately to
show the seriousness with which Norway viewed the incident.
   Kanavin said: ``As a diplomatic question, I don't think this will
be pursued much further in the short term. But in the long term it
stresses the need for mutual warnings.''
   He said Norway is preparing a proposed treaty to present to the
Soviets that would require the two nations to inform each other of
military accidents. The Soviets recently signed such agreements with
the United States, Britain, France and West Germany.
   Kanavin said Norway was justified in its sharp reaction to the
initial Soviet silence.
   ``The submarine came up to the surface, it was being towed and
any observer would have to believe it was involved in an accident,''
he said. ``We had to react quickly ... especially since there have
recently been two extremely serious accidents of which we were not
warned.''
</TEXT>
