<FIRST>u w AM-StarWars-Experiment 1stLd-Writethru a0667 07-17 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Star Wars-Experiment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>SDI Test Successful, Budget Questions Remain, Officials Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Aspin comment, inserting 2 grafs after 14th graf
pvs, ``The real</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $60 million Star Wars experiment was praised
by its managers Monday as ``a major achievement'' in advancing plans
for a space-based missile shield but they said congressional budget
cuts raise questions about the system's future.
   The experiment, launched over White Sands Missile Range in New
Mexico on Thursday, tested how a neutral particle beam accelerator
would work in space. It was the first time such a beam of atomic
particles was fired into the heavens.
   The test known as BEAR _ or Beam Experiment Aboard Rocket _ was
considered a primary step in Pentagon's research into the lasers,
beam accelerators and other futuristic weapons which would be
designed to shoot down nuclear missiles fired at the United States
or its allies.
   The Strategic Defense Initiative, as Star Wars is formally
called, would make use of particle beams as a potential anti-missile
weapon. A beam would determine whether an object is a decoy or an
enemy warhead, and could be used to disable a missile.
   Last week's experiment involved lifting into space _ just for a
few minutes _ a neutral particle beam accelerator atop a small Aires
rocket. Before the rocket returned to Earth, the accelerator was
turned on and scientists collected data on how it worked and how the
particle beams moved.
   At a news conference Monday, the experiment's managers declared
the test a success, displaying a fuzzy black and white video tape of
the bright, pulsing beam as it emerged from the rocket.
   Air Force Col. Thomas Meyer, head of the SDI organization's
office of directed energy, said the experiment showed that the
complex equipment needed to produce the beam could be made in a
compact way, survive being shot into space, and function well.
   ``It is a major achievement, both in technology and
engineering,'' Meyer said.
   He said the experiment ``demonstrates the promise (of SDI) that
we have talked about all along.''
   In the laboratory, the equipment used for ground experiments of
the system would fill an average-size house, while the payload
aboard the rocket was about 24 feet in length and 3{ feet in
diameter.
   The director said the program's designers and scientists also
wanted to test how the beam acted in space and how space affected it.
   ``All ... experiment objectives were succesfully achieved,'' he
said.
   Meyer, asked how long it will take before the system could become
a full-fledged weapon in space, indicated that budget cuts are more
of a problem than technical difficulties.
   ``The real issue is, what is the funding for SDI?'' Meyer said.
``It's difficult for me to tell you when we'll have a weapon in
space without a clear definition of what our future funding is. And
it's continuing to be up in the air.''
   On Capitol Hill, Rep. Les Aspin, chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee, said a number of programs ``have yet to go in
terms of proving and particle beams is one.''
   ``I have not seen the briefing; my reaction is skepticism to say
that it's all fixed,'' he added.
   Meyer called the elements of last week's experiment
``on-the-shelf hardware,'' but that some engineering problems still
need to be worked out.
   ``It only takes the money to put it together ... and that's when
we'll get the weapon,'' he said.
   Army Lt. Col. Warren Higgins, a former manager of the BEAR
program also at the briefing, disputed the notion that the tests
were in conflict with the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty.
   Critics of the Star Wars program say the treaty puts severe
limits on testing and deployment of a space-based defense.
   ``We have a non-lethal beam, we had no target,'' Higgins said,
adding that the experiments have been cleared as
``treaty-compliant.''
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has battled congressional budget
cuts in the space-based anti-missile defense.
   The House Armed Services Committee has approved a $3.5 billion
budget for SDI, compared with the $4.6 billion President Bush
proposed. The Senate Armed Services Committee reduced the
administration's request to $4.5 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-17 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Region of Soviet Georgia Sealed Off After 14 Killed in Weekend Riots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of soldiers patrolled and sealed off the
Abkhazia region of Soviet Georgia, where 14 people were killed and
187 injured in a weekend of ethnic riots, officials reported Monday.
   Also in the Caucasus, daily demonstrations and scattered strikes
over the past three months have turned the ethnically troubled
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan into a tinderbox, the official
Tass news agency reported. It said troops were on patrol.
   Violence in Abkhazia began Saturday night when Abkhazians
surrounded a new university branch to protest its policy of offering
courses only in the Georgian language, said Vadim Bakatin, the
Soviet interior minister, and a spokesman for the Georgian Foreign
Ministry.
   He said the violence stemmed from demands for greater autonomy by
the Abkhazians, who are outnumbered by Georgians 240,000 to 94,000
in their own region.
   In a speech to the Soviet legislature reported by Tass, Bakatin
put the death toll at 13, including 10 killed Saturday night, two
who died later and one killed Sunday.
   An editor at the Georgian news agency Gruzinform, Otar Kapanadze,
said by telephone that another person died of injuries Monday,
raising the toll to 14. No violence was reported Monday.
   Bakatin said 3,000 police and soldiers from his ministry were
patrolling the region.
   Izvestia, the Soviet government newspaper, said ``all roads were
blockaded along the border'' of the Abkhazia region and disturbances
spread on Sunday to the western parts of the Georgian republic.
   Groups of Abkhazians and Georgians roamed the region during the
fighting Saturday and Sunday, attacking police stations and freeing
180 prisoners, Bakatin said. He said they seized 95 automatic
weapons and 100 handguns.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov told a news briefing
in Moscow the Communist Party might postpone a Central Committee
plenum set for late this month, at which the question of
nationalities is to be discussed. He said some policy papers still
were being drafted.
   Unrest in Sukhumi, capital of the Abkhazian Autonomous Republic
nearly 1,000 miles south of Moscow, disrupted food and water
supplies and transportation for tens of thousands of vactioners on
Black Sea beaches, Bakatin said.
   ``Transport workers intend to restore rail and air traffic to
schedule within the next few days,'' Tass reported.
   Bakatin and Roland Beridze, a spokesman for the Georgian Foreign
Ministry reached by telephone in Tbilisi, capital of Georgia, said
Abkhazians were angered by creation of a branch of Tbilisi State
University in Sukhumi that offered classes only in the Georgian
language.
   A university in Sukhumi offers most courses in Russian, with a
few in Georgian and Abkhazian, Beridze said.
   Earlier reports from Sukhumi said Abkhazians had been excluded
from the university, but Beridze said, ``If they wanted to study in
Georgian, there would be no limit on the number of Abkhazians.''
   Beridze, a Georgian, said violence began when ``Abkhazians
surrounded the building of the affiliate of Tbilisi State University
and didn't let applicants go in to take their entrance exams.''
   Abkhazians want their own republic, which would be the 16th in
the Soviet Union. Abkhazia, which has 535,000 people and 3,320
square miles, is in the Caucasus Mountains next to Turkey.
   In nearby Nagorno-Karabakh, Tass said, soldiers patrolled in an
attempt to prevent more of the sporadic violence between Armenians
and Azerbaijanis reported over the past three months. The region's
population is predominantly Armenian, but it was assigned to
neighboring Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Plans to hold an illegal demonstration in the regional capital of
Stepanakert on Friday fell through, but people gather every day
outside Communist Party headquarters and in the central square of
the town of Shusha, the agency reported.
   ``In other populated localities of Nagorno-Karabakh, explosive
situations develop when hundreds of people gather for rallies,'' it
said.
   Tass linked the ethnic violence to the deaths of eight children
killed Friday when a military helicopter crashed in the remote
settlement of Kelbadjar. Initial reports had not indicated the
victims were children or that the accident was related to the unrest.
   The Tass report said the children were watching the helicopter
take off and as it ``began ascending, it got caught in a
high-voltage power line and fell to the ground, killing eight of the
children. The tragedy could have not taken place if troops had not
had to be brought in to restrain the ethnic conflict.''
</TEXT>
