<FIRST>u w AM-NuclearProbe     07-17 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Probe,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Enter Weapons Plant to Widen Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators entered a nuclear weapons
plant in Ohio unannounced on Monday looking into allegations of
mishandling of hazardous wastes, the plant operator said.
   Agents of the Environmental Protection Agency's regional office
in Chicago arrived at the Feed Materials Production Center armed
with videotape cameras, said Pete Kelley, a spokesman for
Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio, which runs the plant.
   ``They just kind of showed up,'' he said in a telephone
interview. He said Westinghouse managers apparently were not told in
advance of the inspection, but added, ``There's no question that
what they're looking at is waste and waste management.''
   Later, Kelley said, ``They were asking to film, or make pictures,
of some areas they consider violations'' of federal regulations
governing waste management.
   EPA officials declined to comment beyond saying an investigation
was under way.
   The plant, situated at Fernald, about 18 miles north of
Cincinnati, is owned by the U.S. Energy Department. It processes
uranium for the department's nuclear weapons program, although last
week Westinghouse stopped production indefinitely. The company said
it wanted to focus more attention on waste cleanup.
   Also last week the EPA added the plant to its list of hazardous
waste sites requiring the most immediate cleanup. But as recently as
this past weekend the agency declined to say whether it was involved
in an investigation at Fernald.
   The EPA inquiry coincided with the start Monday of the Energy
Department's own inspection of Fernald. About 30 members of a
special team of department inspectors began two days of safety
briefings there before starting a wide-ranging inspection of all
operations, including waste management, said spokesman Will
Callicott.
   The Energy Department inspection is unrelated to the EPA's
action. Callicott said his department had been given no information
about the EPA's inquiry.
   At EPA headquarters in Washington, the agency issued a terse
statement that it was ``examining the situation at Fernald regarding
the allegations.'' Spokesman Dave Ryan said he could not describe
the allegations or make any other comment.
   EPA officials at the regional office in Chicago said they had no
immediate information about the Fernald probe.
   Kelley said the EPA team that arrived at Fernald on Monday said
it planned to show its videotapes at a House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee hearing Wednesday to be chaired by Rep. Thomas Luken,
D-Ohio, a critic of Fernald waste management.
   Fernald recently has become the focal point of various federal
probes, including an FBI preliminary investigation of unspecified
allegations of financial fraud.
   Kelley and Callicott said Monday the FBI had provided no
information about the fraud probe, which the bureau last week said
was related to the granting or execution of contracts at Fernald.
</TEXT>
