<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0653 07-17 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0653,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharon Says Israel Should `Eliminate' Arafat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 7th, `The government...' to ADD U.S. comment
on Sharon statement. Pickup 8th pvs, `Sharon, 61,...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, a former defense
minister who favors tougher action against the Palestinian uprising,
said Monday the Israelis must ``eliminate'' Yasser Arafat if they
want peace.
   In an earlier threat against the PLO chairman, Sharon said Jan.
28: ``There will be no peace as long as Arafat lives.''
   Israeli soldiers wounded 13 Palestinians during confrontations in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials
reported. At least 565 Palestinians and 36 Israelis have been killed
in the 19-month-old uprising in the occupied lands and more than
8,000 Palestinians have been wounded.
   Also Monday, the underground Palestinian Popular Army alleged
university professor Sari Nusseibeh, suggested as a possible
Palestinian negotiator with Israel, had embezzling funds from the
uprising and gone abroad with help from the Israeli security service.
   Sharon toured the Golan Heights, captured from Syria in 1967, and
renewed his demands for strong measures to end the Palestinian
revolt, which he called a ``different kind of war'' against Israel.
   ``We have to stop using slogans, dishing out promises and handing
out tranquilizers,'' he told reporters. ``The most important thing
is to restore law and order, to bring an end to terror and
violence.''
   The government must ``eliminate the heads of the terrorist
organizations, first of all Arafat,'' or there is no chance for
peace, he declared.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said he
had not seen the complete text of Sharon's remarks but added: ``I
point out that U.S. policy is to support a de-escalation of violence
in the Middle East, not an escalation of violence. If true, as
reported, these remarks would obviously not help in that process.''
   Sharon, 61, was defense minister and directed Israel's 1982
invasion of Lebanon with the stated aim of driving Palestine
Liberation Organization guerrillas out of the country.
   He resigned in 1983 after a commission found him indirectly
responsible for the massacre of Palestinians in Beirut refugee camps
by Lebanese Christian militia allies of Israel.
   Earlier this month, Sharon led a rebellion in the conservative
Likud bloc that forced Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to accept harsh
conditions for his plan of discussing peace with the Palestinians.
   In response, the center-left Labor Party threatened to leave the
Cabinet, creating a crisis in the coalition government.
   Motta Gur, a Labor minister, said Monday of Sharon's latest
statements: ``In talking, Sharon is most effective. As defense
minister, he led us to a most unnecessary war. Although we were
closer than ever to Arafat in Beirut, Sharon did not harm Arafat,
did not eliminate terrorism, did not resolve the Palestinian problem.
   ``One needs extraordinary audacity to make all these claims,''
Gur said in his comments on Israel radio.
   Palestinians in the occupied lands observed a general strike
Monday to protest alleged harsh conditions in Israeli prisons, where
the army says more than 8,600 Palestinians are held on suspicion of
security offenses.
   Soldiers blew up the homes of two Palestinian youths suspected of
fatally stabbing a 64-year-old Israeli building contractor, Zalman
Yosef Schlein, on Friday, the army reported.
   ``The two confessed to planning and carrying out the murder with
a nationalist motive,'' the army said in a statement about the
destruction of the houses in Gaza City's Shajaiya district
   Nahed Yusef Radwan Gundiah and Mohammed Mahmud Ayed Hamdiya also
said they belonged to groups associated with Fatah, the main PLO
guerrilla group led by Arafat, the army said.
   A leaflet issued by the Palestinian Popular Army, an umbrella
name for loosely organized squads of militants, declared that
Nusseibeh ``has secretly left the country with the help of the
Zionist Shin Bet after it was discovered large sums of money given
to him to be distributed to the popular armies and strike forces
were `lost' on the way.''
   It said the professor at Bir Zeit University ``adores fancy
parties and loves to conduct `Palestinian struggle' ... from fancy
hotels.''
   Nusseibeh was named in recent Israeli court documents as a
paymaster of the uprising, responsible for distributing PLO funds
and publishing uprising literature. He has not been charged.
   Friends said he was abroad on vacation and could not be reached
for comment.
</TEXT>
