<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     07-17 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Assails U.S. Attitude Toward Third World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Monday the
United States has an ``intransigent, hegemonic imperialist
attitude'' toward Latin America and the rest of the Third World.
   On the 10th anniversary of the day the late President Anastasio
Somoza fled Nicaragua, Ortega declared that Washington is not
interested in democracy so much as in ``domesticating the peoples of
Latin America and the Caribbean.''
   He addressed a symposium called ``Democracy and Revolution''
commemorating what the Sandinista government calls the Day of Joy _
July 17, 1979, when Somoza fled and his family's 42-year-old dynasty
ended. The guerrillas entered Managua two days later.
   Festivities for the revolution's 10th anniversary have been
low-key, and no heads of state are expected. Most of the observances
are cultural events.
   During a speech to the symposium that lasted just 10 minutes
short of two hours, Ortega mentioned prominent Americans who had not
accepted invitations to attend.
   Among them were former President Jimmy Carter, former U.N.
Ambassador Jeane J. Kirkpatrick and Elliot Abrams, former assistant
secretary of state for interAmerican affairs.
   Mrs. Kirkpatrick and Abrams, both of whom served President Ronald
Reagan, are known for strong opposition to the leftist Sandinistas
and support for the Contras, rebels who fought Ortega's government.
   Ortega said Nicaragua has more democracy than the United States
because the Sandinistas have increased literacy, lowered infant
mortality, improved health services and distributed land to
peasants. ``The revolution means the attainment of democracy,'' he
said.
   The president said more than 120,000 peasant families have
benefited from land distribution and the number of families in farm
cooperatives has grown to 76,715. Ortega said the number of labor
unions has increased from 163 before the revolution to 873,
representing 28 percent of workers.
   He criticized President Bush for concerning himself with ``the
problems of Hungary and Poland when he has so many problems in Latin
America.'' Ortega described Central America and the Caribbean as
``explosive territories.''
   Washington is not interested in helping solve the economic
problems of Latin America ``because there is no vision, there is an
underestimation of our nations'' and their problems, he said.
   Bush's visits to Poland and Hungary exhibited a lack of interest
in Latin America, Ortega said, and urged Latin Americans to unite in
demanding a change in the U.S. attitude toward their problems.
   ``It's better to collide with U.S. policy now ... than face
revolutionary struggles tomorrow,'' he said.
   Nicaragua, which has 3 million people, is in an economic crisis
that has made it one of the world's poorest nations, according to a
study by a U.S. economist hired by the Sandinista government. Sweden
financed the study.
   Last week, Ortega said he was willing to talk with the opposition
about more changes in electoral and media laws. The opposition has
said the new rules still gave the Sandinistas an unfair advantage.
   General elections are scheduled for Feb. 25.
</TEXT>
