<FIRST>r i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0638 07-17 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Meets With Solidarity Lawmakers on Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with meeting over, Jaruzelski still
undecided, Solidarity comments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
met with Solidarity lawmakers for six hours Monday and tried to
persuade them to support him for president.
   Authorities, as expected, announced that the National Assembly
will convene Wednesday to elect the president. Solidarity said its
senators and deputies will meet Tuesday to consider their votes.
   Jaruzelski has the support of his Communist Party and its ally,
the United Peasant Party, but he has said he doesn't want to be
elected without backing from the opposition.
   It remained unclear if Jaruzelski would allow his name to be
placed in nomination.
   The president is to be chosen by a majority of the National
Assembly _ the 100-member Senate and 460-member Sejm, meeting in a
joint session.
   Because of its overwhelming victories in the June 4 and June 18
elections Solidarity controls 259 of the 560 seats, or 46 percent.
   The legislators from the independent union movement asked scores
of questions at the closed-door meeting with Jaruzelski at the Sejm.
   A small contingent from the anti-communist Confederation for an
Independent Poland demonstrated outside the bulding. One of their
banners read, ``Jaruzelski Really Must Go.'' Police did not
interfere.
   Sen. Karol Modzelewski of Wroclaw, speaking for the Solidarity
lawmakers, told reporters the meeting was difficult ``for both sides
for several reasons. But there is no doubt it is an event of high
rank.''
   Jaruzelski told the Communist Party's Central Committee on June
30 that he did not want to run for president and recommended
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak for the position.
   But the party asked Jaruzelski to reconsider.
   ``It's still not clear what decision he will make,'' said
Modzelewski.
   The senator reported Jaruzelski said he would step down as
Communist Party leader if elected president. ``He said there is no
doubt that the two posts are not to be combined,'' Modzelewski said.
   Kiszczak also attended Monday's meeting, but Solidarity lawmakers
who participated said most of the discussion focused on Jaruzelski's
possible candidacy.
   They said Jaruzelski gave a speech and then answered questions.
Some indicated they did not like the general's responses.
   ``It's the same thing he's been saying for years,'' said Jozef
Slisz, leader of the independent farmers' union Rural Solidarity and
deputy speaker of the Senate.
   Under a revamped constitution, the president is to serve up to
two six-year terms and control Poland's military and foreign
relations. He also will nominate the prime minister who is to put
together the next government.
   On Friday, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said he would cooperate
with Jaruzelski if he is elected. He also said Poland's domestic and
international situation requires that the president come from within
the communist coalition.
   But Modzelewski said Walesa's statement did not mean the
Solidarity lawmakers were bound to vote for Jaruzelski.
   ``It is not a habit of parliamentary democracy that an opposition
votes the same way as the government majority,'' he said. But he
addeed that even if the opposition votes against Jaruzelski,
Monday's meeting was important as ``an attempt at opening a certain
dialogue, which is very difficult but necessary.''
   According to at least one parliamentary leader, there are fears
that a non-communist president would provoke a dangerous reaction
from hardliners inside Poland or from other countries in the Soviet
bloc.
   President Bush praised Jaruzelski during his trip to Poland July
8-11 and that is considered to have eased opposition to Jaruzelski,
who imposed martial law to crush Solidarity in December 1981.
   Solidarity was restored to legal status April 17.
   In a concession to the communist coalition Monday, members of the
Citizens Parliamentary Club _ as the Solidarity lawmakers call
themselves _ agreed the balloting for president should be open. The
opposition previously had favored a secret ballot.
   The communist coalition wants an open ballot to make it easier to
uphold party discipline.
</TEXT>
