<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Gingrich     07-17 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel to Consider Complaint Against Gingrich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee will consider
pursuing a complaint against Republican Whip Newt Gingrich, the
fiercely partisan conservative whose accusations sparked the panel's
investigation of Speaker Jim Wright, sources said Monday.
   The committee could vote Thursday, its first scheduled meeting
since Wright resigned from the House last month, to begin a
preliminary inquiry into Gingrich's conduct. The inquiry, according
to the committee source, will center on a partnership formed to
promote a book written by the Georgia lawmaker, his wife and a third
person, sources said.
   ``We'll probably be taking up Gingrich and not anything else,''
said one committee source, insisting on anonymity.
   The ranking Republican on the committee, Rep. John T. Myers of
Indiana, said he presumed the Gingrich case would be on the agenda
because ``it's one of the things we have not dealt with.''
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., filed a 10-count complaint in April
accusing Gingrich of violating several House rules by the formation
of the COS Limited Partnership. Twenty-one investors put up $5,000
each in an unusual arrangement to promote the book, ``Window of
Opportunity.''
   Gingrich has denied any wrongdoing in the book promotion.
Spokeswoman Sheila Ward said Gingrich was aware of the committee
meeting but has received no formal notification of any action on
Alexander's complaint.
   According to the complaint, the investors' money could be
construed as income to Gingrich, a violation of limitations on
outside earnings applicable to House members.
   The complaint also said the more than $100,000 raised could
constitute a gift to Gingrich from those with a direct interest in
legislation. House rules prohibit members from keeping gifts of more
than $100 from anyone with such a direct interest.
   Alexander alleges the money could be considered campaign
contributions, subject to reporting obligations and restrictions
under campaign financing laws. If so, Alexander said, the investment
money may have exceeded contribution limits and may not have been
properly reported.
   Gingrich said in April that none of the investors received
``unusual or extraordinary personal help'' from him in their
dealings with the federal government. But he acknowledged that some
of the investors had a direct interest in legislation and that he
had handled routine requests from some of them.
   He contended that the $5,000 each investor gave to the
partnership does not constitute a gift.
   Under rules of the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct,
the formal name of the ethics committee, the panel ``shall conduct a
preliminary inquiry'' if members believe a complaint merits further
action. Gingrich would have an opportunity to respond to the
allegations.
   Gingrich initiated the investigation that led to the panel
charging Wright with 69 rules violations. That led to the Texas
Democrat's decision to give up his speakership and resign from the
House.
   Wright's alleged violations including charges that bulk sales of
a book he wrote violated outside earning limits and that he received
gifts from a business associate with a direct interest in
legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
