<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ReflaggingLawsuit     07-17 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reflagging Lawsuit,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wage Suit Filed For Crewmen of Reflagged Tankers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law firm representing U.S. maritime unions
said Monday it had filed a lawsuit accusing operators of the 11
reflagged Kuwait tankers in the Persian Gulf of paying crew members
less than the legal minimum wage.
   Plaintiffs in the suit in U.S. District Court in Dover, Del. are
18 Filipino seamen who, the suit charged, were paid as little as $2
per hour when they should have been getting $3.35.
   The law firm of Quasha, Wessley and Schneider represents the
seamen and the several unions in the AFL-CIO representing seamen,
officers and longshoremen are not parties to the case directly,
though the law firm announced its action in the name of the AFL-CIO
Maritime Committee.
   Spokeswoman Anne Comfort said the firm expects substantially all
crew members of the tankers to join as plaintiffs, about 500 people.
   The Kuwaiti government was permitted to reregister the ships in
the United States in 1987. This made the vessels eligible for U.S
military protection without the complication of treaties or other
government-to-government agreements during the Iran-Iraq war, when
Iranian forces were attacking shipping to and from Kuwait, which
supported Iraq, and Iraqi forces were attacking Iran's tanker
traffic.
   The United States was anxious to keep Kuwait from carrying out a
threat to turn to the Soviet Union for military help.
   At the peak of the effort, the U.S. Navy had 27 warships in the
Gulf. Other western naval forces brought the total to more than 80.
   With the end of the war, those forces were reduced, the U.S.
contingent dropping to 10 in April of this year.
   Kuwait transferred six of the tankers back to its own flag in
April, May and June of this year, but five still were flying the
Stars and Stripes.
   At the request of the Defense Department, the Coast Guard waived
most of the requirement that all crew members aboard U.S.-flagged
vessels be U.S. citizens., leaving only the master and the radio
operator subject to the requirement.
   But the AFI-CIO Maritime Committee said no waiver was granted
from U.S. laws requiring payment of at least $3.35 per hour.
   An inspection team from the International Transport Workers
Federation, an international grouping of union, discovered on
boarding three of the 11 tankers in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, in
May that seamen were paid less than $2 per hour.
   The AFL-CIO announcement quoted Gert-jan Harmsen, one of the
Rotterdam inspectors, as saying crewmen were ``reluctant to complain
for fear of being thrown off the ship or blacklisted in the future.
Some crewmen were even threatened with arrest and jail if they
complained to authorities.''
   Defendants in the suit were Chesapeake Shipping Inc. of Dover,
Del., the registered owner of the ships; Gleneagle Ship Management
Co. of Houston; NAESS Inc., a Manila-based ship crewing agency; and
Santa Fe International, a subsidiary of Kuwait Petroleum Corp., the
Kuwaiti-government owned corporation that is the actual owner of the
ships. Santa Fe employs a majority of the directors of Chesapeake
Shipping, which was formed in 1987 to handle the reflagging.
   At Gleneagle in Houston, a woman answering the telephone said all
executives who could answer questions were in a meeting.
</TEXT>
