<FIRST>u a AM-DuckySentence 1stLd-Writethru a0641 07-17 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ducky Sentence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Cries Fowl Over Sentence to Animal Farm for Duck's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CLARIFY that Ehrnfelt is mayor of Strongsville;
SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT city's name to Strongsville, sted Strongville;
SUBS 12th graf, `Ehrnfelt fined ...,' to ADD background on farm; Pekin
in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH OLMSTED, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor called it murder most fowl
and ordered the defendant to do time on a petting farm. Robert
Yarsky thinks the sentence is daffy but he hasn't tried to duck it.
   Yarsky, 20, of Strongsville, has been baling hay and doing other
chores at a petting farm as part of his court-ordered community
sentence for running over Danny, a beloved neighborhood duck, in
January.
   Strongsville Mayor Walter Ehrnfelt called it ``premeditated
murder of Danny the Duck.'' Joseph and Shirley Spak, owners of the
popular Pekin duck, received dozens of cards, letters and flowers
after Danny's death.
   Yarsky says he could not get police or the mayor to believe
Danny's demise was an accident. ``I figured I would get a fine, but
I didn't think it would be anything outrageous like this,'' he said
last week when interviewed at the Olmsted Township farm, where he
must work two days a week for two months.
   Yarsky's flap with the law began Jan. 23, when he and three
friends were driving down a residential street in Strongsville, a
city of 36,000 in northeast Ohio.
   ``There was a stop sign, and I guess I was paying more attention
to the stop sign than anything,'' Yarsky said. ``My friends shouted,
but I really didn't see anything except for kind of a little white
flash out of the corner of my eye, and I swerved the car. Then I hit
it.
   ``I remember there was this guy in a van who saw it happen, and
he charged at me. So I left the scene, because I didn't know what
that guy was going to do. Later that evening, the police arrested
me. They said they had three witnesses, but I've always said I
didn't do it intentionally.''
   Ehrnfelt said he got a much different impression based on police
accounts and Yarsky's lack of remorse in his appearance in mayor's
court Feb. 9. Yarsky pleaded no contest to the second-degree
misdemeanor charge of killing an animal.
   ``I don't think young people can go through life with that kind
of attitude, whether the life be animal or person,'' the mayor said.
   ``This duck had crossed the road there for maybe about nine
years. It would actually come up to the roadway and hesitate and
then start across the road and then swim in a little creek that is
right next to the fire station,'' said Ehrnfelt. ``Then he would
travel back.
   ``Everyone knew this duck, and cars would stop for him and let
him cross the road. Even school buses would stop if he was going
across the road. Everyone gave him necessary consideration, with the
exception of Mr. Yarsky.''
   Ehrnfelt fined Yarsky $750, assigned $28 in court costs and
suspended a 90-day jail sentence pending completion of community
service at Burnette's Farm and Education Center, which is owned by
Jim Burnette. Yarsky also has to buy a new duck for the Spaks.
   Yarsky, who recently took a job with a storage company, said he
didn't know what to expect when he began his sentence at the pet
farm in June. After about six working visits, he said he was
enjoying the experience.
   ``It's not a bad place, and I like it, but I've always had
compassion for animals,'' Yarsky said. ``My uncle lived on a farm,
and I've been around animals all my life. But the mayor gets the
idea I don't have compassion for animals, so I guess that's why he
sentenced me here.''
</TEXT>
