<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     07-17 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Accuses UN of `Negligence' in Peace Talks; Iraq Blames Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq blamed each other Monday for
the deadlock in peace talks that began after the Aug. 20 cease-fire
that halted their 8-year-old war.
   Iran also said the United Nations was guilty of ``negligence and
complacency,'' and had failed to ensure a lasting peace.
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq said the Iranians had stalled
the peace talks and used the deadlock to ``blackmail the region and
threaten its security and stability.''
   U.N.-mediated peace talks began Aug. 25, five days after the
truce, and have gone nowhere.
   In a separate development, Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of Iran's
parliament and favorite in its July 28 presidential election, said
relations with the West could improve if approached on the basis of
equality, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   A Foreign Ministry statement for the anniversary of Iran's
acceptance of U.N. Security Council Resolution 598 on July 18, 1988,
said the council had promised to implement the resolution, which
also is a peace plan.
   It said the commitment remained unfulfilled after a year.
   The statement, broadcast by Tehran radio, said the Security
Council's ``negligence'' was ``not only a violation of the
resolution by its authors, but also a violation of the duty of
maintaining international peace and security.''
   After several military defeats in the last weeks of fighting,
Iran suddenly accepted the year-old truce resolution. Iraq had
declared soon after passage that it would accept the resolution if
Iran did the same.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the late Iranian patriarch, said
accepting the cease-fire was ``more deadly to me than poison.''
   Other provisions of the U.N. resolution include withdrawal to
prewar boundaries, prisoner exchange, peace negotiations and an
impartial commission to assess blame for the war.
   A fourth round of peace talks was held in May and no further
meetings have been scheduled.
   Iran's statement Monday said Iraq had refused to implement ``the
most important instruction of the resolution'' _ withdrawal to
recognized international borders _ and had ``used every possible
means to avoid honoring that commitment,'' the radio said.
   Iraqi soldiers still occupy about 380 square miles of Iranian
territory. Iran insists they leave before peace talks proceed.
   Iraq rejects a 1975 treaty drawing part of the border down the
middle of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, its only outlet to the sea,
and insists the border be altered to give it all of Shatt.
   President Hussein of Iraq, in an address marking the 21st
anniversary of his Baath Arab Socialist Party's rise to power, said
``this no-war, no-peace situation'' could not continue.
   ``It's been nearly a year and they are still refusing to end the
plight of war prisoners,'' he said. Earlier this year, Hussein
suggested the more than 100,000 prisoners held by both sides be
exchanged under a new agreement separate from the U.N. resolution.
   In an interview with the Iranian newspaper Jomhuri Islami,
Rafsanjani said Iran would would give priority to better relations
with Third World nations and reiterated the desire for good
relations with neighboring countries, IRNA reported.
   It quoted Rafsanjani, who is considered relatively moderate by
Iranian standards, as saying of the West: ``If they deal with us on
the basis of equal terms and do not wish to impose anything on the
revolution, we will deal with them on equal terms.''
   Iran needs Western money and technology to rebuild from the war.
Western analysts estimate reconstruction will cost at least $200
billion.
</TEXT>
