<FIRST>r a AM-FDABribery     07-17 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA Bribery,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pharmaceutical Exec Pleads Guilty to Bribing FDA Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former executive of a pharmaceutical company
pleaded guilty Monday to bribing two former U.S. Food and Drug
Administration chemists in exchange for approval of generic drug
applications submitted by his company.
   It was the latest in a series of charges and guilty pleas
resulting from an investigation into allegations that FDA chemists
accepted cash in exchange for inside information and favorable
treatment toward drug applications from generic drug manufacturers.
   Ashok Patel, 49, of Upper Saddle River, N.J., a former senior
vice president of Par Pharmaceutical Inc., faces up to two years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
   U.S. Attorney Breckinridge L. Willcox also announced Monday that
Par Pharmaceutical, based in Spring Valley, N.Y., and a subsidiary,
Quad Pharmaceuticals Inc., were charged with one count each of
bribery.
   The companies, through their executives, allegedly gave former
FDA supervisor Charles Y. Chang about $2,900 between July 1987 and
April 1988. If convicted, each company faces fines totaling $500,000.
   Chang, 47, of Potomac, Md., has already pleaded guilty to two
racketeering charges and could be sentenced to up to 10 years in
prison and fined $500,000.
   So far, charges have been filed against three FDA employees and
three pharmaceutical companies. In addition to Chang, another former
FDA chemist and two officials of drug companies in Colorado and New
York have either pleaded guilty or agreed to do so.
   Willcox said Patel has been cooperating with investigators for
several months. He said the investigation is continuing and
additional charges are expected.
</TEXT>
