<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AfricanIvory 350   07-17 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-African Ivory, 350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostropovich to Play to Save Elephants; Japan Targeted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mstislav Rostropovich, one of the world's
leading cellists, said Monday he would play a benefit recital to
help raise money to save the African elephant.
   Rostropovich, music director of Washington's National Symphyony
Orchestra, announced the Sept. 18 performance at a news conference
sponsored by conservation groups trying to draw attention to what
they called a possible ``elephant holocaust.''
   ``When I see chairs and tables made with legs of ivory, I think,
how inhuman, how barbaric,'' Rostropovich said.
   Killing for ivory has reduced the African elephant population
from 1.3 million to an estimated 550,000 in the past 10 years, said
Diana E. McMeekin, vice president of the African Wildlife Federation.
   The ivory is harvested after the elephants are killed.
   Sponsors of the concert at Washington's Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts predicted it would net at least $400,000, all to be
used for elephant conservation projects and investigation into the
network of elephant-poaching and ivory trading being outlawed by
many countries.
   Christine Stevens, president of the Washington-based Animal
Welfare Institute, described the poachers as ``totally evil but
wonderfully well-organized.''
   She predicted a fierce battle at the October meeting in
Switzerland of the 102-nation Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species ``to ensure there are no weakening'' moves
against a proposed total ban on ivory imports.
   Japan, the major ivory buyer, and Botswana, South Africa and
Zimbabwe, the major suppliers, want reservations that would allow
them to trade among themselves.
   Many African nations, led by Kenya and Tanzania, support
curtailing the ivory trade.
   Japan accounts for 40 percent of world ivory consumption and the
United States 15 percent. Japanese use carved ivory for personal
signature stamps as well as jewelry.
   In June, Japan banned ivory imports but continues to permit
shipments certified by the countries of origin. Ms. Stevens said
such a loophole would mean that ``all of the elephants in all of
Africa will be at risk.''
   President Bush issued an executive order June 5 banning U.S.
import of ivory from all countries. The West European Community has
taken similar steps.
</TEXT>
