<FIRST>r a AM-Stealth-Scene     07-17 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth-Scene,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeoff Gives Stealth Watchers Rush of Pride and Patriotism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stealth Test Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patriotism rippled through a crowd of
thousands who gathered among the tumbleweeds outside a tightly
guarded Air Force plant to watch Monday's maiden flight of the B-2
stealth bomber.
   ``Great God,'' exclaimed Les Holland as the bat-winged plane
soared into the air from Air Force Plant 42 in the Mojave Desert,
where spectators had parked motor homes, trucks, sports cars and
motorcycles.
   Holland was one of the many employees of Northrop Corp., the
builder of the craft that already has cost about $22.4 billion in
development, who woke up early to watch the flight.
   The four-engine flying wing took off from a runway at Plant 42,
then made what appeared to be a perfect landing at nearby Edwards
Air Force Base.
   Air Force Capt. Tess Taft unfurled an American flag and ``The
Star Spangled Banner'' was sung on the runway by Alis Clausen,
employee of a local cable television station.
   Among the thousands outside the plant's perimeter, aviation
enthusiast John MacWhirter, a former Marine aviator in F-4 Phantoms,
gave play-by-play announcements about the takeoff over a public
address system on his truck.
   ``There was an emotional ripple, and I shouted `God bless
President Ronald Reagan,''' he said. ``It was ecstasy.'' Reagan was
a strong supporter of the B-2.
   MacWhirter had been waiting for the B-2's first flight since
January, rising before dawn on many days hoping to get a glimpse of
the craft that only recently was shown to the public.
   Others were equally enthusiastic.
   ``This was a big day for all of us,'' said George Adelmann, who
joined MacWhirter on the early morning vigils.
   ``I'm shaking. My legs are shaking. It was going right over my
head,'' said Shari Cutler of Lake Los Angeles, who brought her four
children.
   ``It was beautiful. I know the pilot's wife and I can never get a
word out of her about the stealth,'' said Barbara Resterfeld of
Lancaster.
   ``It gave me goose bumps,'' said Nancy Moore of Lancaster.
</TEXT>
