<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-17 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Roll Through Eastern Oklahoma, Western Arkansas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms spawning torrential rains and high winds
rolled through much of eastern Oklahoma and parts of western
Arkansas on Monday, collapsing a roof at a Tulsa airport hotel and
leaving thousands without power.
   Winds howled to 90 mph near Peggs and gusted to more than 80 mph
near Bartlesville, Okla.Sections of eastern Oklahoma received 3 to 5
inches of rain, prompting flash flood watches.
   A 15- by 20-foot section of a lobby roof at the Sheraton Airport
Hotel in Tulsa collapsed during the Monday morning downpour,
officials said. Hotel patrons, who saw the ceiling bulging downward
before it collapsed, left the area.
   The storms in Tulsa also interrupted power for up to 20,000
utility customers.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell over most of the Florida
Peninsula. In Boynton Beach, thunderstorm-generated winds knocked
down trees and power lines.
   Showers and thunderstorms with heavy rain fell over a large part
of central and east central North Dakota.
   Elsewhere, rain and thunderstorms continued over much of eastern
North Carolina and parts of eastern South Carolina. A few showers
also lingered over New England; thunderstorms were reported over
parts of northern Wisconsin.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 2\ inches at Fort Smith, Ark.; 1{ inches at Fayetteville,
N.C.; 1\ inches at Homestead, Fla.; and 1 inch at Alexandria, La.,
Fayetteville, Ark., and Joplin, Mo.
   Record-setting heat continued over west Texas; the temperature in
Midland soared to 107 degrees, beating the previous record of 103
degrees set in 1981. San Angelo tied its record high of 104 degrees
set in 1978.
   The low for the Lower 48 states Monday morning was 31 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Worcester, Mass., to 105 degrees at Phoenix.
   The national weather forecast for Tuesday called for scattered
showers and thunderstorms over the Mississippi Valley and from
Florida to southern Georgia, the eastern Carolinas and southeast
Virginia; showers and thunderstorms from southern Minnesota to
Missouri and central Mississippi and over most of Florida.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 70s over most of New
England, Iowa and Washington state; over 100 degrees from southeast
Arizona to southwest and central Texas and in the interior valleys
of central and Southern California; near 110 degrees in the desert
Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
