<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-India 1stLd-Writethru   07-17 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-India, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0654,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Refuses to Sell Missile-Testing Device to India</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs comment from embassy statement, background</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has refused to sell
India a device for testing missiles, State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher said Monday.
   ``It could conceivably contribute to the development of further
ballistic missiles,'' Boucher told reporters.
   The device is called CAVCTS, for combined acceleration vibration
climatic test system.
   Boucher said he was not aware of any protest from the Indian
government against the U.S. denial of an export license for the
device.
   But the Indian Embassy said later the refusal was unjustified
since India had already received a U.S. license to purchase the
equipment in 1985, and the device was usable only for testing
short-range missile launchers.
   An Embassy statement said the denial was based on ``alleged
concern arising out of the Missile Technology Control Regime'' that
the United States concluded in 1987. The agreement with France,
Britain, the Soviet Union, Japan and several other countries, aimed
to curb proliferation of missile technology in the Third World.
   However, the Embassy said, ``this piece of equipment is only
relevant for short-range launchers and does not attract MTCR
concern.''
   The Embassy did not explain the delay in buying the $1.2 million
device, which allowed the original license to expire.
   India has successfully tested its ``Agni'' surface-to-surface
ballistic missile, which Western experts speculated could carry a
nuclear warhead. But the Indian government continues to renounce
nuclear arms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
