<FIRST>r i AM-Evangelicals 1stLd-Writethru   07-17 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evangelicals, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0630,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large-Scale Crusades Ineffective, Evangelical Conference Told</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with one graf to CLARIFY that speaker believes rallies
are ineffective in competing with rival religions. Pick up 2nd pvs, `The
Rev....' with minor editing thereafter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Large rallies are ineffective in
spreading Christianity to members of rival faiths, and the focus
instead should be on low-profile dialogue, delegates to a worldwide
evangelical conference were told Monday.
   The Rev. Martin Alphonse, a Methodist minister from Madras,
India, said at the Lausanne II conference that such dialogue ``will
not be seen as a threat to or an open assault on other faiths.
   ``By playing a low key, it will still be able to permeate the
various spheres of peoples of other faiths in a quiet but firm
way,'' said Alphonse, who lives in a predominantly Hindu city.
   The conference, which opened last Tuesday, has brought together
about 4,200 evangelical Christians from more than 160 countries to
devise ways to spread the Christian religion worldwide by the end of
the century.
   Alphonse told the delegates that they face a seemingly
insurmountable task in reaching 900 million Moslems, 690 million
Hindus, 320 million Buddhists and others by the year 2000.
   ``We are not thinking about organized conventions and
evangelistic crusades for thousands of them exclusively in one
place,'' he said. ``Such strategy may not simply work.
   ``Rather we are thinking about world evangelization by local
evangelization, by reaching a few here and a few there, thus
eventually making this gospel proliferate everywhere,'' he said.
   Colin Chapman, a lecturer in religion at Trinity University in
Bristol, England, said such quiet dialogue paralleled the style of
preaching used by Jesus and the apostles when dealing with Jews and
members of other religions in the Roman Empire.
   Chapman said it is important for evangelicals to avoid insulting
other faiths even if they find the religions erroneous and
incomplete.
   The Lausanne committee, which organized the conference, is
chaired by the Rev. Leighton Ford, a Canadian who lives in North
Carolina and is the brother-in-law of American evangelist Billy
Graham.
   Graham has used large-scale rallies, or crusades, as his
principal method for evangelizing for nearly 40 years. Graham was to
have addressed the opening session of the conference, which ends
Thursday, but he canceled because of a schedule conflict.
   Alphonse said Christianity faced resistance from other religions
because of cultural conflict, the faith's association with European
colonialism, and the aggressive activities of early Christian
missionaries.
   He said other religious groups had expected a decline in
missionary activity after the collapse of European empires after
World War II.
   ``On the contrary, most of the national churches have revived the
traditional evangelistic work and some have become much more
vigorous in it than ever before,'' he said. ``The number of converts
from other faiths to Christianity has continued to increase in
several nations in the post-colonial era and in unprecedented
measure in a few cases.''
   No figures were immediately available.
   He said Islam had attempted to resist Christian encroachments by
taking on a political aspect and had become established as a state
religion in Pakistan, Malaysia, Brunei and nations of the Middle
East.
</TEXT>
