<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TimberCompromise     07-17 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Timber Compromise,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service, Industry Call Environmentalist Plan Unworkable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the timber industry and the Forest Service
on Monday rejected a proposal offered by environmentalists aimed at
ending the fight over logging in the ancient forests of the Pacific
Northwest.
   The rejections came as lawmakers from the region sought to craft
a legislative compromise that would ensure an adequate short-term
supply of logs to keep the region's mills operating over the next 15
months and protect the old-growth forests that are prime habitat for
the rare northern spotted owl.
   The lawmakers had hoped to attach the compromise to the Interior
Department appropriations bill when it came before a Senate
appropriations subcommittee Tuesday, but the meeting has been put
off until later in the week for unrelated reasons.
   The lawmakers have made clear they will act whether or not the
environmentalists and the industry agree. The spending bill will
include funds for the Forest Service and the Bureau of Land
Management.
   Industry representatives said the environmentalists' proposal
would be ``technically infeasible'' because its restrictions on
old-growth logging would make it impossible to meet the timber sales
levels it envisions.
   ``This is a non-starter _ an offer of terms of surrender,'' Mark
Rey, a vice president of the National Forest Products Association,
said at a news conference, adding that environmentalists had just
repackaged their previous demands.
   The environmentalists proposal would reduce the harvest over the
next 15 months to a level 400 million board feet below that of the
earlier plan and Rey said that would result in the loss of 7,000
jobs, $171 million in payrolls and $162 million in government
revenue at all levels.
   In a letter to Northwest lawmakers, F. Dale Robertson, Forest
Service Chief, said the environmentalist proposal would be
``unworkable. The timber targets are achievable with protection of
significant old-growth stands, but not under the conditions and
criteria proposed.''
   The restrictions on old-growth logging proposed by the
environmentalists would allow harvesting in mostly younger stands
and ``such areas are not capable of providing the intended sales
volume.''
   The federal government has been prevented from selling many older
stands to timber companies as a result of court injunctions won by
environmental groups, who argued the stands may be the last
remaining habitat of the spotted owl.
   Environmentalists said that despite the rejections, they were
still willing to negotiate.
   ``We think the industry ought to be doing a little more in terms
of coming up with their own proposals rather than taking cheap shots
at ours,'' said Rich Hoppe, a spokesman for the Wilderness Society.
   Hoppe said that environmentalists were a little surprised at the
Forest Service's comments as their plan was based on numbers
supplied by the agency.
</TEXT>
