<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Rebels     07-17 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Rebels,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 50 Youths Die In Rebel Crackdown, Paper Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 youths died of suffocation
after being crammed into unused train cars for three days in a
military crackdown on rebels, a government-owned newspaper reported
Monday.
   New Vision said the dead were among 276 youths rounded up on July
10 from villages around Kumi, about 150 miles northeast of Kampala
and a region believed to be a major hideout for Uganda People's Army
rebels.
   New Vision said government soldiers locked the youths in old
train coaches where they were kept for three days, and more than 50
of them died of suffocation.
   The English-language daily said the government planned to send a
military intelligence team to Kumi to investigate the report. It did
not say why youths were targeted in the roundup.
   The London-based Amnesty International has accused Uganda's
National Resistance Army of human rights violations including rape,
torture, murder and illegal detention of civilians and says such
incidents appear to be on the increase.
   But the group has credited President Yoweri Museveni with
bringing an ``immediate end to the gross human rights violations
inflicted by previous governments.''
   Museveni came to power in 1986 after a five-year guerrilla war
and has been fighting several rebel groups opposed to his government
in northern and eastern Uganda.
   In the northern Uganda town of Gulu, rebels Thursday abducted 40
people, killed one, robbed police and military personnel of their
weapons, and stole drugs from the hospital, New Vision reported.
   Two nurses were among the captives who were made to carry the
rebels' loot, said the newspaper.
   The rebels were believed to be members of the Holy Spirit
Movement, which has been harrassing and torturing civilians and
looting the area around Gulu since the beginning of the year.
</TEXT>
