<FIRST>r a AM-PTLTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0675 07-17 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Agent Says Taggarts Used $290,000 In PTL Funds in 1985</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with afternoon testimony. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Dortch, Jim Bakker's former top
deputy, and not former Bakker aides David and James Taggart actually
ran PTL during its heyday, defense witnesses testified Monday.
   PTL founder Bakker ``had agreed to turn the reins over to
Dortch,'' Charlotte attorney John York testified. ``In my
experience, David (Taggart) was never a power figure. He was just a
mouthpiece for Jim.''
   York, a member of the law firm that served as PTL's general
counsel, was one of the first witnesses called by defense attorneys
for the Taggart brothers. The Taggarts are charged with evading
$487,000 in income taxes during their years at PTL.
   Prosecutors say the two men diverted $1.1 million in ministry
funds to their own use.
   York and the former assistant secretary to the PTL board said
Dortch wielded much of the authority at PTL.
   Dortch, York said, once ordered him to leave a PTL board meeting
just before bonuses for ministry executives were discussed.
   Sylvia Watson, who served as the assistant board secretary in the
early 1980s, said she resigned in 1982 after Dortch ordered her to
stop writing into the minutes who made the motion to pay bonuses.
   York said he once met with David Taggart and outside accountants
who were auditing PTL when Taggart explained that he took large cash
advances on ministry credit cards because he served as the ``bank''
when the Bakkers traveled.
   Don Hardister, who was Bakker's bodyguard for seven years,
testified that David Taggart once carried $25,000 in a briefcase on
a trip with the Bakkers.
   ``You've got to realize there were 10 to 15 people who were
getting expenses from that money,'' said Hardister, one of seven
defense witnesses to testify Monday afternoon. ``I got $5,000 to
$7,000 of that amount for my staff.''
   Bakker, Hardister said, lived an opulent lifestyle and insisted
on carrying $1,000 in cash in his billfold at all times. He said it
was Taggart's responsibility to make sure Bakker always had 10 $100
bills.
   The prosecution's final witness, Internal Revenue Service agent
Charles Mauney, said David and James Taggart used $150,000 in cash
advances on PTL credit cards and $140,000 in ministry checks for
their personal expenses in 1985.
   Mauney said the government did not challenge an additional
$320,000 in questionable PTL payments made to the brothers in 1984
and 1985.
   For 1984, Mauney testified, the Taggarts did not pay any taxes on
$48,000 in additional income. The goverment decided not to challenge
$208,000 on cash advances on PTL credit cards, PTL checks used to
pay off the defendants' personal credit card accounts and the use of
PTL credit cards to purchase personal items.
   Mauney said the Taggarts had $523,354 in unreported taxable
income in 1986 and $260,000 in 1987.
   He testified the total unreported taxable income for the two
brother was $1.2 million ffrom 1984 to 1987. David Taggart owed
$264,911 in back taxes; James Taggart owed $260,576.
   The Taggart brothers joined PTL in the late 1970s as piano
players. Within a few years, David Taggart, 32, was promoted to
Bakker's top personal aide and James Taggart, 35, became PTL's
interior decorator.
   Both were fired when Jerry Falwell took over at the television
ministry following Bakker's resignation in March 1987 following
revelations of the Jessica Hahn sex-and-money scandal.
   Beginning July 5, testimony from dozens of New York shopkeepers
and friends of the Taggarts showed the defendants went on spending
sprees in the most exclusive stores in New York, Florida, California
and Europe.
   Prosecutors charge the Taggarts also used money donated to the
tax-exempt ministry to buy a $640,000 condominium in New York's
exclusive Trump Tower.
   If convicted, the Taggarts each could be sentenced to 25 years in
prison and face fines totaling more than $1 million.
   Bakker and Dortch are scheduled to go on trial in Charlotte on
Aug. 28 on 24 counts of wire and mail fraud and conspiracy.
</TEXT>
