<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Shepard     07-17 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shepard,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>First American in Space Opposes Joint Soviet Missions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rocket Scientists, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should pursue travel to
other planets rather than joint space ventures with the Soviet
Union, Alan Shepard, the first American in space, said Monday.
   Shepard, one of 12 Americans to walk on the moon, disagreed with
Apollo 11 moonwalker Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin, who said Saturday during
a trip to Huntsville that America should pursue joint missions with
the Soviet Union and possibly Japan.
   Shepard on Monday visited the Space and Rocket Center, a tourist
attraction, for festivities celebrating the 20th anniversary of
America's moon landing.
   Speaking from what he described as an engineering perspective
rather than a political one, Shepard said: ``I would rather see us
develop the technology to have planetary travel _ manned and
unmanned. I think our space technology level, in general, is ahead
of the Soviets.''
   He said the United States should find things other than
technology to share with the Soviet Union.
   Shepard rode a Huntsville-built Redstone rocket into space on May
5, 1961, as the American space program rushed to catch the Soviets.
   After recovering from an inner ear disorder that temporarily
grounded him, Shepard returned to space in February 1971 on Apollo
14 and became the fifth man to walk on the moon.
   Shepard said his first trip, though brief, remains his favorite.
   Pointing to a model of the Redstone rocket at the Space and
Rocket Center, he said, ``From the standpoint of pure gut
excitement, obviously riding that baby for the first time had to
take the prize.''
   Turning to his moon trip, Shepard said his famous swing at a golf
ball on the moon's surface was not spontaneous, as the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration made it appear at the time.
   ``We practiced in the suit. We worked out all the safety
aspects,'' he said.
   Now 65, Shepard lives in Houston, where he is a commercial real
estate developer.
</TEXT>
