<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignAid     07-17 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Aid,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippine Aid Increased by Subcommittee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee Monday evening approved a
$14.4 billion spending bill for military, economic and development
aid to foreign countries after boosting money for a ``mini-Marshall
plan'' for the Philippines.
   The Appropriations Committee's foreign operations panel added $30
million to the Philippines aid program, called the Multilateral
Assistance Initiative, bringing the total proposed U.S. share to
$160 million for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   But that total still was $40 million below the amount Secretary
of State James A. Baker III pledged for the program at a recent
Tokyo meeting with other nations participating in the development
effort.
   In another concession to the Bush administration, subcommittee
chairman Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., shifted $128 million from a
variety of development programs to military aid grants. But the
resulting total of $4.6 billion for military aid still fell well
below Bush's request of $5 billion.
   The measure also was altered to earmark $15 million to pay for a
package of incentives Bush announced last week in Budapest to
encourage economic and political reforms in Hungary.
   ``I think we have made a considerable amount of progress,'' said
Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., who got into an argument with Obey
when the panel met last week and broke up without acting on the bill.
   As usual, Israel and Egypt get the lion's share of U.S. aid as a
continuing reward for their agreement to the Camp David peace
process. Israel would get about $3 billion in military and economic
aid, Egypt about $2 billion.
   Money for the Export-Import bank, which subsidizes overseas sales
of big-ticket items like airplanes for U.S. manufacturers, was cut
by $60 million to $615 million.
   The bill must be approved by the full committe before action by
the House.
</TEXT>
