<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ElectionProbe     07-17 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Election Probe,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Graddick Aides Plead To Reduced Charge, One Says Graddick Approved
Bugging</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two aides to a former state attorney
general pleaded guilty Monday to charges stemming from his 1986
gubernatorial battle, with one saying the candidate approved the use
of state equipment to spy on political foes.
   Andy Yeomans, who admitted to a misdemeanor charge of aiding in
the use of state-owned property for political purposes, said former
state Attorney General Charlie Graddick endorsed electronic
surveillance at state Democratic Party headquarters and at a
telephone bank run by Graddick's opponent in the 1986 Democratic
runoff, then-Lt. Gov. Bill Baxley.
   Yeomans' co-defendant, Don Bekurs, pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor charge of misapplying state property. Bekurs was accused
of taking eavesdropping equipment from the attorney general's
office, while Yeomans was accused of implementing the bugging.
   Graddick, an investment banker who is considering a return to the
political arena in 1990, did not immediately return telephone calls
seeking comment Monday. He previously has denied wrongdoing in his
campaign.
   District Attorney Jimmy Evans declined comment on whether charges
were being considered against Graddick, who reportedly is thinking
about a campaign for lieutenant governor or attorney general.
   Yeomans and Bekurs, a former assistant to Graddick, had been
scheduled to go on trial Monday on felony theft charges stemming
from the use of the state-owned bugging equipment.
   Yeomans reached a plea-bargain agreement with prosecutors before
the trial began, and Bekurs' plea to the reduced charge came after a
jury was seated.
   Yeomans told reporters after his guilty plea that Graddick
approved of using state-owned electronic bugging equipment at
Democratic Party headquarters and at a telephone bank operated by a
firm he said was working for Baxley.
   Yeomans said workers at the phone bank called people and asked
them such questions as whether they knew certain candidates were
endorsed by the Ku Klux Klan, but they never mentioned Baxley.
   Baxley, a Birmingham attorney, acknowledged having a phone bank
during the race but denied any political trickery.
   ``The Graddick folks are the ones who did all that kind of
stuff,'' said Baxley.
   Yeomans said that although Graddick never listened to any of the
tapes made in the bugging operations, aides kept him informed about
what was overheard.
   The battle between Baxley and Graddick helped spell victory for
Republican Guy Hunt, who trounced Baxley in the general election to
become Alabama's first GOP governor since Reconstruction.
   Yeomans, a private detective in Birmingham, faces a maximum
penalty of six months in jail and a $500 fine. However, his
attorney, David Cromwell Johnson of Birmingham, said prosecutors
would recommend only a $50 fine.
   Bekurs could be sentenced to one year in jail and fined $2,000,
but there was no word on a possible sentence to be recommended by
Evans' office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
