<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0749 07-17 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Injunction Barring Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf, ``I feel...'' to delete extraneous 1st name.
Pickup 5th pvs: Her lawyer...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VAL D'OR, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Quebec Superior Court judge on Monday
upheld an injunction won by a pregnant woman's ex-boyfriend
preventing her from having an abortion.
   ``A conceived child that is not yet born is a human being under
Article 1 of the Quebec Charter of Rights and Freedoms,'' and has
the right to life guaranteed every person, said Justice Jacques
Viens.
   He said the mother, Chantal Daigle, faced a difficult and painful
problem, but that the court had to rule in favor of the fetus.
   ``I feel like a victim,'' said Ms. Daigle, 21. ``I still have
hope and it is still my choice. ... I have more rights than a
20-week-old fetus.''
   Her lawyer planned to appeal the ruling Wednesday. Ms. Daigle
told reporters outside the courthouse that she will wait until the
appeal is heard before taking action on the abortion.
   Ms. Daigle's ex-boyfriend, Jean-Guy Tremblay, 25, hugged his
lawyer and anti-abortionists who had come to the courthouse to hear
the judgment.
   ``I intend to raise the child but with her,'' said Tremblay, who
won the injunction in the superior court July 7.
   Henri Kelada, a lawyer representing Tremblay, said the ruling
will have ``an impact on doctors giving abortions, and women will be
more cautious about getting pregnant.''
   Ms. Daigle's lawyer, Daniel Bedard, said the ruling, if not
overturned on appeal, will mean that anyone can intervene on behalf
of the fetus and say that it has rights.
   ``This means no more abortions and means women will have to be
silent,'' he said.
   Bedard had argued that the judge's job is to ``apply the law, not
create it.'' He said the injunction should be quashed since there is
no law to base it on.
   The Supreme Court of Canada last year struck down the country's
abortion law, which permitted abortions under certain conditions.
Canada now has now criminal law governing abortion.
   The case is the third of its kind this month to grab headlines
and re-ignite the abortion debate in Canada.
   In Toronto last week, Barbara Dodd had an abortion hours after
the Ontario Supreme Court quashed an injunction obtained by her
ex-boyfriend, Greg Murphy. In Winnipeg, a 20-year-old single mother
had an abortion shortly after a July 6 court decision struck down an
injunction obtained by the woman's ex-boyfriend.
</TEXT>
