<FIRST>u a AM-CannibalismExpedition 1stLd-Writethru a0669 07-17 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibalism Expedition, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0669,0820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dig Begins for Bones of Packer's Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to include details of Monday's work; picks
up 15th graf, ```From the ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd is cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LKCX2,LXCX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists using radar mapping Monday
found subtle signs of underground disturbances that could be the
century-old remains of the victims of admitted cannibal Alferd
Packer.
   ``We don't have for you the knife in the bone, but we have subtle
indications that we are in the right place,'' said James Starrs, a
George Washington University law professor heading the expedition.
   As residents and reporters watched, 13 archaelogists and other
scientists looked for clues to determine how the five gold seekers
died during the bitter winter of 1874 and whether their remains were
consumed by Packer.
   The search concentrated on a 50-by-50 foot section of Deadman's
Gulch where it is believed the bodies of the five men were buried.
The equipment detects rocks, depressions and other anomalies by
shooting radar beams underground.
   Starrs said a ``rather demonstrable blip'' was detected near the
suspected graves.
   ``It's subtle, but after years of looking at this type of data, I
feel confident there has been some disturbance in the area,'' said
engineer Stan Smith, who conducted the radar mapping.
   The scientists plan to begin digging Tuesday in areas singled out
through radar mapping.
   Starrs is 90 percent sure that the bones of the victims lie
beneath a boulder roughly marking the gravesite in the gulch, which
lies between Cannibalism Plateau and Round Top Mountain about 2
miles south of Lake City.
   A grave marker honors the five men ``who were murdered on this
spot early in the year 1874 while pioneering for mineral resources
of the San Juan country.''
   Packer, a harness maker from Utah, led the party of five into the
San Juan Mountains in search for gold. He told authorities in April
1874 that Shannon Bell, a member of his party, killed the others
with a hatchet while Packer was away from camp, looking for an
escape route from the mountains.
   Packer said he killed Bell in self defense and that he was forced
to eat the remains of the other victims to survive.
   Packer escaped from custody, but was captured in 1883 in
Cheyenne, Wyo. He was convicted of killing one of the prospectors,
but that sentence was overturned by the Colorado Supreme Court.
   He was retried for all five murders, convicted of manslaughter
and sentenced to 40 years in prison. He was paroled in 1901 and died
April 24, 1907.
   In the years to follow, Packer's admitted cannibalism provided
plenty of joke fodder and made him a bizarre folk-hero in Colorado
and the United States.
   Although Starrs is confident the group will locate the bones,
Walter Birkby, curator of physical anthropology at the Arizona State
Museum in Tucson who is on the dig, said he was unsure whether there
were any bones to find.
   The dig differs from usual practices of archaeologists, who tend
to be secretive about the location and progress of their research.
However, Starrs said his goal to raise $10,000 to fund the
expedition has not been reached, so he and his assistants have
encouraged press coverage of the event.
   Starrs assembled a team of anthropologists, archaeologists and
pathologists for his expedition near Lake City, about 170 miles
southwest of Denver.
   Starrs believes the bones will be in good condition.
   ``From the bones we will be able to see bullet holes and
hatchmarks where the skinning knife might have scraped the bones.
We'll be able to tell if the victims were cannibalized, if they were
struck by a hatchet blow, if they were really near starvation,''
Starrs said.
   The group has set aside this week to search for the bones. Later
this month, its findings will be sent to the Arizona State Museum at
Tucson for analysis.
   Next month, Starrs plans to rebury the bones and restore the
gravesite. The results of the expedition are scheduled to be
released early next year.
   As the scientists worked, about two dozen residents watched while
sitting in lawn chairs with coolers packed with refreshments.
   Most were amused by the expedition and one joked that he thought
the group probably would unearth Elvis Presley belt buckles instead
of bones.
   One resident, Byrne Smith, said he believed that Shannon Bell,
one of the gold seekers, killed his companions and was later killed
himself by Packer.
   ``I don't disagree that Packer probably was a liar, but I'm not
sure he was literate and he might have signed a confession he
couldn't read,'' Smith said. ``It will be interesting to find out if
there is any corroborating evidence because there are so many
stories.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
