<FIRST>u a AM-SpyTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0759 07-17 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0759,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Colonel Testifies in Spy Trial of Turkish National</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `He also ...,' to CLARIFY that Roney was asked
about the conspiracy's effects.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired colonel testifying in the spy
trial of a Turkish man said Monday a U.S. soldier accused in the
case attracted attention at an Army base by buying an expensive car
for cash.
   Retired Col. Kenneth Roney's testimony came on the opening day of
the U.S. District Court trial of Huseyin Yildirim, 61, who is
accused of scheming with Army Warrant Officer James William Hall III
to provide military secrets to the Soviets and East Germans.
   Roney said then-Sgt. Hall was ``singled out'' to him at Field
Station Berlin in Germany in 1986 because he owned a $21,000 1985
Volvo 760 GLE. Roney, the base's commander, was considering buying
the car.
   Questioned about the effects of the alleged conspiracy, Roney
said he noticed toward the end of his command that there was a drop
in the amount of material coming to the Berlin listening base from
Eastern bloc sources.
   Yildirim, who worked as a civilian mechanic on an Army base in
Berlin, was identified in court documents as the man Hall identified
as his conduit of classified national defense documents to East
German agents.
   Hall, in the Army since 1976, spent most of his career in Europe,
working as an analyst of intercepted radio and telephone traffic and
code messages.
   Prosecutors said Roney's testimony was important because it
showed apparent excessive spending by Hall, who made $20,000 a year.
   In opening arguments earlier in the day, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Fred Kramer talked about military tensions between the East and the
West, and said NATO forces are vastly outnumbered.
   ``What is required to equalize the balance is information,''
Kramer said after jury selection was completed. ``Intelligence in
the modern world is not James Bond stuff. It never was.''
   The trial is being held in Savannah because Hall was stationed at
nearby Fort Stewart at the time of his arrest.
   Kramer said for the first time that Hall, who was court-martialed
earlier this year, will be a government witness against Yildirim.
   In his opening argument, Yildirim's attorney, Lamar Walter, said
his client ``did not participate in this conspiracy to the extent he
should be charged.''
   ``I know some of you read spy novels. You never know what the
conclusion is until you read the last chapter,'' Walter told the
jury, adding that Hall did most of the work.
   Yildirim, who has been held in seclusion since his arrest at his
Belleair Beach, Fla., home in December, speaks little English and
was accompanied by an interpreter in the courtroom.
   Hall, 30, an intelligence analyst in the 24th Infantry Division,
was court- martialed at Fort McNair near Washington, D.C., in March,
and pleaded guilty to 10 counts of espionage, attempted espionage
and failing to obey Army regulations.
   He was sentenced to 40 years in prison, fined $50,000 and
dishonorably discharged.
   Yildirim is charged with conspiring with Hall to provide
classified information from 1983 to 1988. Hall was named as an
unindicted co-conspirator in the civilian indictment.
   Army intelligence experts said the operation funneled information
about the West's electronic eavesdropping capabilities to East
German and Soviet agents for more than six years. They said the case
appeared to have inflicted serious damage to surveillance efforts in
Europe.
   Army officials began investigating last summer after being tipped
that Hall, recently promoted from staff sergeant to warrant officer,
was living above his military salary of $20,200.
   Hall admitted to Army officials he received more than $100,000
from 1983 to 1988 to provide classified documents to Eastern bloc
agents.
</TEXT>
