<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Ultraman Adv25   07-17 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Ultraman, Adv 25,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, July 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japan's Favorite Superhero Takes on America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As much as Godzilla stomps buildings and eats
telephone wires, he'll never measure up to Ultraman, the benevolent
bug-faced alien who's spent 23 years battling bizarre monsters from
outer space.
   Noboru Tsuburaya says the time has come for audiences around the
world to see the other side of his father, Eiji Tsuburaya, the man
who created the reptillian Godzilla, Japan's most infamous movie
monster.
   That other side is Ultraman, who Tsuburaya says is still the
ultimate Japanese superhero, and the special-effect wizard's most
important legacy.
   ``Ultraman will be a much greater hit than Godzilla ever was,''
said the younger Tsuburaya, now president of the production company
that owns rights to the superhero.
   So confident is the 53-year-old Tsuburaya, that he is preparing
to set Ultraman loose in the most difficult market of all _ the
United States. A new 13-part series is to be syndicated next year by
New York-based Teletrib.
   ``America is the home of the entertainment industry, and though
Japan exports material goods, it lags behind in pop culture,'' he
said. ``Ultraman will change that pattern.''
   Rights to broadcast an old Ultraman spin-off series in North
America have been purchased by Turner Broadcasting System, and
translation of the dialogue has already been completed. Ultraman
will also be shown in the European market, primarily France, later
this year.
   And just who is this Ultraman and what is his story?
   Ultraman and other inhabitants of several planets in the M78 star
cluster have been sent to protect Earth from attack by
interplanetary intruders and Earth-born mutants, which range from
giant crayfish to fluffy snowmen.
   Many of the monsters come from Tokyo Bay, making the series a
statement against pollution and radiation, Tsuburaya said. ``The
monsters aren't all bad, but the wasteful, polluting people who
created them are.''
   Each installment ends with spectacular fights, usually in drab
industrial areas in Tokyo with lots of buildings to smash and
electric lines to break, after Ultraman transforms himself into a
130-foot, 35,000-ton giant.
   For the animated export to America, Tsuburaya has elaborated on
his father's idea, having a Stars-and-Stripes clad Ultraman enter a
special base through Abraham Lincoln's mouth in Mount Rushmore.
   Aside from the cosmetic changes, the Ultraman story is universal,
Tsuburaya said. ``He is a Japanese superhero and an international
superhero.''
   After debuting on the Tokyo Broadcasting System network in July
1966, the Ultraman series was followed by seven spinoffs, including
``Ultra Seven,'' ``Ultraman Returns'' and the animated ``Ultraman
80,'' which went off the air in 1981. The network still airs weekly
reruns.
   Over the years, Ultraman and his ultrarelatives have done battle
with more than 600 monsters, including Godzilla.
   ``But the TV producers had to promise to change the monster's
name and design to get permission to use the Godzilla suit from the
movie studio which owns his rights,'' Tsuburaya said. Ultraman, of
course, won the fight.
   Like Superman's problem with kryptonite, Ultraman has a weakness:
as a giant he burns up energy at an incredible pace and can only
remain ultrasized for three minutes at a time.
   Myojo Foods used that shortcoming in TV ads starring Ultraman to
promote its three-minute instant noodles. The superhero has also
endorsed a bank and publicized a booklet on national defense.
   Tsuburuya says sales of Ultraman products, including diapers,
chopsticks, golf bags and cigarette lighters, have quadrupled over
the last three years.
   ``Sales of Ultraman goods alone annually bring in revenues in the
1 billion yen ($7.6 million) range,'' he said. ``If he's a hit in
America, that could easily increase by one digit.''
   In March, Ultraman starred in three Tokyo Broadcasting System
television specials _ a movie, a prime-time dramatization of how he
was created and a the-making-of-Ultraman documentary.
   Tsuburaya has other big plans for Ultraman.
   He envisions a theme park where a 330-foot Ultraman will beam his
smile _ and cable TV signals _ over the surrounding countryside.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues July 25</NOTE>
