<FIRST>a w AM-NewstoUse Adv19   07-17 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-News to Use, Adv 19,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, July 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vacation: Times for Fun and Crime Lookout, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's summer and Americans are on the road
enjoying new places. And burglars are out searching for the vacant
houses left behind.
   For many people the perception of a burglar is someone breaking
into a home in the dark of night, but that isn't always the case,
the FBI reports.
   More home burglaries occur in the daytime than at night, and in
nearly one-fourth of the cases the crook simply gets in through an
unlocked door or window, the FBI has found.
   Many cases are simply crimes of opportunity, with people knocking
on doors and, if there is no answer, trying the door. If it opens
they go in and help themselves, police explain. If the door is
locked, they go on to the next house.
   That means a simple thing like making sure the door is kept
locked can prevent a burglary, certainly a cost-effective measure if
ever there was one.
   Of course, that means all doors, not just the front door. Make
sure there are locks on windows and attic, basement and garage
doors, too.
   If you are unsure about where your home may be vulverable, check
your local police department _ many departments will conduct free or
low-cost home security audits and make suggestions for improvement.
   One of the things they stress is to never leave keys available
outside the home.
   Once upon a time people left keys in mailboxes or under doormats
with little fear, but no more. Today thieves know all the obvious
places to look and check them out quickly.
   The Insurance Information Institute, which is interested in crime
because its members wind up paying for many of the losses, suggests
making the home look lived-in while you are away.
   For example, ask neighbors to collect mail and newspapers and
have someone mow the lawn.
   In addition, get automatic timers for the lights and set them to
turn lights on and off in different rooms at different times to make
it look like someone is home.
   A telephone answering machine can be a good idea, too. That way
thieves aren't tipped off by an unanswered ringing phone. Turn off
automatic garage door openers while away.
   The insurance group urges putting ladders away and says to be
sure not to advertise your vacation in the newspaper society columns.
   Valuables should be locked in a safe or safety deposit box. The
costly items should be inventoried with photos for use in making
insurance claims and identifying the items in the event of theft.
   Electronic equipment is among the most popular with crooks, so
make a mark on it to identify it later. For example, many people
engrave their Social Security number on a metal part of the product.
Electric engraving tools can be rented or borrowed from many police
departments or purchased at a reasonable price.
   Finally, when coming home from vacation check the house before
going in. If there is any sign of entry, go to a neighbor's house
and call the police _ the last thing you want to do is walk in on a
burglar in the act.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs July 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--TheKochYears Adv30-1stAdd   07-17 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--The Koch Years, Adv 30-1st Add,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: house prisoners.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With all the police and all the arrests, New Yorkers still name
drug abuse and crime as the city's greatest problems. ``It would not
be fair to lay the total responsibility on the mayor and the Police
Department,'' Reppetto says. Still, ``The question is, could they
have responded in a better way?''
   At a minimum, Koch's response is true to form: Hiring more
employees to address problems has been his consistent practice, says
Charles Brecher, research director for the Citizens Budget
Commission, another independent watchdog group.
   The city's budget has grown from $13.6 billion the year before
Koch took office to $25 billion now, and most of it goes for
compensation, Brecher says. City employment has risen from 195,176
to 231,982.
   Brecher says such wide-scale hiring has serious flaws. ``There
has been a tendency to associate more workers with better services,
and that has not proven to be the case,'' he says. ``Delivery of
services has not improved in proportion to the amount of money put
into them.''
   The problem, Brecher says, is that Koch's approach shifts the
focus off productivity and innovation. ``You have to give him good
marks for keeping the budget balanced,'' he says. ``But less good
marks for spending the money wisely.''
   City spending under Koch has been funded largely by dint of a
steady economic upswing. Property values have soared and real estate
development, particularly in midtown Manhattan, has boomed, in part
with the help of city-supplied tax benefits.
   One result has been a drastic cut in so-called ``single-room
occupancy'' hotels _ the cheap and dreary tenements that housed the
poorest of the poor. ``The city has lost 70,000 SRO units in the
last 12 years,'' says Robert Hayes, counsel to the Coalition for the
Homeless, an advocacy group. ``That is a gaping hole that hasn't
been filled.''
   Today, the coalition estimates, 70,000 to 90,000 people are
homeless in the city. When polls ask about New York's greatest
problem, homelessness invariably is the third most-cited issue,
after drugs and crime.
   ``There are many, many people of great affluence who are
suffering great spiritual angst as they step over prone bodies
literally on the streets,'' Hayes says. ``Homelessness, apart from
the tragedy for homeless people, is sapping vitality from the entire
city.
   ``It's demoralizing..It raises questions that are very
fundamental about our ability as a society and a government to deal
with problems. It's not that in 1977 there were no problems. But the
visibility of homelessness as a chronic assault on our
self-confidence did not exist.''
   The city faces other pressing problems that did not exist, or
were not so severe, at the dawn of the Koch administration. Acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, with its enormous demands on the health
care system, was unknown. The bridges and highways were not
crumbling so badly; racial tensions were not so great; the public
education system had not deteriorated so badly.
   Now polls put Koch _ after overwhelming re-election victories in
1981 and 1985 _ as the underdog in this year's contest. As he
campaigns, Koch points to a list of programs he has initiated to
address the city's problems, and he argues that his experience never
was so needed as now.
   His opponents promote their own initiatives, from appointing a
drug czar to building schools with billions in bonds. But when it
comes to the voting, first in the Sept. 12 primary, the decision
will reach to the past as well as the future, comprising a judgment
on the words Koch spoke in January 1978.
   ``We are the trustees of a national treasure _ the city of New
York itself,'' the new mayor said. ``History will hold us
accountable for how well we live up to that trust. We must not let
this city dwindle and diminish. We must not fail.
   ``The mistakes of the past are past. We have been tested and the
testing will continue. But we have survived. And soon we will begin
to flourish.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
