<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Accidental Tourist'' (Warner Home Video. VHS, $89.98. Rated
PG)
   
   ``The Accidental Tourist'' was a lumbering exercise on the large
screen, and becomes even more narcoleptic on the small screen at
home.
   It was one of the year's most overrated movies with one of the
year's most overrated performances, namely that of Geena Davis who
won an Academy Award as supporting actress for her portrayal of a
free-spirited dog trainer.
   Based on the acclaimed novel by Pulitzer Prize-winner Anne Tyler,
the movie illuminates the world of a finicky travel writer named
Macon Leary (William Hurt) who is thrown into a tailspin when his
wife (Kathleen Turner) leaves him.
   He takes his dog to a rather bizarre trainer, Muriel (Davis), who
does more than merely mold the pooch. Macon's reluctant and
accidental romance with Muriel forms the meat of this very spare
tale.
   Tyler's novel was a sophisticated and bittersweet romp,
interspersed with travel notes from all over. What's translated to
film, however, is a studied, boorish examination of unglued people
that takes far too long to say nothing. And yes, there are travel
notes from all over and they just might be the most interesting
thing about the film.
   Hurt speaks like he has marbles in his mouth and looks like he
really wishes he were someplace else. Davis speaks like her jaw's
been wired shut; her dialogue comes out as clipped, chirpy phrases.
There is nothing special about her performance. If anything, it's
grating.
   Tyler took the reader on an excursion of sorts, through family
relations, through introspection, through the human comedy of
living. Too bad the tale went through the Hollywood Cusinart and
turned into a Slushy.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
   

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' (Virgin Vision. English subtitles. VHS-Beta,
$79.95. Unrated)
   
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' is a heartrending look at the homeless street
children of Bombay, India. But its meanings and nuances transcend
that exotic locale.
   The film, which won a number of international film awards in
1988, is a riveting portrayal of how 20th century societies,
including so-called civilized ones, are devouring their young,
alternately selling them, or selling them short.
   Producer-director Mira Nair traveled the streets of Bombay,
fascinated by the resilience of the thousands of children who
survive by their wits in a squalid world of dirt, drugs and
prostitution. She decided to tell their story, not with actors, but
with children she gathered from those very backstreets.
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' is the story of 10-year-old Krishna. Abandoned
first by his mother, then by the traveling circus he joins, he
travels to Bombay hoping to earn 500 rupees to take back to his
mother.
   Krishna acquires street wisdom and a toughness that even leads to
a murder. But somehow, almost miraculously, he keeps a child-like
empathy even as he is failing in his own hopes. He befriends a
desperate drug addict, and comforts an abject 16-year-old sold by
her own mother to a brothel.
   The film's producers decided to use proceeds to establish
learning centers for the street children of Bombay and Delhi.
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' is not rated. It has no objectionable language
or sexual encounters, but the themes of street life are nonetheless
unvarnished.
   It is a truly exceptional film.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
