<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   07-17 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Images'' (O.M. Records) _ Georganne Cassat, harp.
   
   Like some of the larger planets in our solar system, Marcel
Tournier's Images for harp are heavy in atmosphere. The music covers
the gamut of harp effects. These short pieces sound a little like
Debussy piano etudes, though less complex. They were unquestionably
written by a harpist _ the liner notes call Tournier one of the most
important harpists and harp composers of the 19th and 20th centuries
_ and a judicious one at that. We can be thankful he doesn't indulge
in too many of those sweeping runs such as the kind used as a
backdrop for movie flashbacks.
   These pieces, presented here as a whole for the first time, are
fairly simple and pleasant to listen to. They have quaint titles
such as ``Moonlight in a Pool,'' replete with rippling run effects,
and ``Children by the Christmas Crib,'' which nicely evokes the
choir sound of a Christmas carol.
   Cassat is an accomplished harpist who more often than not avoids
the sometimes annoying over-plucked quality of solo harp
performances. She has an excellent sense of dynamics, offering a
constant interplay of soft and loud passages.
   Her brief biography oddly points out that she has ``brought the
music of the harp to some of the leading Royal Houses in Europe and
the Orient.'' Has royalty traditionally been deprived of harp music?
And do those kings and queens feel properly grateful? Maybe playing
this disc can make our living rooms feel a bit more regal. It
certainly lends a little atmosphere.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Cycles'' (Capitol) _ The Doobie Brothers
   
   Give one of the world's most popular bands six years off, and
it's amazing how many fresh ideas they'll come up with _ hardly any.
   If that's a revelation, it's the only one shed by ``Cycles,'' the
Doobie Brothers' first album since 1983, and their first studio
album since 1980.
   Five of the six Doobies who reunited for ``Cycles'' were with the
band when they first hit the Top 40 in the early 1970s, and much of
the music here sounds like the Doobies of that period. That means
boogie guitars, tight harmonies and plenty of percussion.
   The music is professionally played, but the formula is too
familiar to generate much excitement. And most of the material _
especially the feeble first single, ``The Doctor'' _ fails to match
the Doobies' best songs of the past.
   Still, there are moments of merit. Guitarist Tom Johnston's
``Wrong Number,'' an anti-cocaine song, has a stirring lyric. ``I
Can Read Your Mind'' offers a lovely vocal counterpoint by Patrick
Simmons and could have been an outtake from ``Minute by Minute,''
perhaps the band's best album.
   But ``Cycles'' sounds used rather than new. The guitar riff from
the Doobies' chestnut ``China Grove'' kicks off ``The Doctor''; the
riff that opens the oldie ``Listen to the Music'' begins ``Need a
Little Taste of Love.'' Maybe this album should've been called
``Recycles.''
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
