<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-17 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0943</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Paramount Communications Inc. appeals a
judge's decision allowing Time Inc. to proceed with a $14 billion
tender offer for Warner Communications Inc., lawyers and corporate
executives have begun studying the opinion to see how it might
affect transactions between other firms.
   Friday's decision by Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T.
Allen disputed the claim by Paramount _ which is trying to buy Time
in a $12.2 billion hostile tender offer _ that Time directors put
the company up for sale when they agreed to a friendly stock-swap
merger with Warner last March.
   The Delaware Supreme Court later agreed to hear the case. If
Paramount loses there it will pave the way for Time and Warner to
merge, forming Time Warner Inc., the world's largest communications
concern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's seven richest industrial nations called
for ``decisive action'' to fight global pollution as they completed
a harmonious economic summit that will be remembered more for
bicentennial fireworks than concrete achievements.
   There was so little disagreement that the leaders had time to
discuss an unexpected letter from Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev
and still wrap up ahead of time Sunday
   The closing communique addressed a number of initiatives of
President Bush, including aid to the communist East bloc,
endorsement of the administration's Third World debt plan and a call
for greater efforts to clean up the environment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, trying to knock down the last
hurdles to its new Third World debt strategy, has promised to
arrange as much as $2 billion in loans for financially strapped
Mexico, officials said.
   French President Francois Mitterrand said Friday that Mexico,
burdened by a whopping $100 billion in foreign debt, urgently needs
help.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices fell in June for the first
time in 18 months while retail sales recorded the first back-to-back
monthly declines since the 1987 stock market plunge, the government
said.
   Prices one stop short of retail, as measured by the Labor
Department's Producer Price Index, dropped 0.1 percent in June,
driven down by tumbling energy and food costs, the government said
Friday. It was the first decline since December 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June, dragged
down by falling auto and home furnishing purchases, the government
reported. Analysts said big-ticket items would continue to bear the
brunt of the anti-inflation fight.
   The Commerce Department reported Friday that sales fell to a
seasonally adjusted $140.8 billion last month after dropping 0.1
percent in May. It was the first back-to-back monthly decline since
1987 when sales declined 0.8 percent in September and 0.9 percent in
October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the factory operating rate and industrial
production fell last month, providing more evidence of a slowing
economy caused by anti-inflation measures.
   The Federal Reserve said Friday the June operating rate declined
to 83.5 percent, a 0.3 percentage point drop from May. The rate was
84.1 percent in April and hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent in
December.
   The Fed also said industrial production was off 0.2 percent last
month, with its industrial production index standing at 141.1
percent of its 1977 base, down from May's 141.4 percent. It was the
first decline since it fell 0.2 percent in February, which had been
the first drop in a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi plans to renew
its court battle to recover losses stemming from a Chicago Board of
Trade order forcing soybean traders to liquidate large positions in
the market.
   Raul Gardini, chairman of Ferruzzi Finanzaria SpA, reiterated
Friday in Milan that his company's accumulation of futures contracts
to take delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans was legal.
   A Feruzzi spokesman said a lawsuit probably would be filed in
Chicago, but did not provide a timetable. The company also indicated
it might seek compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage
to its reputation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fixed-rate mortgages dropped to the lowest
point in more than two years last week and the Veterans Affairs
Department lowered the interest rate cap for VA-backed mortgages to
9.5 percent.
   Fixed-rate, 30-year mortgages averaged 9.82 percent last week,
down from 10.03 percent the previous week, according to the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp., known as Freddie Mac.
   The government-created company, which finances the housing market
by purchasing mortgages, said it was the lowest weekly average since
the week ending April 10, 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing financial disarray in Massachusetts'
government, a major bond rating agency cut the state's credit rating
for the second time this year, a move that could add millions to
borrowing costs.
   The decision Friday by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. to downgrade
Massachusetts bonds from AA- to A represents a harsh assessment of
the fiscal policies of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis and the state
Legislature.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran its July record to nine gains in nine
sessions with an afternoon advance Friday. The Dow Jones industrials
average rose 16.50 to a new post-crash high of 2,554.82, extending
its gain for the week to 66.96 points.
   The dollar gained ground against all major currencies except the
Canadian dollar.
   Bond prices fell.
   Gold futures prices tumbled more than $6 an ounce; orange juice
futures plunged; grains and soybeans were higher; energy futures
were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
