<DOCNO> AP890717-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 0756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Olivetti-AT&amp;T     07-17 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivetti-AT&amp;T,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T To Exchange Stake In Olivetti For Share Of Holding Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. says it
will end its six-year partnership in Italian computer maker Ing. C.
Olivetti and Co. in exchange for a stake in Olivetti's parent
company.
   AT&amp;T said it agreed to swap its 22.2 percent stake in Olivetti
for a more liquid 18.6 percent interest in Compagnie Industriali
Riunite SpA, or CIR, a key holding company of Italian financier
Carlo De Benedetti.
   The swap amounts to exchanging a $735 million Olivetti stake for
a $635 million CIR holding, based on current share prices, the
telecommunications company said. Executives said that probably
little or no cash would change hands.
   The complex financial transaction was announced Saturday at a
joint news conference here by De Benedetti, chairman of both CIR and
Olivetti, and Robert Allen, chairman of AT&amp;T.
   The deal signals a first-ever diversification for AT&amp;T outside
the high-technology industry. In addition to its stake in Olivetti,
CIR has major interests in financial services, publishing,
mechanical engineering and auto parts.
   As a result of the transaction, CIR will consolidate its control
of Olivetti by raising its stake to 40 percent, and, following a
number of capital increases, will raise as much as 2.65 trillion
lire, or the equivalent of $1.9 billion, in fresh funds for De
Benedetti's financial empire.
   One of the planned capital increases will be arranged by
Olivetti, which hopes to raise the equivalent of $900 million in
support of its expansion plans.
   The two executives admitted that the original 1983 AT&amp;T-Olivetti
relationship, which combined an original 25 percent stake by AT&amp;T in
Olivetti with a wide-ranging technological and commercial agreement,
hadn't lived up to expectations. AT&amp;T said it paid about $260
million for its original stake.
   Under the 1983 accord, AT&amp;T bought Olivetti personal computers
for resale under it own name in the United States, but these sales
have seriously slumped over the past few years.
   Allen told the news conference that the alliance with CIR gives
AT&amp;T ``a sizeable investment in a broad base of European buinesses.''
   He declined to comment on whether this diversification by AT&amp;T
outside the high tech field would be followed by similar moves.
   Both executives said the upgrading of AT&amp;T's financial alliance
with Olivetti to the level of the holding company wouldn't alter the
commercial relationship between the two groups.
   They said that Olivetti will continue to supply AT&amp;T with
personal computers for sale in the United States even though AT&amp;T
agreed earlier last week to jointly develop personal computers with
Intel Corp.
   Likewise, Olivetti will continue to sell AT&amp;T minicomputers in
Europe and is expected to sell AT&amp;T's Starlan local area network.
   De Benedetti said the restructuring of the alliance with AT&amp;T
doesn't mean Olivetti is looking for another partner. He denied
recent newspaper reports that Olivetti was negotiating a partnership
with a European computer company.
   AT&amp;T will be represented on CIR's board with three seats,
including one reserved for Allen. The alliance will last for at
least five years.
   The De Benedetti holding company has assets throughout Europe
valued at about $4.69 billion. It had a profit of $280 million last
year.
   The 40-percent Olivetti shareholding is CIR's single largest
investment, accounting for about 30 percent of its total holdings.
Financial investments represent about 15 percent of its invesments,
publishing about 14 percent, auto parts 12 percent and mechanical
engineering 3 percent.
</TEXT>
