<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened sharply
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Weather was the dominant feature in the market, particularly a
National Weather Service forecast released after the close of
trading Friday that called for above-average precipitation and
below-average temperatures for the next 6-10 days.
   The July soybeans contract, at the center of last week's storm
over a possible attempt to corner the market, was 16{ cents lower.
   But weather clearly was at center stage this morning, as
evidenced by the fact that new crop soybeans were bid even lower
than the old crop contracts, and corn was falling the daily trading
limit lower across the board.
   On the open, wheat was 4 cents to 5 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.91 a bushel; corn was 6 cents to
a limit-down 10 cents lower, with July at $2.50 a bushel; oats were
9 cents to 10 cents lower, with September at $1.49 a bushel; and
soybeans were 17{ cents to 29{ cents lower, with July at $6.86 a
bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .70 cent higher, with August at
72.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .63 cent
higher, with August at 83.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .1 cent
to .5 cent higher, with July at 47.70 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .2 cent to .85 cent lower, with July at 29.15 cents a
pound.
