<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MutedAdvertising Bjt   07-17 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Muted Advertising, Bjt,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mute Button: Another Weapon Against Advertising?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of worrying about ``zappers'' who use
remote controls to make rapid-fire channel switches during
commercials, television advertisers are facing another weapon: the
muting button.
   Some advertisers sound off against prospective muters, or deny
that they exist, but som industry observers claim the muting threat
is having an impact on the modern commercial.
   ``You can see how much more entertaining commercials are now.
That I feel is an indication that they are quite concerned, that
they can't just present the product,'' said Camille Elebash, an
advertising professor at the University of Alabama in Tuscaloosa.
   ``My guess is that the button has had a modest effect, no doubt
about it. It's one of the factors influencing the reformatting of
commercials, making commercials look more like rock videos,
sportscasts or newscasts,'' said Everette Dennis, executive director
of the Gannett Center for Media Studies at Columbia University.
   Bobby Calder, a professor of marketing and psychology at
Northwestern University's Kellogg School of Management called the
mute button's impact obvious.
   ``The traditional way (of advertising) is to very early on get
attention, identify the product, but that may be precisely the kind
of activity that signals people to turn off the sound,'' he said.
   Advertisers can fight back, says Calder, with the same tactics
they use against zapping, such as building interest slowly, telling
some kind of story, or creating a commercial so cute that viewers
just want to watch it.
   Anheuser-Busch Cos. made such an attempt during this year's Super
Bowl, with a series of commercials featuring a game between teams of
animated beer bottles labeled Bud and Bud Light. If sports fans
watched the last spot, they knew Bud eked out a last-minute victory.
   One recent campaign for Goodyear had no spoken words at all. Made
by Hill, Holliday, Connors &amp; Cosmopoulos Inc., the commercials
flashed a series of images and questions, such as ``Are you ready
for a change?'' accompanied by a hard rock musical track.
   John F. Farrell, executive vice president and chief creative
director for Hill, Holliday, said the threat of remote control
muting had no influence on the campaign's style.
   Zenith Electronics Corp. included a mute button on the first
remote control device, introduced in the 1950s, and on every remote
control the company issued thereafter.
   One 1957 Zenith advertisment even urged consumers to ``just touch
a button to shut off the sound of long, annoying commercials while
the picture remains on the screen.''
   In 1989, an A.C. Nielsen survey showed 72 percent of a
4,000-person sample owned remote control mechanisms, compared with
29 percent of a survey group in 1985.
   Still, while zapping gained attention several years ago, many in
the advertising industry turn a deaf ear to the concept of consumer
muting.
   ``My gut tells me that its a non-issue. I just don't believe that
people do that,'' said Allen Banks, a media director for Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi DFS Advertising Inc.
   According to a 1986 survey by Television Audience Assessment, 40
percent of 3,000 day-time viewers sampled missed commercials, but
muting or changing the channels accounted for only about 5 percent.
   Other advertisers said they recognized the power of the mute
button, but were resigned to its use.
   ``While zapping is more of a boredom mechanism, muting seems to
be an issue of someone has something else to do. I think at that
point we've lost them anyway,'' said Bill Oakley, the creative
director on the Budweiser account and vice president of Darcy Masius
Benton &amp; Bowles-St. Louis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0212 </DOCNO>
