<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Computer     07-17 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computer,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCR Corp. Says Earnings Fell 2 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCR Corp. said its earnings fell 2 percent in
the second quarter, hurt by a stock-repurchase program, increased
research and development spending and the strength of the dollar.
   Net income declined to $110.4 million from $112.4 million a year
earlier. Earnings per share, boosted by the reduction in shares
through repurchases, rose 4 percent to a record $1.42 from $1.36 in
the same period last year.
   A drop in earnings per share in the first quarter had broken a
string of record quarterly earnings per share that began in the
fourth quarter of 1985.
   Second-quarter revenue totaled a record $1.53 billion, a 2
percent increase from last year's $1.50 billion. The revenue growth
occurred even though NCR's returns were hurt by the impact of the
stronger U.S. dollar against major foreign currencies, NCR Chairman
Charles Exley Jr. said.
   For six months, net income was $171.5 million, an 8 percent
decline from $186.6 million for the first half of 1989, NCR
reported. Earnings per share for the six months ended June 30 were
$2.17, down 3 percent from last year's $2.23. Revenue for the six
months was $2.778 billion, even with $2.778 billion last year.
   NCR reported buying 3.9 million shares of its common stock during
the first half of the year, leaving 6.1 million shares authorized
for future purchase in an ongoing program.
</TEXT>
