<DOCNO> AP890717-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-GE     07-17 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-GE,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE Earnings Up 16 Percent in 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co., citing increased
productivity and demand for its products, on Monday reported its
second-quarter earnings rose 16 percent on a 14 percent increase in
revenue.
   The company said its profit rose to $972 million, or $1.08 a
share, from $835 million, or 93 cents a share, in the second quarter
of 1988.
   Consolidated revenues were $13.5 billion for the quarter, up from
$11.9 billion a year ago.
   For the first six months, the company had earnings of $1.82
billion, or $2.02 a share, up 17 percent from $1.56 billion, or
$1.73 a share, a year ago.
   Consolidated revenues for the half year were $25.4 billion, up 14
percent from the $22.4 billion for the first six months of 1988.
   ``Continued strong earnings performance was spurred by GE's
second-quarter operating margin rate _ 12.1 percent _ a record for
any quarter in our history,'' said GE chairman John F. Welch Jr.
   ``This performance resulted from sustained company-wide
productivity, as well as excellent volume increases in many of our
businesses,'' he said.
   Welch cited strong sales for GE jet engines and a resurgence in
the company's electrical generating equipment as key factors in the
earnings increase.
   GE has $2.4 billion in orders for power equipment. The company
also received $4 billion worth of orders for its jet engines,
bringing its backlog to $13 billion.
   The company said its broadcasting operations posted a strong
increase in operating profit on higher revenue from its NBC
television network and improved margins.
</TEXT>
