<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wet, Cool Forecast Sends Grain and Soybean Futures Prices Skidding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed sharply
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A National Weather Service calling for above-average
precipitation and below-average temperatures for the next 6-10 days
sent the markets into a tailspin and most fell the daily trading
limit shortly after the opening bell.
   The July soybeans contract, which occupied the center of last
week's storm over what some viewed as an attempt by Italian
agribusiness giant Ferruzzi to corner the market, was 30 cents lower
at the close.
   But traders said weather clearly was at center stage, and they
noted that new crop soybeans were hit just as hard as the old crop
contracts, and that corn was down the limit and wheat sharply lower
as well.
   On the close, wheat was 7 cents to 8} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was 9 cents
to 12 cents lower, with July at $2.47} a bushel; oats were 9} cents
to 12 cents lower, with July at $1.38{ a bushel; and soybeans were
28 cents to 30 cents lower, with July at $6.73{ a bushel.
