<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TexasAir-Boeing     07-17 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Air-Boeing,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Air Reportedly Discussing Boeing Jet Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. has little choice but to pursue a
reported $2.8 billion purchase of new jets, despite the
strike-induced bankruptcy at one of its major subsidiaries, industry
analysts said Monday.
   ``An ongoing Texas Air will need to have aircraft which are
competitive with other carriers and that are able to meet any noise
standards to be imposed,'' said James Carey, an analyst at
Washington-based Airline Economics Inc.
   ``Therefore, they have to raise the capital to make this
replacement to be competitive. All airlines do.''
   Texas Air, parent company of Continental and Eastern airlines, is
one of only two major U.S. carriers which have not announced major
jet purchases within the past several months.
   The Wall Street Journal, quoting airline and aerospace industry
sources, reported Monday that the Boeing deal would involve the
purchase of 50 new 737-300s with options on 50 more with delivery
dates as early as 1991.
   Texas Air spokesman Art Kent said Monday the company has been
talking to aircraft vendors, but would not confirm the Boeing
discussions.
   ``What we've been saying all along is that we are always
reviewing our options and talking to various suppliers,'' Kent said.
   Analysts said the narrow-body planes would be used mainly by
Houston-based Continental, which completed a bankruptcy
reorganization three years ago. The airline posted losses of $718
million last year and $255 million in the first quarter of 1989.
   Eastern currently is operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy court
supervision in the wake of a machinists strike that virtually shut
down the Miami-based airline.
   Robert J. Joedicke, an advisory director on the airline industry
for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said analysts have known about the
Texas Air-Boeing discussions for some time.
   ``All they're doing is basically reserving a position for
deliveries five years down the road,'' Joedicke said. ``Prudence
would say they would have to have some aircraft on delivery by the
early 1990s.''
   ``It's something I would view more as insurance,'' Joedicke said,
adding he would be more surprised if Texas Air were not negotiating
a deal.
   Analysts said Texas Air could face a serious problem unless it
buys more planes because of expected noise limits that will restrict
the use of older jets and an average four- to five-year wait for
airplane deliveries.
   In the past, Texas Air has purchased new aircraft under a
sale-leaseback arrangement in which the parent company leases its
planes back to its subsidiaries, and analysts described that as a
likely scenario under current negotiations with Boeing.
   Boeing spokesman David Jimenez declined comment Monday on the
Texas Air talks, saying the Seattle-based company allows its
customers to announce purchases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890717-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-BAT     07-17 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-BAT,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stock Exchange to Investigate BAT Trading Before Hostile Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   London's Stock Exchange indicated Monday it will
conduct a routine investigation into trading of BAT Industries PLC
shares and options that took place before last Tuesday's hostile $21
billion bid for the British conglomerate.
   Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith, joined by British
merchant banker Jacob Rothschild and Australian entrepreneur Kerry
Packer, offered the equivalent of $13.69 a share in securities for
BAT, which quickly rejected the bid.
   ``We really don't discuss individual cases,'' said a spokeswoman
for the stock exchange, who wasn't identified in accordance with
British practice.
   But she said ``We would automatically investigate in a bid of
this size...particularly where there is unusual volume movements or
other suspicious factors that would alert our attention.''
   Prices and trading volume in both BAT shares and options surged
in the two trading sessions immediately ahead of the bid
announcement.
   The offer represents the second-biggest corporate takeover
attempt ever, trailing the $25 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.
earlier this year. BAT, the world's biggest tobacco company, also
has interests in retailing _ including the Saks Fifth Avenue and
Marshall Field's department stores in the United States _ paper
making and financial services.
   BAT shares climbed 31 cents a share in moderately active trading
last Monday, the day before the bid was announced, after advancing
29 cents the previous Friday.
   The shares rose $3.33 to close at $14.51 the day of the bid.
   On Monday, the shares finished at $14.15, up 3 cents.
   In options trading, 9,864 BAT options contracts changed hands
last Monday, representing an underlying volume of 10 million shares,
the spokeswoman confirmed. That accounted for nearly a quarter of
the options market's total volume that day. Last Tuesday, another
11,161 contracts were traded, she confirmed.
   The average daily volume in the previous week had been around
2,000 contracts, including the 4,000 contracts traded on Friday,
also an unusually active day, she stated.
   An investigation into BAT trading could take months. Even after
its conclusion, the exchange itself is unlikely to disclose the
outcome.
   ``We never officially comment,'' the spokeswoman said.
   While the stock exchange regularly engages in such probes, it is
unable to bring charges. Instead, it submits its findings to the
Department of Trade and Industry, which then decides whether or not
to prosecute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
