<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-17 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against most major currencies
except the Japanese yen in sluggish U.S. trading Monday, reversing
course after heading higher on overseas markets.
   Gold prices closed with minor changes. On the Commodity Exchange
in New York, gold bullion for current delivery rose 20 cents to $371
a troy ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of
$370.30 for an ounce of bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, down 20 cents from
Friday's late bid.
   Peter Wild, a senior currency trader at Bank Julius Baer &amp; Co.,
said a cautious mood prevailed in the foreign exchange markets with
participants reluctant to trade heavily before the U.S. merchandise
trade report for June is issued Tuesday. Volume was very light, he
said.
   The Commerce Department report on the country's merchandise trade
balance frequently influences the dollar's value and has an impact
on financial markets.
   Some economists say the dollar's strength this year could cause a
deterioration in the balance, pushing the U.S. deeper into deficit
in its trade with the rest of the world.
   Dealers on foreign markets described trading as nervous but the
volume of activity was heavier than in the United States.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 2.03 yen to a closing 141.53 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 141.95 yen. In New York, the
dollar closed at 141.43 yen, up from 140.85 Friday.
   The British pound fell to $1.6075 in London from $1.6125 late
Friday. Sterling fetched $1.6150 in New York, compared with Friday's
late level of $1.6050.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.9030 West German marks, down from 1.9125; 1.6445
Swiss francs, down from 1.6515; 6.4555 French francs, down from
6.4890; 1,380.00 Italian lire, down from 1,385.00; and, 1.19065
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1917 Canadian.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with late rates
Friday included: 1.9138 West German marks, up from 1.9030; 1.6540
Swiss francs, up from 1.6455; 6.4890 French francs, up from 6.4575;
2.1580 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1400; 1,387.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,378.50, and 1.1905 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1916.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Gold bullion was bid at $372.20 a troy ounce late Monday in
London, up from late Friday's $370.50. In Zurich, the bid was
$370.75 an ounce, unchanged from late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 61 cents to close at a bid of
$372.02 an ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid of $5.29 a troy ounce, up
from $5.25 late Friday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery closed at $5.263 a troy ounce, up from Friday's
settlement of $5.207.
</TEXT>
