<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Banks 1stLd-Writethru f0110 07-17 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0110,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Quarter Net Down At Chase, Morgan; Up At Security Pacific</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS net interest income figure for Security Pacific in
18th graf, Net interest ..., to $662.2 million sted $762.2 million.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the nation's largest bank holding companies reported
differing results Monday, with second-quarter earnings down at Chase
Manhattan Corp. and J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc. but up at Security
Pacific Corp.
   Chase, second to Citicorp in total assets, said its earnings fell
38.8 percent from mainly because of special factors that boosted
earnings in the year-earlier period.
   Third-ranked J.P. Morgan, parent of Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.,
said its earnings fell 9.8 percent, hurt by its sharply higher cost
of funds during the period.
   Fifth-ranked Security Pacific said its earnings rose 20 percent
due partly to strong growth in domestic loans.
   Bad loans to Latin America continued hampering the banks'
results. U.S. bank regulators in June required banks to charge off
20 percent of their loans to Argentina.
   New York-based Chase reported a profit of $137 million, or $1.31
a share, down from $224 million, or $2.45 a share, a year earlier.
The 1988 second quarter included an after-tax gain of $69 million
the sale of an interest in Cain Chemical Inc. and the use of $35
million in federal tax benefits.
   Net interest income in the quarter increased to $791 million from
$782 million a year earlier, largely because of interest payments by
borrowers in Brazil, partly offset by non-payment by Argentine
borrowers, Chase said. Other operating income totaled $491 million,
down from $569 million a year earlier.
   For the first six months of 1989, Chase reported a profit of $269
million, or $2.59 a share, down from $501 million, or $5.53 a share,
a year earlier. The 1988 results included $120 million in after-tax
gains from asset sales and the use of $75 million in tax benefits
plus the income from the Cain sale.
   Net interest income for the first half rose to $1.62 billion from
$1.55 billion a year earlier. Other operating income for the first
six months totaled $911 million, down from $1.20 billion a year
earlier.
   Chase's new provisions for possible credit losses totaled $150
million in the second quarter, level with a year earlier, bringing
the total new provisions in the first half to $300 million, also
level with a year earlier.
   New York-based J.P. Morgan said its second-quarter profit fell to
$206 million, or $1.09 a share, from $229 million, or $1.23 a share,
in the comparable 1988 period.
   Net interest income fell to $316 million from $383 million a year
earlier, while non-interest income rose to $485 million from $376
million a year earlier.
   Morgan said earnings for the first six months of the year
declined to $386 million, or $2.05 per share, from $510 million, or
$2.75 per share, in the comparable 1988 period.
   For the six-month period, net interest income fell to $614
million from $824 million a year earlier, while non-interest income
rose to $879 million from $811 million a year earlier.
   Morgan's total of non-performing loans rose to $1.84 billion as
of June 30 from $1.62 billion a year earlier. Of that, loans to
Brazil accounted for $1.04 billion and loans to Argentina accounted
for $473 million.
   The company made an additional provision of $35 million for
credit losses in the quarter, compared to a provision of $30 million
a year earlier, bringing the total new provisions this year to $45
million, down from $80 million a year earlier.
   For the three months ended June 30, Los Angeles-based Security
Pacific said its net income totaled a record $184.5 million, or
$1.58 a share, up from $154.3 million, or $1.36 a share, in the
year-ago period.
   Net interest income rose to $732.2 million from $662.2 million a
year earlier, while non-interest income rose to $449.7 million from
$410.7 million a year earlier.
   For the first six months of 1989, Security Pacific's earnings
rose 21 percent to $363.8 million, or $3.12 a share, from $301.5
million, or $2.66 a share, in the first half of 1988.
   Net interest income for the first six months rose to $1.47
billion from $1.29 billion a year earlier. Non-interest income rose
to $881.3 million from $831.7 million a year earlier.
   Security Pacific Chairman Richard J. Flamson III said that in
addition to domestic loan growth, the holding company benefited from
an overall increase in non-interest income and slow growth in
non-interest expense.
   Security Pacific's portfolio of non-performing loans rose to
$1.64 billion as of June 30, down from $1.74 billion a year earlier.
   The company added $111.6 million to its reserve for credit losses
in the quarter, compared to a provision of $79.3 million a year
earlier, bringing total new provisions this year to $222.9 million,
up from $157.9 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
