<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern     07-17 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Says Court Filing On Schedule Cutback Is Inaccurate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said Monday that a bankruptcy court
filing inaccurately indicated the company's August schedule would be
more than 15 percent smaller than earlier announced.
   However, a spokeswoman said, the strikebound airline was
reviewing its schedule and adjustments were possible.
   Eastern, in a federal bankruptcy court filing last week in New
York, indicated its August schedule would have 330 daily flights,
compared with the 390 it had announced previously.
   The company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization March
9, five days after Machinists, pilots and flight attendants unions
went on strike and left it at 10 percent of its pre-strike schedule
of nearly 1,100 daily flights.
   Pilots union officials said Monday the disclosure proved Eastern
could not live up to its announced efforts to rebuild without the
unions.
   But Eastern officials in Miami expressed surprise Monday at the
figure, which was included in documents requesting release of $100
million in funds held in escrow.
   ``The 330 figure is inaccurate,'' said spokeswoman Karen
Ceremsak. ``The number will be corrected.''
   Ms. Ceremsak said no cancellations had been made for the August
schedule.
   ``We're reviewing all of the schedule on a daily basis and any
adjustments are going to be minor and within a small period of time
in August,'' Ms. Ceremsak said.
   Eastern has begun reorganizing as a smaller carrier under a plan
that includes the sale of some $1.8 billion in assets to help pay
off its creditors.
   The company more than doubled its daily schedule in July to 220
flights daily and said it would be up to 390 flights daily.
   ``On Aug. 1...Eastern intends to further increase operating
levels to 330 departures a day,'' said a July 13 court application
filed by Eastern attorneys.
   Eastern unions, which support a buyout by Chicago options trader
Joseph Ritchie as an alternative to the downsizing, have argued that
Eastern doesn't have the trained personnel, particularly pilots, to
make its rebuilding plan work.
   ``We told you so. They're short pilots and they can't do it,''
said Gary Greksa, spokesman for the Eastern pilots union local, said
of the apparent schedule buyback. ``Buyer beware. They left people
stranded at the gates in March, and they'll do it again.''
   Eastern's request for $100 million also calls for $50 million
immediately, saying Eastern needs the money by the end of the month.
   Fewer than 300 of Eastern's 3,800 union pilots have come back to
work since the March 4 strike.
   Meanwhile, Eastern has hired 835 pilots, 559 of whom still are in
training. The company said 215 are flying, and 61 have flunked out
or left its round-the-clock training program.
   Eastern, which once flew into 102 cities, plans to rebuild its
schedule to 65 cities by Aug. 1 and 77 cities by the end of the
year. The August schedule requires 580 pilots for 390 daily flights.
</TEXT>
