<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru   07-17 0854</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0238,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain and Soybean Futures Continue Skid As Cool, Wet Weather in Forecasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one new graf after 14th graf pvs, Without the ... with
precious metals prices. Picks up 15th graf pvs, Heating oil ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybeans futures prices plummeted Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade as a forecast for cooler, wetter weather over the
next 10 days eased traders' fears of supply tightness through the
summer.
   On other markets, coffee was sharply lower on news that Colombia
was lifting nearly all taxes on its exports to become more
competitive in the newly deregulated marketplace; heating oil led a
modest rally in the petroleum futures complex; and cattle futures
climbed in anticipation of a government report expecting to show
fewer animals on the feedlots.
   After the close of trading Friday, the National Weather Service
released a forecast calling for above-average precipitation and
below-average temperatures over the next 6-10 days, especially in
the western cornbelt region. Corn and soybeans tumbled at the
opening bell at the BOT and most contract months for both
commodities locked down the daily trading limit.
   ``The grain prices have been carrying a substantial amount of
risk premium for fear of another drought,'' said Rich Feltes,
director of commodity research for Refco Inc., Chicago. ``But people
are coming around to the idea that we're not going to have the
persistent heat and dryness that characterized last year.''
   Traders remained split over whether last week's order by the
exchange forcing market players to liquidate large positions in July
soybeans still affected the market.
   The BOT's board of directors ordered all holders of such
contracts to reduce their positions to 3 million bushels by the
close of business Tuesday and to 1 million by Thursday, when the
contract goes off the board.
   The move was widely interpreted as an effort to prevent Italian
agribusiness giant Ferruzzi SpA from cornering the soybean market.
The company has acknowledged contracting for delivery of some 24
million bushels while slightly less than half that amount remains
accessible, but said it needs the beans for export business and to
keep its processing plants working.
   Ferruzzi lost a court fight last week to block the BOT action,
but said it intends to return to court and seek monetary damages for
losses tied to the forced liquidation.
   Those who suggested the fallout from Ferruzzi's fight with the
exchange had already been figured into prices noted that the July
contract, which has no daily trading limit, only slid 26 cents,
compared to 30 cents in the new crop months.
   They also noted that the limit-down move in corn and oats pointed
to weather as the culprit for Monday's slide.
   Wheat settled 6 cents to 11\ cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.84 a bushel; corn was 10 cents to 12 cents
lower, with July at $2.47{ a bushel; oats were 10 cents to 12 cents
lower, with July at $1.38{ a bushel; and soybeans were 26 cents to
30 cents lower, with July at $6.77{ a bushel.
   Coffee was .03 cent to 1.03 cents lower on the New York Coffee,
Sugar and Cocoa Exchange, with July at 86.85 cents a pound.
   Analysts said a trading skirmish is shaping up in the wake of a
July 3 move by the International Coffee Organization abolishing
export controls on the commodity.
   ``Without the umbrella of the ICO, there is going to be some
adjustments by the big exporters,'' said Arthur Stevenson, who
tracks the soft commodities for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
New York. ``The byword now is `market share' and you're going to see
some aggressive strategy to retain and build on it.''
   Gold settled 20 cents lower to 20 cents higher on the Comex, with
July at $371 a troy ounce; silver was 5.6 cents to 6.4 cents higher,
with July at 526.3 cents a troy ounce. Platinum was 70 cents to a
$1.30 higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange, with July at
$508.70 a troy ounce.
   Heating oil was the star performer on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. It settled .19 cent to 1.1 cents higher, with August at
50.43 cents a gallon; crude oil was 13 cents to 44 cents higher,
with August at $20.45 a barrel; and unleaded gasoline was .24 to .97
cent higher, with August at 57.08 cents a gallon.
   Some analysts said the surge may be speculation that a report
Tuesday by the American Petroleum Institute will show inventories
are lower.
   Livestock analysts were looking for bullish numbers Tuesday as
well _ these from the U.S. Department of Agriculture on how many
animals were placed on feedlots this past month.
   Live cattle were .28 cent to .97 cent higher, with August at
72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .60 cent to .92 cent higher,
with August at 83.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to
.60 cent higher, with July at 47.65 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .15 cent to .80 cent lower, with July at 29.07 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
