<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-HomeShopping     07-17 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Home Shopping,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>HSN Records Third Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Shopping Network Inc., the
nation's leading shop-by-television retailer, said Monday it lost
$5.9 million in its third fiscal quarter, and blamed legal expenses
associated with its current civil trial with GTE Corp.
   The loss for the three months ended May 31 contrasted with a
profit of $6.4 million, or 7 cents per share, for the comparable
period in 1988.
   The loss for the latest period included an extraordinary
after-tax gain of $1.8 million from the repurchase of $13 million in
long-term obligations.
   Third-quarter revenue slipped 2.4 percent to $178.7 million from
$183.2 million a year earlier.
   ``This was a disappointing quarter,'' said Roy M. Speer, HSN
chairman and CEO. ``However, electronic retailing, HSN's core
businss, remains profitable on a fundamental basis.''
   The video retailer said its earnings reflected a $9.3 million
increase in general and administrative costs in the latest quarter
over the year-ago figure, including $4.9 million in legal expenses.
   HSN and GTE went to trial June 19 in a case in which the HSN
accused the telecommunications firm of inadequate service and faulty
equipment and GTE countersuing alleging slander. The case is
expected to last six-to-eight weeks.
   HSN's nine-month earnings fell to $11.2 million, or 12 cents per
share, from $14.6 million, or 17 cents a share, last fiscal year.
   The latest results include an extraordinary after tax gain of $7
million from buying back $37.6 million in long-term obligations.
   Nine-month revenue rose 4.4 percent to $586.9 million from $562
million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
