<FIRST>u f AM-CenTrust-GreatWestern     07-17 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CenTrust-Great Western,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>CenTrust Sells 63 Branches to California Thrift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CenTrust Bank said it agreed to sell nearly all its
branches Monday to Great Western Financial Corp. of Beverly Hills
for more than $100 million.
   The Miami-based savings and loan is selling 63 of its 71 branches
and all of the accounts in those brances to Great Western Bank, a
Great Western Financial subsidiary. The branches have $2.4 billion
in deposits.
   The move comes as CenTrust seeks to restore its financial health
and alleviate concerns of federal and state banking regulators.
   CenTrust will be left with eight branches and $800 million in
deposits. The deal will give Great Western the largest branch
network in Florida.
   ``By more than doubling our retail banking presence in Florida,
this transaction will give us the largest savings branch networks in
California and Florida, the two best growth markets for retail
banking in the country,'' said James F. Montgomery, chairman of
Great Western.
   Curtis Cravelli, executive vice president of retail banking at
Great Western, said the giant thrift hasn't achieved the clout it
wants in Florida, despite acquiring more than 30 offices in the
state from other S&amp;L's.
   After the CenTrust deal, Great Western will have 114 offices in
Florida and more than $4 billion in retail deposits.
   Great Western's parent firm has assets of $36 billion. Its
capital, which is a measure of its financial health, is well above
minimum federal standards.
   For CenTrust, the move ultimately will give the S&amp;L the money it
needs to meet federal standards for net worth, the company said.
   CenTrust's asset base will drop to $6.4 billion. But its net
worth will rise to 4 percent of assets _ putting it in compliance
with federal standards.
   The $100 million proceeds will also help rid CenTrust of a
sizable chunk of its past losses that it has been carrying on the
books and writing off slowly.
   CenTrust grew from the ashes of the insolvent Dade Federal
Savings in the early 1980s. Chairman David L. Paul, in part using
investments in high-yield securities known as junk bonds, built
CenTrust into one of the nation's largest thrifts.
   It is perhaps best known for its brightly lit headquarters
building that dominates the downtown Miami skyline.
</TEXT>
